<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEXT STEPS ON IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Dec. 25:
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's reflexive rejection of a new U.N. weapons inspection plan
need not be taken as the last word. With some assistance from
France and Russia, which have an interest in limiting Iraq's
development of chemical, biological and nuclear arms, an effective
monitoring system can yet be put in place.
</P>
<P>
   Saddam Hussein would clearly prefer to have no U.N. arms
inspectors snooping around as he tries to rebuild his biological
and chemical arsenals and continues his pursuit of nuclear weapons.
He has already had more than 13 months to work on these programs
unobserved. But his ability to resist U. N. directives depends on
his success in sustaining divisions within the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the Security Council passed, by an 11-0
vote, a resolution creating a new inspection system and outlining
the steps Baghdad can take to win some relief from sanctions.
Regrettably, France, Russia and China joined Malaysia in
abstaining. But as even Paris is quick to acknowledge, the areas of
disagreement on the council have appreciably narrowed during the
eight months of diplomacy that produced this resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The council's action, despite the four abstentions, now has the
force of international law. France and Russia, both of which have
long argued for the kind of sanctions relief and other incentives
for Iraq's cooperation embodied in this resolution, should now use
their influence with Baghdad to convince Iraq to abide by its
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution requires Iraq to comply with a list of essential
remaining disarmament tasks to be drawn up by the new inspection
commission. If these are achieved, some international economic
sanctions would be suspended, and remain suspended as long as Iraq
continued to cooperate. While Baghdad's oil revenues would still be
monitored and its import of weapons and weapons-making materials
prohibited, Iraq would gain more freedom in its purchases of
civilian goods. It might also be allowed to repair its oil pumping
and transmission facilities.
</P>
<P>
   To get the resolution passed, Washington had to agree to replace
the old inspection commission, known as Unscom, with a new one
likely to be more closely supervised by the Security Council. It
also had to accept the idea of suspending some sanctions before
Iraq demonstrated full compliance with all disarmament
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Those concessions are acceptable if they permit resumption of a
serious arms-control program inside Iraq. Unhindered inspections
are the best way to monitor Iraqi weapons programs. That is a point
even the abstaining members of the Security Council agree on. Their
help is now needed to convince Iraq that it must honor the new
resolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
