<HEADLINE>
WOMAN FOUND ALIVE IN CAR AFTER TWO DAYS TRAPPED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jennifer Hamm and Bhavna Mistry  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Santa Clarita woman who was trapped for two days in her
wrecked car off the side of a freeway was found alive Friday in
what many were calling a Christmas Eve miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters had to cut Jolene Donohue, 52, from the crushed
car, which had rolled down a 70-foot embankment near Sylmar, just
off the transition road from the southbound Golden State Freeway to
the eastbound Foothill Freeway. She was taken to Providence Holy
Cross Medical Center, where she was listed in serious but stable
condition Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very lucky to be found,'' said Darin Conant, Los Angeles
County Fire Department paramedic. ``What a great Christmas present
-- somebody found their mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue was last seen at 9 p.m. Wednesday when she left a
Christmas party in La Crescenta. Her son filed a missing person
report Thursday when his mother failed to come home, said Sgt.
Richard Larue of the Santa Clarita Valley sheriff's station.
</P>
<P>
   Then, while David Donohue was at the station Friday checking on
the status of the case, he got a call from his uncle saying that
his mother's car had been found.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials said that if it weren't for Stockton resident
John Teslich, 41, who had pulled off the road around 12:10 p.m.
Friday, Donohue may not have been found.
</P>
<P>
   After Teslich flagged down a delivery truck, someone called 911.
</P>
<P>
   The California Highway Patrol did not know why Donohue's car
went undetected.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue was able to tell the rescue and emergency workers she
had been there for two days but couldn't remember the sequence of
events.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe she was driving west on the Foothill Freeway
at about 65mph on her way home Wednesday night, said Sgt. Rick
Sirovy of the CHP's Newhall Office.
</P>
<P>
   For unknown reasons, Donohue crossed the dirt divider and drove
the wrong way on the freeway, Sirovy said.
</P>
<P>
   Her midsized two-door car tumbled 70 feet down an embankment and
landed on its wheels, Sirovy said. The crushed roof trapped Donohue
in the car.
</P>
<P>
   Highway patrol officials said Donohue had been wearing her seat
belt and that there is no suspicion of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't remember what happened,'' Conant said. ``But you
could see the tire marks on the roadway and in the grass and where
she had crossed the ravine.''
</P>
<P>
   When rescue crews arrived, they cut the roof off the car.
Firefighters spent 20 minutes removing the woman from the crushed
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a long-sleeved shirt made of light material and sweat
pants, Donohue was in the driver's seat of her car with her seat
belt on and was alert, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters said that temperatures may have dipped into the low
60s.
</P>
<P>
   She complained of neck and back pain but was conscious and able
to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that she had only minor injuries from the
accident,'' said Bob Collis of the Los Angeles Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   She was said to be surrounded by family members at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
