<SLUG> BC-HOPE-MEMORIES-LADN </SLUG>
 
GI's THANKFUL FOR MEMORIES OF BOB HOPE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Dennis McCarthy  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They crawled out of foxholes and walked out of jungles and
deserts to see him. Mr. Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, the kids were waiting for Santa Claus. Thousands of
miles away, in the middle of another war, their G.I. dads and older
brothers were waiting for Bob Hope.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Christmas never let them down, and they've never forgotten
him for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're 18, 5,000 miles from your loved ones at Christmas, the
mail hasn't come in two weeks, and you're so very homesick,'' Ernie
Meylan of Granada Hills says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, out of nowhere, Bob Hope shows up, and it's like a shot
in the arm, like a visit from home.''
</P>
<P>
   For Meylan, a young army private in World War II, it was a visit
on Okinawa. For Arvid Larson, it was France. For Dan Trifunovich,
it was Germany and England. For Hillard Friedman, it was Ora Bay,
New Guinea. For Grady Carmickel, Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``His show was in the evening, but all the guys started showing
up for it after lunch, just sitting there waiting,'' Carmickel
said. ``That's how much we wanted to see him, how much his visit
from home meant to the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   From early in World War II through Operation Desert Storm in
1990, Mr. Christmas went wherever American GI's serving this
country needed a shot in the arm during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   In the South Pacific, he gave one to a young Navy officer named
John Kennedy, who would one day become president of the United
States and present Hope with the Congressional Gold Medal telling
Mr. Christmas how he had sat in a torrential rainstorm for hours
with thousands of other soldiers to see his show.
</P>
<P>
   And he gave a shot in the arm to all the vets mentioned above,
and many more who spend at least part of their days now at the
Sepulveda and West Los Angeles VA facilities.
</P>
<P>
   They all wanted to say thanks again to Mr. Christmas today, to
tell him how much he meant to them back when they were young
soldiers, scared and so far from home.
</P>
<P>
   They all wanted to say a special Merry Christmas to Bob Hope.
</P>
<P>
   After her husband would return from his Christmas tours, they
would sit for hours talking about the young faces he had seen
looking back at him from the audiences, Dolores Hope said.
</P>
<P>
   It was how Mr. Christmas unwound after coming home from
somewhere in the world where America's soldiers needed a shot in
the arm during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meeting the men and making them smile was always the thing he
talked about most,'' she said. ``It gave him such satisfaction to
be able to replace the fear and loneliness on their faces with
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a few hours, he could make them forget where they were and
make them feel like they were home again.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband was sleeping now, Dolores said when we talked
Thursday. He sleeps a lot, she laughs. But, don't worry, he is
doing well for 96, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his good friend, former President Ronald Reagan, he does
not suffer from Alzheimer's, she said. They still entertain friends
and enjoy together reading the holiday cards and letters that have
come from all over the world again this year.
</P>
<P>
   I tell her there are thousands of veterans in Los Angeles who
want to wish Bob Hope a merry Christmas and thank him again for
giving up all those Christmases with his own family to spend them
with GI's somewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   She would tell Bob that, Dolores said. Thank you. He'll
appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he could, he'd do one more show for them right now,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   Now wouldn't that be a great way to wrap up the century?
</P>
<P>
   One final present to his country from Mr. Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
