<SLUG> BC-INDIA-HIJACK-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN AIRLINES JET SEIZED
</HEADLINE>
 (UPDATES, revisions thruout) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
By SUSAN SACHS  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five Sikh men said to be armed with grenades, rifles and knives
hi- jacked an Indian Airlines jet Friday and killed at least one of
the 189 people aboard, during a forced odys- sey across India,
Pakistan, Afghani- stan and the Persian Gulf before touching down
in Kandahar, Afghani- stan, Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, the militia that rules most of Afghanistan, said
their sol- diers had surrounded the plane in Kandahar, Agence
France-Presse reported. A Taliban spokesman said the militia had
nothing to do with the hijackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has been allowed out of the plane, which is surrounded
by the military vehicles,'' said the spokes- man, Abdul Hai
Mutmaen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got nothing to do with the hijackers,'' he said,
according to the French agency. ``We are con- cerned about the
safety of those ab- ducted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban reportedly refused both an Indian request for a
rescue attempt and a plea for asylum for the hijackers.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft had taken off from a military air base in the
United Arab Emirates and, low on fuel, landed in Kandahar two hours
later, at 7:33 a.m. local time Saturday. The ruling Taliban
permitted the troubled jet to land, after denying an earlier re-
quest for a night-time landing.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen comandeered the A- 300 Airbus after it took off from
Katmandu, Nepal, at 4:25 p.m. local time Friday. Over the next 15
hours, they landed on three separate occasions to refuel. During a
five- hour stop at the Al Minhad military base outside Dubai, they
released about 35 hostages, including women, children and one
injured man.
</P>
<P>
   The hijackers also brought out the body of a hostage they had
killed, an image broadcast on Dubai television.
</P>
<P>
   Two male passengers who were also released told The Associated
Press that the hijackers had killed two hostages with knives but
that no guns had been fired.
</P>
<P>
   Emirates officials, who had allowed the plane to land after
nearby Oman had refused per- mission, said the hijackers had agreed
to free some hostages after the plane had been refueled.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the hijackers, their demands and their intended
destination remained a mystery. At one point in the erratic
journey, they ordered the pilot to fly to Afghanistan but the
ruling Taliban militia refused to allow the plane to land.
</P>
<P>
   The men were confirmed as Sikhs, the BBC reported Friday night,
and both Indian and Pakistani officials said the gunmen spoke
Hindi, the official language of India and the predominant language
in the north- ern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was originally bound for New Delhi from Katmandu, the
capi- tal of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities in the emirates said negotiated for the release
of women and children without trying to hold the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will allow it to refuel and we will provide it with medical
aid and food if needed,'' Information Minister Abdullah bin Zayed
said. ``That airport is equipped with ambulances. We are not
interested in allowing them to stay for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines officials said Flight IC 814, which left Katmandu at
4:25 p.m. local time, 5:55 a.m. Eastern time, had a crew of 11 and
178 passengers on board.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, however, had conflicting reports on passengers'
nationalities. At least 154 were reported to be Indian and eight
Nepalese. Officials told Reuters that other passengers included
four Swiss, four Spaniards, a Japanese, a Canadian and a Belgian.
The nationalities of the other five passengers were not known.
</P>
<P>
   The flight, which is usually a one-hour trip, was seized about
30 minutes after it took off and just as the plane crossed into
Indian airspace.
</P>
<P>
   The hijackers, armed with AK-47 rifles, grenades and knives that
they had apparently carried when they boarded in Nepal, first
ordered the pilot fly to Lahore, Pakistan. After Pakistani
authorities denied them permission to land, the plane was allowed
to land in nearby Amritsar, in northwestern India, because it was
running low on fuel, with 20 minutes of flying time remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In Amritsar, the hijackers appeared to panic after having warned
authorities that they would begin killing passengers if anyone
tried to approach the plane except to refuel it. Airport officials
said the gunmen opened fire while the aircraft was on the ground
and then, without waiting for refueling, ordered the pilot to take
off.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said later that the pilot reported to air
controllers that the hijackers had told him that they had killed
four people and had injured several others.
</P>
<P>
   The plane again turned toward Lahore, sinking to an altitude of
just 500 feet before Pakistani officials finally agreed to let it
make an emergency landing on a darkened runway.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan had already sent army commandos to patrol the airport,
although officials tried hard to avoid having anything to do with
the plane. The airport manager, Ghulam Mustafa Mirani, told the
Agence France-Presse that the runway lights had been switched off
to prevent the plane from landing. Only when the plane was
dangerously close to a crash landing, Mirani said, did authorities
relent.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Foreign Ministry in Islamabad said
permission was granted on humanitarian grounds after the pilot
reported that he was almost out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   In Lahore, the hijackers demanded fuel and food but apparently
did not speak directly to officials. A spokesman for the
government, General Rashid Qureshi, said the hijackers made their
demands through the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   After 2 1-2 hours in La- hore, the gunmen ordered the pilot to
fly to Afghanistan, the authorities said. But it was denied landing
per- mission, and detoured to Dubai be- fore returning and being
allowed to land at Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
   Security experts speculated that the hijacking could be linked
to the disputed territory of Kashmir, the object of a long and
bitter struggle between India and Pakistan that heated up into a
military confrontation this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
