</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-SHOPPING (Undated) _ The season started at 4:30 a.m. the
day after Thanksgiving with shoppers lining up outside Toys ``R''
Us in Atlanta to buy Pokemon cards _ and it built from there.
Yahoo, the leading Internet portal, recorded more purchases through
its Web site in five days this month than it did during the entire
1998 holiday season. In New York, the Gap ran out of $175 leather
pants so fast that the sight of shoppers breaking into tears of
frustration became common. The millennium celebration may turn out
to be a bust, but by any measure Christmas 1999 was swinging. By
Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-BEER (Cairo, Egypt) _ When the Egyptian government put the
national beer company up for sale a few years ago, nobody was
buying. The brewery was a management nightmare. Workers napped
while grimy, ancient machines gushed foaming beer into dirty green
bottles, often along with insects, twigs and clumps of dirt. But
Ahmed Zayat, an Egyptian entrepreneur, spotted potential where
others saw only pitfalls. Nearly three later, Zayat has turned the
bedraggled enterprise into one of the best-performing companies in
Egypt. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT18 and graphic are being sent to NYT
photo/graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BOND-RATES (New York) _ For much of this year, the question in
financial markets has been: What happens if there are real
computer-generated problems at the turn to the Year 2000? But as
1999 closes _ and as the fears of Year 2000 fade _ the question has
changed to: What if there are no Year 2000 computer problems? By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK-FISHER (Rochester, N.Y.) _ George Fisher was once hailed
as Kodak Co.'s shining star, and was treated like a hero in Kodak's
hometown. But now Daniel Carp, a 29-year Kodak employee who has
long been Fisher's heir apparent, is to become Kodak's chief
executive _ a year before Fisher's contract officially runs out. By
Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-TOBACCO (Undated) _ The California state treasurer imposes
a moratorium on state investments in tobacco stocks and asks the
state's big public employee pension fund to consider divesting its
shares. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-Y2K (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ With less than a week to go, no
one is quite sure what the fallout will be from Latin America's
approach to dealing with the Year 2000 problem. Some of the
region's poorest countries, like Paraguay, are drastically
ill-prepared, while other nations, like Chile and Mexico, planned
ahead and budgeted funds to sufficiently adapt their government
computers. Nevertheless, there appears to be a consensus emerging
among the people who have been rushing to prepare the region: The
parts of Latin America most at risk are also the most
technologically advanced, while the most underdeveloped regions,
while they will almost surely also be affected by the problem, are
not likely to suffer as much as the pockets of wealth. By Simon
Romero.
</P>
