<P>
   BBN-METS (New York) _ On the Mets, who in the last 18 months
have acquired Mike Piazza, Robin Ventura, Armando Benitez and now
Mike Hampton. No team has been as aggressive in piling on talent,
and payroll. And the reason is obivous: the Mets share New York
with the world champion Yankees and are trying to compete. By
Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW-RELIGIONS (Undated) _ Studying new religions is a growing
field, attracting psychologists, law anthropolgists and literary
critics. Many say we're seeing a spurt of intense religious
activity, comparable to last century when the Mormon and
Seventh-day Adventist churches began. By Gustav Niebuhr. (1350
words)
</P>
<P>
   MODERN-MASKS (Undated) _ Once upon a time masks belonged to
anthropology. They were strange objects made of wood, shells,
feathers and bells that primitives wore for coming-of-age rituals,
funerary rites, rain dances, fertility festivals and seasonal
get-togethers. Modern people also wear masks: hockey masks, gas
masks, surgical masks. You could say that modern masks are just for
protection. You could also say that hockey, war and surgery are
rituals and that these masks reveal something about the
relationships of the people who wear them. And now puppeteers,
artists and dramatists are spinning their own theories about the
place of masks in modern culture now, and they are finding that it
is not all kinship or cranial protection. By Barbara Boxer. (1300
words).
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT 7-10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ZERO (Undated) _ Before the millennium gasps its last tired
breath, a final tribute must be paid to something overlooked. It
might seem to be nothing, yet during the last 1,000 years it has
transformed physics, mathematics, commerce and the shape of Western
civilization. That something is nothing. And that nothing is marked
by something. The object in question is the number zero. And zero,
whose presence declares absence, is a cipher in more ways than one
_ or maybe in more ways than none. Edward Rothstein looks at two
recents books about zero. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   STUART-MOVIE (Hollywood) _ How the movie ``Stuart Little''
differs from the book. By Rick Lyman. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   KENEALLY-IRISH (Undated) _ Thomas Keneally talks about his new
book on the Irish diaspora, ``The Great Shame and the Triumph of
the Irish in the English-Speaking World.'' By Mel Gussow. (1600
words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-AMERICAN-WRITERS (New York) _ The Asian American Writers
Workshop is thriving. By Robert Waddell. (700 words)
</P>
