<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-MAKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUSTOM SKIS FOR THE NEW MILLENNIUM, AND $2,000
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wyo.)   (rk) 
 By   BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Adam Sherman thought it was a joke when advertising executives
from Dewar's, the Scotch whiskey maker, phoned him about appearing
in an advertisement. As the founder of a fledgling ski
manufacturing company in Jackson Hole, Wyo., Sherman was hardly a
mover or shaker.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he had been living in a van the past few years. He
took his showers in the back of the cement-block warehouse where
his staff of eight workers make custom-built skis in Jackson Hole.
One of the employees even lives there now, in a custom-built
cardboard box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were kidding, of course,'' Sherman said
recently about the phone call from the Dewar's executives in New
York City. ``But then they called me back with 16 people on a
conference call.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were definitely curious. I'm sure they envisioned me
sitting there in a coat and tie like them, just talking on the
phone. But I was just hanging out in ski clothes. I don't think
they understood we are all ski bums.''
</P>
<P>
   The subsequent ad contact proved fruitful beyond his wildest
dreams. Dewar's told Sherman, 30, that the company wanted him and
his two partners, Bryce Roberts, 26, and Niki Singlaub, 24, to be
featured in its new ``Profiles for the New Millennium'' campaign.
The $2 million advertisement would appear in national magazines
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Why us, they asked. ``Today it's all about going there, not
getting there,'' said Frank Ginsberg, chairman of Dewar's
advertising agency, Avrett, Free &AMP; Ginsburg. ``The risk, not the
reward.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman could relate. He had named his company Igneous Skis,
igneous as in rock that ``comes from fire,'' he said. Dewar's flew
the three budding stars to New York last August for the photo
shoot. They were picked up at the airport and taken to a Soho hotel
for three days. Plenty of good food and wine, too, Sherman reports.
</P>
<P>
   But is their company truly hot? Well, not yet, especially given
the company's allegiance to skis and the preponderance of
snowboarders on the slopes these days _ 27 percent of all Alpine
visits last season. But each one of the Igneous triumvirate is a
diehard skier who puts in 100 days or more on the slopes each
winter. Just try to reach them before 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Dewar's ad shows Sherman and his two partners on a chairlift
(in a shot that was fabricated in an air-conditioned New York City
studio). All three have that 20-something, baggy-clothed demeanor
of a contented snowboarder. But Sherman scoffs at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skiing is going to become cool again,'' he said. ``The ski
industry is in one big cycle. Snowboarding catches on with the
younger set, and they take over the sport. But then all the
50-year-olds want to do it, and it's no longer punk. So then all
the early snowboarders go back to skiing, looking for ways to make
it more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman's confidence comes despite modest revenue. Still in the
red after four years, Igneous has reached its goal for the coming
season: 350 pairs of custom-built skis. Word is getting out,
Sherman said, through the company's Internet site,
www.igneousskis.com/.
</P>
<P>
   But theirs is a select market. To create a custom ski, Sherman
and his colleagues try to meet face to face with potential
customers. They watch how a person skis and then listen to what the
skier thinks he or she needs. Then they suggest a design based on
eight basic models, but with individual adaptations.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is fierce from companies like Rossignol,
Salomon, K2 and Atomic in a relatively flat sales market. But with
prices that range from $600 to $2,000 for a pair of custom skis,
the team at Igneous is not worried about cutting costs for
materials that make a good ski better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking at the bottom line on skis,'' Singlaub said.
``And we don't use the gadgets that other manufacturers are using
to sell skis. They're all little add-ons that change the ski in a
minor way.''
</P>
<P>
   It still remains to be seen whether a small operation like
Igneous can eventually compete with mass producers. Hugh Harley,
president of Rossignol Skis in the United States, said recently
that consolidation in the industry has a way of swallowing up small
companies. ``If they can develop a little bit of a cult following,
they might survive,'' Harley said. ``But the rubber's going to meet
the road at some time. It's going to be very, very rough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
