<HEADER>
A8766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-YACHT-DISASTER-NYT &LR;      12-25 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHT-DISASTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECTER OF DISASTER LOOMS OVER AUSTRALIAN RACE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOHN SHAW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Last year on the day after Christmas, Iain
Moray _ banker by profession, sailor by preference _ skippered his
35-footer, Siena, in the 630-mile Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up helping in the rescue of the crew of a larger yacht
shattered by 70-knot winds and 50-foot waves.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the 1,135 sailors in the 54th running of the
Sydney-to-Hobart classic were killed. Scores of other crew members
were injured, and 57 had to be hauled from damaged yachts, sinking
rafts and the sea itself by helicopters and coast guard craft in
the largest maritime civilian rescue operation in Australia's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Only 44 of the 115 boats that started the race finished the
course. Five of them sank in a tempest that quickly escalated from
a grim forecast of storm-force gales to the terrifying reality of
90 mph winds and 35-foot waves.
</P>
<P>
   When this year's race begins here on Sunday, Moray, a veteran of
six Sydney-to-Hobarts and three other major ocean races, will stay
in the harbor as some 80 yachts put to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Moray and some other skippers say they would not have started
last year, or would have quit sooner, if they had been fully
briefed on storm warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-hour hurricane-force ``extreme event,'' as weather
experts called it, was predicted by some forecasters, but the
warnings were not fully heeded by race officials _ an aspect of the
disaster that remains controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the sport dearly, but not enough to die for it,'' Moray
said, recalling winds of 86 knots and whiteout conditions in which
``the tops blew off the waves and spume came at you horizontally
like bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this year there will most likely be 35 fewer starters
than a year ago, most of the absentees are not protesters or
sailors worried by storms. Rather, many regular crews have heeded
family requests to stay home for millennium celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Moray has vowed to shun the passage to Hobart, the capital
of Australia's island state of Tasmania, until more is revealed of
the 1998 disaster and reforms are made to help avoid another.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the worst tragedy in Australia's sporting history,
and there must be an independent investigation without further
delay,'' Moray said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the government of New South Wales ordered
a coroner's inquiry last December into the death of the six
yachtsmen, no judicial verdict on the deaths has been delivered,
nor is one expected soon because of bureaucratic tardiness and the
illness of a coroner.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 1998 Sydney-to-Hobart remains the deadliest event
in world yachting since the 1979 Fastnet race when 80-knot winds
off the British and Irish coasts capsized 80 of the 300 entrants,
sinking 20 boats and killing 15 sailors.
</P>
<P>
   A report on last year's disaster by the race organizers, the
Cruising Yacht Club of Australia, did not find fault but
recommended 12 new or stricter safety measures, including mandatory
carrying of high-precision position-indicating radio beacons able
to guide rescuers within three miles of an emergency location. A
helicopter equipped with advanced search and communication systems
will shadow the fleet this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian club's commodore, Hugo Van Kretschmar, a veteran
of 19 Hobarts, including last year's, said: ``The race has grown in
stature as a result of last year. Some lesser competitions would
have crumbled, but world yachting recognizes the challenge here and
the quest for adventure which draws sailors to it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a test of offshore sailing, the Australian race is rated
alongside two northern hemisphere events _ the annual 600-mile
Atlantic voyage from Newport, R.I., to Bermuda and the Fastnet
contest for Britain's Admiral's Cup, sailed every two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney-to-Hobart's macho reputation belies the race's more
relaxed beginnings in 1945 as a vacation voyage (``no spinnakers,
gentlemen''). It evolved into the current mix of recreation and
rivalry where weekend craft of skilled amateurs, from lawyers to
laborers, blend with the maxis of tycoons crewed by professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's winner, as in 1995, was the maxi-yacht Sayonara,
owned by Larry Ellison, the billionaire founder of Oracle software.
His crew of 22 sailed fast enough (two days and 19 hours, but
almost 19 hours outside the record time) to escape the worst of the
storm. But Ellison, upon arrival in Hobart, still deemed the
experience ``just awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, three American entries will race this year, Alaska
Eagle, Mari-Cha III and Pipe Dream IX, all here on transworld
voyages.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Roger Badham, an Australian meteorologist who is in
Auckland, New Zealand, advising the America's Cup campaign of
America One, one of three U.S. qualifiers for the cup semifinals
next month, said the storm that struck the 1998 Sydney-Hobart was
``a one in 50 or more years event, rare and extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   Badham sees early indications for favorable northeast winds to
give the fleet a good start southward this year, with the chance of
a low-pressure front _ the condition that forms storms _ across the
course later.
</P>
<P>
   Severe weather is hardly rare on the haul to Hobart. In 1984,
southerly gales forced 104 of 150 starters to retire. In 1993,
there were 110 starters but only 38 mastered gusts up to 70 knots
to finish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
