<HEADER>
A8811 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-SPAIN-SIESTA-2TAKES-N     12-25 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-SIESTA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MODERN SPAIN, THE SIESTA FACES OBSOLESCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ With Spain under pressure to conform to the
shorter lunch- break habits in most of the 14 other countries in
the European Union, its traditional workday _ with its three-hour
siesta break to eat and sleep _ is disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, large companies are cutting lunch to two hours and
corporate culture is turning against the concept of nodding off
during the day, seeing it as a sign of laziness.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Carranza Ortiz, the director of human resources for
one of Spain's largest banks, Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, is clear on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who can take siestas do,'' he said. ``But those who are
really serious about working do not.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all Spaniards agree. Some openly rail at this
sort of thinking. Others have become closet nappers, sometimes
retreating to their cars or into nearby health clubs for a quick
snooze. Carranza had no sooner disappeared down the hall to his
next meeting when another bank official confided that he still
slipped home every day for a 30-minute rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very healthy,'' he said. ``You feel much better.'' But
please, he begged, he could not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   The siesta question is a big issue here because abandoning the
midday snooze amounts to a radical change in a traditional way of
life. When the European Union tried in the early 1990s to get the
Spanish to take the tilde _ the squiggle over the letter n _ from
their keyboards to conform with the single market enshrined in the
Treaty of Rome, howls of protests went up. The European Union
eventually backed down.
</P>
<P>
   Feelings about the siesta can run just as deep. The mayor of
Plasencia, a town in the western province of Caceres, was so
concerned about the growing noise during the lunch hour that he
issued an order calling for silence between 3 and 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Studies suggesting that naps are healthy are routinely trumpeted
in Spanish papers, proof that the rest of the world is finally
coming around to something that Spaniards long ago discovered. Last
summer, the national daily El Mundo devoted 10 pages to the
subject. It said that siestas in America were called ``power naps''
and it cited Levi Strauss, Ben &AMP; Jerry's and Mac World Magazine as
some of the companies trying out ``nap lounges.''
</P>
<P>
   The headline read: ``It's proven _ the siesta is beneficial, and
if in the United States they are starting to discover it, here it
continues to be part of the national heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   But even its proponents say the siesta is under attack on many
fronts. The economy is on the upswing, with more new jobs created
here this year than in any other country in the 15-nation European
Union _ 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   This has increased traffic in the cities and allowed young
people to move to the suburbs. More and more Spaniards are facing
long commutes, and increasingly women are joining the work force,
although the unemployment rate for women remains at 22 percent,
twice that for men.
</P>
<P>
   Still, all this means that popping home is getting harder. And
since couples are both working, no one is there cooking the hot
meal that usually preceded the siesta.
</P>
<P>
   The siesta has pretty much vanished from the cities of Latin
America, though some rural areas carry on, especially in the most
tropical climes. Last April it came to an abrupt halt in Mexico
City when President Ernesto Zedillo imposed a new schedule that
required officials to be at their desks from 9 a.m. until 6 p.m.
That has quickened a lengthy erosion in the siesta there.
</P>
<P>
   A Spanish mattress company, Pikolin, which recently did a survey
on the subject, found that only 25 percent of Spaniards surveyed
still take a siesta and, unlike 50 years ago, few actually get into
bed anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The siesta is nothing more than a cliche for most working
people in Spain,'' said Juan Ignacio Perez-Nievas, the company's
marketing director. ``They do not have time for it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The survey indicated that the siesta is most popular among the
older generation and rarest for young people, particularly in the
most northern regions of Spain, where the weather is coolest.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many young people mourn the loss of the afternoon nap, which
they say gave a certain pace to the day and intimacy to their
parents' relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Suarez Santos, for instance, director of the labor
relations department of the powerful Spanish Employers'
Organization, said a siesta was out of the question for him.
</P>
<P>
   Suarez, 31, said he is really expected to have lunch with his
colleagues, talk about work and then get back to the office
quickly. He looks on the siesta, however, as something that
enhanced his parents' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had this time to go back home and talk to each other,''
Suarez said. ``They had two or three hours together in the middle
of the day to discuss what was going on in their lives. It gave a
coherence to the family. Now it seems there is less and less time
to talk. There is time at the end of the day, but somehow it is
perhaps not the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the workday in Spain is a bit chaotic these days. Big
department stores are open throughout the afternoon lunch break now
and remain open way into the evening, usually until 8:30 p.m. But
most small stores continue to close from 2 to 5 p.m. Almost
everybody knows someone who still has a three-hour lunch, someone
who has two hours and someone who is working an eight-hour shift.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say that new collective bargaining agreements
are increasingly calling for continuous shifts, and many union
officials say they are glad about it. Otherwise, they say,
Spaniards tend to have a very long day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our people are up at 6 a.m. to get to work and then
they don't get home from work until about 9 p.m.'' said Antonio
Ferrer, the secretary of the General Workers' Union, which has
nearly 1 million members. ``Where else in the world do you have a
workday like that?''
</P>
<P>
   But many of those who still have the traditional Spanish day
like it that way. In the historic district of Madrid, Florencio
Cordoba, 46, closes his famous cape shop, Sesenin, at 2 p.m. and
goes home for three hours, where he changes into his pajamas, eats
his lunch and usually sleeps on the couch with the television on.
</P>
<P>
   Back to work at 5 p.m., he closes at 8:30 p.m. He considers the
siesta not only healthy, but a Spanish custom that should never be
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he sees the changes coming even in his own household. His
oldest daughter now works a continuous day, getting home at 6 p.m.
``She is always complaining she is tired,'' Cordoba said.
</P>
<P>
   And these days his wife has begun talking about going to work.
But he hopes she will not. ``I know that if she was not at home
everything would change,'' he said. ``We do not have two fancy
cars, but we have been happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some diehard nappers have just found creative ways of getting a
little nap in on a shortened lunch break.
</P>
<P>
   A chain called ``Masajes a 1000'' _ which offers busy Spaniards
a sort of McDonald's version of a siesta _ has opened 21 franchises
since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At one of its newly opened health spas in downtown Madrid, the
lights were dim and all was quiet as four customers napped in
ergonomically correct chairs, wrapped in plaid blankets. Each had
paid $6 for a five-minute massage and a chance to take a half-hour
snooze.
</P>
<P>
   The occupant of one chair was Sara Ibanez, a 35-year-old
biologist. She happily leaned her head forward on the padded
cushion and fell asleep sitting up.
</P>
<P>
   Her employer, a Spanish pharmaceutical company, cut her lunch
break from three hours to two six weeks ago. She is understanding
about the company's need to have her at her desk when workers in
other European countries are at theirs.
</P>
<P>
   But she still wants her shut-eye. ``Afterward you have energy
for the rest of the day,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
