<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GERMANY-KRENZ-2TAKES &LR;      12-25 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-KRENZ-2TAKES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DECADE AFTER THE BERLIN WALL CAME DOWN, QUESTIONS ABOUT PUNISHING
EGON KRENZ  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Egon Krenz, who had the bad luck to become leader of
Communist East Germany three weeks before the Berlin Wall fell in
1989, is not going to prison without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Hunkered down on a recent December day in his comfortable home
on the east side of Berlin, he pleaded on the telephone in fluent
Russian for support from old allies in Moscow. He cited German and
European law from thumb-worn paperbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly he complained about being made a scapegoat. After years
of courtroom battles, he is supposed to start serving a six-year
sentence for his complicity in his government's policy of shooting
people who tried to escape to the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is regrettable that there were deaths at the border,''
Krenz, 62, said sullenly. ``But I didn't divide Europe. I didn't
divide Germany. I didn't create the Iron Curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few miles away, a former comrade on the Politburo has
decided to stop arguing. Guenther Schabowski, 70 and ill with
diabetes, was effectively the old government's spokesman and was
prosecuted alongside Krenz. Unlike his former boss, Schabowski
quietly entered prison on Dec. 14 to serve a sentence of three and
a half years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have absolutely nothing in common anymore,'' Schabowski
said in a brief interview before he entered prison. ``Krenz can do
what he wants and talk about `victor's justice.' But I don't see it
that way. I think the German courts are fully within their rights
to render a judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   These are two aging men who woke up on the wrong side of history
10 years ago. One is unrepentant and combative. The other is tired
and remorseful. Both are among the very few top-ranking former
Communist leaders punished for their deeds, and they embody the
uncomfortable debate in Germany about trying and jailing those who
served the old Communist government.
</P>
<P>
   Many Germans consider Krenz's rendezvous with prison long
overdue. German courts have prosecuted nearly 150 other former East
German officials, from lowly border guards up through the former
defense minister. Some have already completed their prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz took over from East Germany's longtime strongman, Erich
Honecker, just as the government was crumbling. Honecker, who had
cancer, escaped prosecution by arranging exile in Chile, where he
died in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Many Germans, even those who reviled the Berlin Wall, are uneasy
about sending Krenz to prison. They worry that evidence of his
personal complicity in border shootings is weak, that he has been
convicted for what he represented rather than what he did. They
sympathize with his contention that he was convicted for actions
that were not illegal under the old government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was really a political decision,'' said Uwe Wesel, a
professor of civil rights law at the Free University in Berlin.
``Some of the other prosecutions were appropriate, because they
were against people who were in the leadership when decisions were
made that led to people being shot at the border, but with Krenz
and Schabowski, it was completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference, Wesel said, is that both men joined the
Politburo in the mid-1980s, long after the border policies were
decided. Neither played a direct role in the shootings, and it is
doubtful that either could have changed the policy, which Krenz
said was laid down in Moscow and ultimately depended on the Soviet
leader, Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev enjoys considerable respect in Germany, though, as the
person who allowed the peaceful reunification of east and west.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz is a pariah. Aside from trying to put him in prison, the
German government is also trying to seize his spacious home,
contending that the purchase was never lawful and that the home
belongs to the state. Krenz has even been kept at arm's length by
the re-engineered successor to East Germany's old Communist Party.
Except for some occasional writing, he has been unemployed for
years.
</P>
<P>
   He gets little sympathy from people in his neighborhood of
Pankow. Though some neighbors are uneasy about the way he was
prosecuted, most say he deserves to be punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Krenz should have been put before an East German court right
after the wall came down and should have been prosecuted by his own
people,'' said Frank Fischer, a 48-year-old truck driver who grew
up on the east side of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Lengsfeld, now a member of the German parliament who was
imprisoned in 1988 because of her public opposition to the
government's military policies, said: ``I look forward to the day
when we no longer have to be preoccupied with Krenz and his lies. I
think the verdict is entirely appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Krenz showed no remorse. ``I would rather be a hard-liner than a
soft egg,'' he said during a two-hour interview. A bookshelf of
decorative miniature books in his living room is dominated by the
writings of Marx, Engels, Lenin and Honecker.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz's greatest legacy may well be that he lived with one of
history's most notorious bumbles. On the evening of Nov. 9, 1989,
it was Schabowski who announced _ in error, as he later admitted _
that the Berlin Wall would suddenly be open to anyone who wanted to
cross.
</P>
<P>
   It was not what the Communist Party's governing Central
Committee had intended, but it was greeted by joyous mobs who
poured through the gates. Krenz, forced to choose between leaving
the gates open or blocking them with tanks, left them open.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent he feels guilty about anything today, Krenz said,
it is about the mistakes he made that night. ``From the point of
view of the German Democratic Republic, I was guilty on Nov. 9 of
letting events just flow and not guaranteeing the sovereignty of
East Germany,'' he said. ``But the courts would never prosecute me
for that. Instead, they are prosecuting me for the crimes of which
I am not guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has charged that Krenz, Schabowski or a third defendant,
Guenther Kleiber, ever gave orders to shoot people at the border.
The main evidence of their personal complicity comes down to two
tangential votes taken by the Central Committee. One was a vote in
1986 to ``take note of'' a long speech by Honecker, which included
praise for the national police and border patrol. The other was a
vote in 1985 to accept a report from the Defense Ministry, which
noted that border guards had fulfilled their duty and would
continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz contends above all that none of his actions were illegal
at the time. ``The German Democratic Republic was a legitimate
state that was accepted and existed alongside the old Federal
Republic of Germany,'' he said. ``Its laws were never challenged
before an international tribunal like the United Nations. But
suddenly, as soon as the GDR collapsed, it was delegitimized.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Under Germany's reunification treaty in 1990, crimes committed
in the old East Germany were supposed to be prosecuted under that
country's laws. But West German courts ruled that the border
shootings, the most visible aspect of repression under the
Communist government, should be prosecuted as basic violations of
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   A Berlin court sentenced Krenz in August 1998. A federal court
in Leipzig upheld the sentence in early November and ordered all
three defendants to surrender by mid-December.
</P>
<P>
   Schabowski did just that. Kleiber, another former Politburo
member who was sentenced to three and a half years, received a
short reprieve, because his wife is ill. Krenz got his respite on
Dec. 14, when the German supreme court said it wanted time to
evaluate his plea to remain free until his appeals were exhausted.
The court is expected to rule shortly after the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz contends that the trial violated his own human rights, and
he is appealing his conviction to the European Court of Human
Rights in Strasbourg. His contention, rejected by the court in
Berlin, is that his government's border policies were decided
entirely in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our highest commander was Mikhail Gorbachev,'' he said. ``I
never saw any sign before 1990 that he was willing to accept
opening the border.''
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit for Krenz's trial in 1996, Gorbachev contended
that prosecution of top officials amounted to a ``witch hunt''
against people who actually contributed to reunification. ``The
question is whether there is any merit in making people, who were
partners not long ago, into scapegoats,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's reconstructed Communist Party, the Party of Democratic
Socialism, has also defended Krenz even as it has avoided any
active political association with him.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz, puttering about his living room, said his court trial
might as well have been in a foreign language for all the
misunderstandings. ``We may all speak German, but I felt we needed
a translator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Schabowski freely accepted the court's jurisdiction
and gave a moving apology for his role in what he called a failed
regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who died at the wall are part of the burden we inherit
from our misguided attempt to free humanity from its plagues,'' he
said at the time. ``As a former supporter and protagonist of this
world view, I feel guilt and shame when I think of those who died
at the wall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
