<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Dec. 26:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Russian media say Russian forces have
begun what is billed as the final assault on Grozny. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-SIESTA (Madrid, Spain) _ With Spain under pressure to
conform to the shorter lunch break habits in most of the 14 other
countries in the European Union, its traditional workday _ with its
three-hour siesta break to eat and sleep _ is disappearing. By
Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-KRENZ (Berlin) _ Egon Krenz, who had the bad luck to
become leader of Communist East Germany three weeks before the
Berlin Wall fell in 1989, is not going to prison without a fight.
By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PHONE-DEAL _ A few years ago, when an American company
was seeking a toehold in the newly privatized and potentially
lucrative Russian telecommunications market, it cut a secret deal
with directors and officers at the Moscow telephone company. By
Raymond Bonner.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-TENSION (Seoul, South Korea) _ Ever since war divided the
Korean peninsula in 1953, residents of this bustling capital city,
30 miles from the demilitarized zone, have lived with the threat
that Communist troops from North Korea could storm the border at
any time. But a decision by the United States military to
distribute 14,000 protective gas masks to American dependents
living in Seoul has raised concerns here that North Korea is
planning a major assault that will include chemical warfare. By
Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-ASYLUM (United Nations) _ During the last six months,
Australians have been surprised by an influx of people arriving in
small boats from Iraq and Afghanistan who, officials say, are first
being delivered to nearby Indonesian islands by smugglers from the
Middle East and then moved to Australia's north coast, where they
try to claim asylum. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-CHRISTMAS (Rome) _ On the first day of the 2000 Holy Year,
John Paul II delivered a Christmas speech Saturday that called for
repentance in the new millennium. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-ERRORS _ Spurred by an Institute of Medicine report last
month, big employers, health care organizations, state regulators
and the federal government are stepping up pressure to revamp a
health care system that calls itself the best in the world yet
hides and ignores mistakes that kill tens of thousands of patients
a year. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   NY-IMMIG (New York) _ Here at the end of the century, one in
three city residents is an immigrant and, of those, nearly half are
newly minted New Yorkers who arrived only in the last 15 years. Not
since 1910, at the peak of this century's great wave of immigration
through Ellis Island, has the ratio of newcomers been as high. By
Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHANCELLOR-ASSESS (New York) _ As New York City seeks its
12th schools chancellor in 20 years, one question seems
inescapable: Can anybody do this job? By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-BABIES (Houston) _ In the last year, without any
apparent pattern, the Houston metropolitan area has experienced an
unprecedented rash of baby abandonment. The problem has baffled
local officials, who say an ordinary year might bring two or three
cases and who are confronted by a pair of questions no one can
answer: Why here? Why now? By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   RETIREE-EDUC (Los Angeles) _ Here at the Plato Society, an
educational haven for retirees, they prefer not to even call it a
class. Please, say study group. Teachers? Call them coordinators.
No papers, no tests. Just learning, for learning's sake. By Jodi
Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR-FIGHT (Spokane, Wash.) _ The 15-month struggle between
Kaiser Aluminum and the United Steelworkers of America is one of
the biggest, longest and fiercest labor disputes in years, but it
is far more than an old-fashioned labor war. It is a war of
attrition, a test of wills and a propaganda war against the
billionaire Texan who controls Kaiser, a man the union denounces as
a latter-day robber baron. By Steven Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   EPA-COAL-POWER (New Haven, W.Va.) _ The Philip Sporn electric
plant here is one of the coal-fired plants cited by the EPA in a
suit filed last month against seven utilities that are charged with
violating the Clean Air Act, in what the agency says is one of the
largest investigations in its history. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-POLITICS (Austin, Texas) _ His father's failed re-election
effort stands as one of the most difficult episodes of George W.
Bush's life, a period when events seemed to spin out of his
family's control and he watched a man he reveres suffer the
ultimate public rejection. But, just as important, the loss carried
with it indelible lessons in the controllable and uncontrollable
ways a campaign can go wrong, and it has a clear bearing on the
kind of candidate Bush is today. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HIGHTECH (Washington) _ At a time when Congress is
bitterly divided and unable to reach consensus on issues like gun
control and health care, Democrats and Republicans are happily
reaching across party lines to pass legislation backed by high-tech
companies. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE-BUDGET (Washington) _ Flush with this year's first real
growth in military spending in more than a decade, Defense
Secretary William Cohen has quietly told all the services that in
drawing up this coming year's spending plan they must live within
the limits imposed in the current budget of more than $285 billion
and not expect additional increases. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   RIVERS-AID-DISPUTE (Washington) _ From the vantage point of its
supporters, the Clinton administration's river restoration program
is flowing smoothly, carrying federal aid to the neglected reaches
of participating communities. To opponents, the program is an
illegal expansion of federal powers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ Pucci, Yes! Prawns, No! By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN _ Waiting for Assad. By Thomas L. Friedman.
</P>
