<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 11:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8819 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-POLITICS-2TAKES(     12-25 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLITICS-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT BUSH'S BITTER DEFEAT SET COURSE FOR SON'S CANDIDACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For months, George W. Bush had sensed what was
coming; he could see it in the news coverage of the campaign, feel
it in the restlessness of the crowds he addressed on his father's
behalf, hear it in acquaintances' apologies for their sudden
fascination with a political insurgent named Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush had tried, with intermittent success, to smile through
it all, because that was his role: the tireless cheerleader, the
dauntless optimist.
</P>
<P>
   By 3 p.m. on Nov. 3, 1992, there was no more pretending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exit polls look bad,'' Bush told his father, who had clung
to the belief that he might beat back Bill Clinton's challenge in
the end. Bush was actually underselling the truth. The exit polls
looked awful.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, hours later, when Bush listened to his father bid
goodbye to the presidency in a concession speech in a Houston
hotel, all the waiting and all the knowing that had preceded the
moment did not make it any easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember looking down at a White House photographer, a woman
who just had tears streaming down her face _ and mascara _ and then
I kind of looked at the ceiling,'' Bush said in a recent interview
here. ``If I'd looked at her, I would have been weeping like a
baby.''
</P>
<P>
   To this day, his father's failed re-election effort stands as
one of the most difficult episodes of Bush's life, a period when
events seemed to spin out of his family's control and he watched a
man he reveres suffer the ultimate public rejection.
</P>
<P>
   But, just as important, the loss carried with it indelible
lessons in the controllable and uncontrollable ways a campaign can
go wrong, and it has a clear bearing on the kind of candidate Bush
is today.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, he came to question the devotion of some of his
father's associates from inside the Beltway. Now, he entrusts his
own presidential campaign to a so-called ``iron triangle'' of three
longtime advisers in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   He saw his father tarred and feathered for agreeing to raise
taxes after saying he would not. Now, Bush seems to avoid emphatic
pledges that could come back to haunt him. He is also assiduous
about articulating the themes and priorities of his campaign and
reaching out to minorities, two things his father was criticized
for not doing well enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father's term in office _ and the campaign of 1992 _ have
had as much impact on the way he's been governor and his current
campaign as any other experience in his life,'' said Robert M.
Teeter, who managed the re-election effort.
</P>
<P>
   That bitter year was also a case study of the traits that
distinguish the Bushes: their loyalty to one another, their stiff
upper lips, their potent belief in their own worthiness.
</P>
<P>
   It provided a similarly revealing glimpse of Bush, underscoring
his capacity for anger and especially his competitiveness, so keen
that he responded to his father's loss by insisting on a different
kind of victory and training for a marathon, the first and only one
he ever ran.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts, journalists and even some of Bush's
opponents have speculated that his current quest is in part an
effort to avenge his father's defeat. Bush has repeatedly laughed
at this suggestion, but it is a sensitive enough point among his
friends that one of them called a reporter to dispute it even
though the reporter had not broached the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Another friend, Joe O'Neill, a businessman in Midland, Texas,
who grew up with Bush, acknowledged that the way President Clinton
ended up comporting himself in office probably helped keep Bush's
emotional memory of 1992 alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ignominy of losing to this guy, in particular, probably
burns him,'' O'Neill said. ``He has no respect for Clinton morally.
And morals count in the Bush family.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Bush's tangle of motives, his friends and relatives say
that whatnessed in 1992 illustrated firsthand how quickly
and dramatically political winds can shift and how little can be
taken for granted. That perspective, they say, could stand him in
good stead over the months to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having seen his dad go through four national
campaigns, particularly the last one, has given George a very
realistic picture of what he faces,'' said former President Bush in
a written response to several questions that were submitted to him,
an interview format that he requested.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is a bump in the road, I expect he will not be
thrown off course,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Although Barbara Bush has described her husband's interest in
their eldest son's campaign as obsessive, the former president said
he did not butt in with unsolicited counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am available if George wants to ask my advice, but I was
then and he is now,'' President Bush said. ``I am yesterday. He is
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   President Bush receded into the past sooner than he wanted to,
sooner than anyone around him thought he would. Just a year and
half before the 1992 election, on the heels of the Persian Gulf
War, he had a stratospheric job approval rating of 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It dipped 20 points or so later in the year, but that seemed
little cause for worry. ``We went into the Christmas season
upbeat,'' George W. Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush also had more personal reasons to be happy,
because he was finally making the kind of name for himself that he
would need if he wanted to run for governor, a prospect that had
long been on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After living briefly in Washington to work on his father's
successful 1988 presidential campaign, Bush had returned to his
beloved Texas, settled in Dallas and put together a partnership
that bought the Texas Rangers baseball team and paved the path
toward the construction of a gleaming stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was the organization's managing partner and public face, an
exuberant presence not in some distant sky box but in a seat above
first base, where he beamed with pleasure as fans approached him
for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But as the new year began, his father's fate seemed increasingly
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush, more assertive by nature than his father, had
urged the president and his advisers to give the re-election
campaign an early, aggressive launching, it was not moving as fast
as it could have been, nor was it headed in a clear direction.
</P>
<P>
   A downturn in the economy showed no sign of abating. And
President Bush was still recovering from the departure of John H.
Sununu, his chief of staff, who was coaxed into resigning after
doing and saying things that embarrassed the president, an
unacceptable breach of loyalty in the Bush family's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Most ominous was the emergence of two protest candidates in
addition to the herd of Democrats ganging up on President Bush. The
first was Patrick J. Buchanan, whose attacks on the president in
the Republican primaries badly bruised him. The second was Perot, a
wealthy Dallas entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's business office was across the street from a
small building where Perot posters, yard signs and bumper stickers
were sold, and he had a perfect vantage point to observe the
activity there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember seeing cars lined up, and these were nice, North
Dallas cars,'' Bush said. ``They should be screaming Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the drivers were people who were friendly with Bush or
his wife, Laura, and she said he called a few to seek explanations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd say, `We love your dad, we love your dad, but we just
feel we've got to,''' Mrs. Bush said in a recent interview. ``And
when that started, there was no way to figure out what was going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush conferred with Mary Matalin, the campaign's
deputy manager, as often as three times a day. He flew frequently
from Dallas to Washington to try to pump energy and confidence into
troops who seemed less spirited and focused than in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   He also confronted the Republican opinion makers who were
expressing doubts about his father.
</P>
<P>
   But it seemed to Ms. Matalin and to Bush that they could not
catch a break. President Bush's approval ratings sank lower, tugged
in part by the country's economic doldrums, which the president had
been slow to acknowledge. And the portrait of President Bush that
took hold in news coverage was that of an elite, weak leader
disconnected from the concerns of most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   This characterization, as much as anything else, devastated his
oldest son, who could not stand to see his father's character
impugned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They so love each other,'' Ms. Matalin explained. ``It's
something to behold. I've been in a million situations with the
father and son, and it's a movie _ I don't know how else to explain
it. The relationship is so complete.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of that closeness, George W. Bush loudly berated
reporters on a few occasions, demonstrating a temper that he has
since controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't act well,'' he conceded. ``I got frustrated because
of my dad. I got in some people's faces, out of frustration for
him, out of love for him, not out of disdain for the person. In
retrospect, those were such strong emotions for me, to see a good
man get whipped.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the Bush family seemed amazed that voters might
prefer Clinton or Perot over a man with such a long and
distinguished political resume.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Bush scribbled in her diary, ``I do not know whether
George will survive this political year or not, but I do know that
he is the only stable person running.''
</P>
<P>
   The last weeks of the campaign were tense. Laura Bush said she
could still remember the dread she felt every morning when, in a
ritual that she and her husband continue to this day, he would go
to the front stoop to get the newspapers and bring them back to
bed. Too often, she said, the publications carried newly
discouraging polls or freshly critical editorials.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she and her husband used to watch the morning news
programs on television as well, but the habit died in fall 1992.
``We just didn't want to hear another bad story,'' she said. ``It
was too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband said that he knew it was all over before the actual
moment of reckoning but that he tried not to let it show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect if he got down, he wouldn't burden me with that,''
his father said. ``We don't work that way.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 2, 1992, Bush was on the campaign plane with his father
on the way to Houston, where the whole family would gather for the
election. The Oak Ridge Boys, a vocal group that sometimes traveled
with President Bush, sang ``Amazing Grace'' at his request.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, as the returns trickled in, President Bush went to
buy a fishing reel. Ms. Matalin remembered that he also joined
George W. Bush and Jeb Bush, a younger son, in a game on the hotel
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most candidates sit on the phone all day,'' Ms. Matalin said.
``They were out there playing horseshoes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not that President Bush had stopped caring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe the emotions of something like this,''
he said in a Nov. 4 diary entry that was included in his recent
book of letters and other writings, ``All the Best, George Bush.''
``But it's hurt, hurt, hurt and I guess it's the pride, too.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush took 38 percent of the popular vote, to 43 percent for
Clinton and 19 percent for Ross Perot. The president's defeat,
oddly, made his oldest son's current candidacy possible. George W.
Bush said that he would not have felt comfortable about running for
governor of Texas in 1994 if his father had still been in office.
And without the five years he has spent as the leader of the
country's second most populous state, Bush would not be in a
credible position to seek the Republican nomination today.
</P>
<P>
   But in the days immediately after the election he was mainly
concerned with dissipating the frustration and disappointment he
felt. So he laced up his running sneakers, put on the grubby outfit
he typically used for exercise and hit the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   He ran too far and too fast, opening the window to a severe cold
and prompting a stern reprimand from his physician, who told him it
was ridiculous to shoot for the Dallas marathon in December. Bush
settled on the Houston marathon in January, still an ambitious
goal.
</P>
<P>
   His parents stood and waited at the 19-mile mark and, as Bush
remembered it, cheered him on.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some elderly women ahead of you!'' his mother
teased. ``Why are you running so slow?''
</P>
<P>
   His father just shouted, loudly and proudly, ``There's my boy!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
