<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8827 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-REVIEW-N     12-25 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING MARRIAGE, AN ISSUE REIGNITED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Hawaii, Alaska, Calif.)   (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jw) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the Vermont Supreme Court's bombshell ruling last week
stopping just short of legalizing gay marriage, it might be said
that the ``courtroom period'' of the national movement for same-sex
marriage has all but ended for now. With no major marriage cases
left pending in other states, the battle, all agree, shifts to
legislatures and the court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   But in its wake, some legal experts say, the ruling leaves
fodder for a long-running debate: How effective are courts at
bringing about social change?
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Koppelman, assistant professor at the Northwestern
University School of Law, who has argued that a ban on gay marriage
amounts to sex discrimination, noted that a colleague cites gay
marriage as an example of how courts cannot counter public opinion:
In both Hawaii and Alaska, he says, judicial moves toward
permitting gay marriage were blocked by popular initiatives in
which nearly two-thirds voted to protect traditional definitions of
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast, he says, he believes the Vermont ruling shows
how litigation can help bring about social change. The court
``understood both its power to reshape culture and its political
limitations,'' he says. ``It did no more than nudge the
Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermont's court told the Legislature that it must either
legalize gay marriage or fully equalize the benefits gay and
heterosexual couples receive. And it retained jurisdiction over the
case to ensure that its order was carried out.
</P>
<P>
   A model often used by gay rights advocates like Evan Wolfson,
head of the national Freedom to Marry Coalition, is the ban on
interracial marriage in the 1960s, which was abolished by judges
even while public opinion polls showed most people still
disapproved of interracial unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have to remember it was the courts that ended race
discrimination in civil marriage, not the people and not the
legislatures first,'' Wolfson said. ``But having said that, I
believe that the polls show, and the growing support shows, that
fair-minded people in this country, the persuadable middle, are
ready to support equality and inclusion for lesbians and gay men if
the legislatures will show some leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of gay marriage disagree that the public is so ready,
and some brand the Vermont decision ``judicial tyranny.'' But they
emphasize that even in such a ``tyrannical'' mode, the courts are
held back by the weight of public opinion and cannot push it too
hard even if they want to.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Sekulow, chief counsel of the conservative American Center
for Law and Justice, pointed out that Vermont's finding that gay
couples were discriminated against could reasonably have led the
justices to rule that gay couples should simply be granted marriage
licenses. But the justices did not, though one dissenting justice
said they should have. Sekulow said, ``You ask yourself, `Gee, why
didn't they issue the marriage license? What stopped them from
taking that step?' They react as if they have a sword of Damocles
over their heads and they don't want to go there.''
</P>
<P>
   That reluctance, he said, stemmed from the awareness that
Vermonters were not ready for gay marriage _ and, according to
public opinion polls, most particularly do not believe that the
decision about gay marriage should be made by the courts rather
than the people or the lawmakers. The ruling, he said, was a
``dodge-the-bullet opinion.'' The Vermont Legislature will convene
next month, and is expected to invite testimony on how to equalize
benefits for homosexual and heterosexual couples.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want to follow the debate over gay marriage should
also keep an eye on Hawaii, where, gay rights advocates say, the
issue of gay partnership is alive despite the state Supreme Court's
recent ruling that the same-sex marriage question was moot because
voters had passed an initiative that favored limiting marriage to
man-woman unions.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii's lawmakers, Wolfson said, will reconvene next month
still facing a court finding similar to Vermont's: homosexual
couples are discriminated against. Its lawmakers thus face a
decision about finding a remedy similar to the one their colleagues
in Vermont must make _ without the option of marriage. The third
place to watch is California, where a major fight over a ballot
initiative is brewing.
</P>
<P>
   The language on the state's Proposition 22, which will be voted
on in March, is quite simple: ``Only marriage between a man and a
woman is valid or recognized in California.''
</P>
<P>
   But gay rights advocates see the initiative as a threat that
goes far beyond marriage, threatening gains in areas like domestic
partner benefits and adoption. Kate Kendell, executive director of
the National Center for Lesbian Rights, said that in contrast to
the progress seen in Vermont, Proposition 22 ``would be the
beginning of rolling back the very basic elementary protections our
families here have been able to achieve in the last two decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Other states may turn into lesser battlegrounds as well,
although no other major marriage lawsuits are pending. Laws against
gay marriage have been passed in 27 states, along with initiatives
in two more. But groups opposed to gay marriage are calling for a
push to get statutes against gay marriage passed in the 20 or so
remaining legislatures in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   One of those groups, the Family Research Council, is also
``urging people to resist sex-partner subsidies at every level,''
said spokesman Robert Knight, referring to domestic partnership
benefits. The council will also be pushing corporations to drop
domestic partner benefits, he said, and lobbying the public against
them as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0797 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-REVIEW-N     12-25 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING MARRIAGE, AN ISSUE REIGNITED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Hawaii, Alaska, Calif.)   (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jw) 
