<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0799 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-MILLENNIUM-TIME-REVIE     12-25 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-TIME-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
 
COUNTING THE YEARS TO MAKE SENSE OUT OF LIFE  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jw) 
 By EVA HOFFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the hype, the panic and the prophecies, the occasion is
real. This New Year's Eve feels different, no matter how arbitrary
the date announcing the new millennium may be. The big round number
about to invade our diaries and our lives has an undeniable
symbolic force.
</P>
<P>
   Is this mere superstition, the kind that stops us from walking
under ladders? Perhaps not entirely, for while our systems for
measuring time may be arbitrary, they are also necessary.
</P>
<P>
   in seemingly infinite time and space, we humans are
mortal and finite, and we cannot get along without borders and
markers to make the world graspable to our minds.
</P>
<P>
   Sigmund Freud famously opined that ``There is no time in the
