<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SKOREA-TENSION-NYT &LR;      12-25 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-TENSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREANS SEE DARK SCENARIO IN A U.S. PRECAUTION _ GAS MASKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Ever since war divided the Korean peninsula
in 1953, residents of this bustling capital city, 30 miles from the
demilitarized zone, have lived with the threat that Communist
troops from North Korea could storm the border at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite doomsday scenarios that North Korea would attack this
city of 10 million people with every imaginable weapon, including
chemical and biological agents, few residents have taken such dire
predictions seriously, and for seemingly good reason.
</P>
<P>
   About half a million South Korean soldiers are guarding the
border, backed up by 37,000 American servicemen and some of the
most sophisticated military technology available. Recently, North
Korea has seemed more interested in diplomacy than making war.
</P>
<P>
   But a decision by the U.S. military in November to distribute
14,000 protective gas masks to dependents of American soldiers and
embassy staff members living in Seoul has raised concerns here that
despite its new diplomatic tone, North Korea is planning a major
assault that will include chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard that the United States was issuing gas
masks to its citizens in Seoul, I was deeply troubled because our
government has no plans to do the same,'' said Lee Shin-Bom,
chairman of the foreign affairs committee of the opposition Grand
National Party. ``I asked myself what does the United States know
that our government isn't telling us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States says that the decision is not tied to
any increased threat or impending attack by North Korea, rumors
have spread across Seoul that an assault is imminent and is likely
to occur sometime near the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid,'' said Kim Yong-Shik, a taxi driver who was
waiting for a fare near the U.S. military base at Yongsan. ``None
of us have gas masks like the Americans. We are like sitting
ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korean and U.S. military intelligence officials said in
recent interviews that North Korea had large stocks of chemical
weapons and missiles and artillery shells to carry those weapons to
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Should chemical warfare be used against an unprotected civilian
population in Seoul, enormous casualties would result, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of North Korea's chemical warfare capability vary
widely. A South Korean defense ministry report issued in October
estimated that North Korea's chemical and biological arsenal was
2,500 to 5,000 tons, including nerve gas, blistering agents and
anthrax. The ministry's latest figures were a fivefold increase
over last year's, which the ministry said were grossly
underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence officials said that equipping the public with
protective masks could reduce the number of civilian casualties and
injuries to about one-tenth.
</P>
<P>
   But very few residents of Seoul own gas masks, and neither the
state nor local governments have plans to distribute them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are recommending that individual citizens purchase their
own gas masks to guard against an attack of chemical and biological
warfare from North Korea,'' said Chun Jung Soo, head of the gas
mask distribution team at Seoul City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't started any massive campaigns yet because this
would obviously lead to a panic among Seoul citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Chun said that although residents could buy gas masks from a
booth at City Hall or at retail outlets for about $25, sales were
low because most Koreans ``don't believe that a war will actually
break out.''
</P>
<P>
   Seoul city government plans to distribute about 1.7 million gas
masks over the next 10 years to civilian defense squad leaders,
volunteers who supervise neighborhood evacuations in the event of
an attack or other emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The city government said that it had distributed about 300,000
masks to defense squad leaders and that recent surveys indicated
that about 200,000 Seoul residents had bought gas masks on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Chun said the city government hoped that the U.S. military's gas
mask program would increase awareness among South Koreans of the
importance of masks.
</P>
<P>
   Col. David R. Apt, public affairs officer for the U.S. Forces
Korea, said that distributing gas masks to dependents of military
personnel was part of the Pentagon's effort to improve protection
of noncombatants stationed overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the ability to provide your dependents with this
protection, you'd be negligent not to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military is issuing M-17A2 masks and hood systems,
which are used by many active duty forces around the world to
protect against chemical warfare. It is the first time that such
protection is being provided for noncombatants in South Korea,
which is a test case for other U.S. military installations.
</P>
<P>
   Apt emphasized that the plan was not related to any specific
event and had been in the works for more than a year. He said that
the United States had deliberately delayed distribution of the
masks until November, when relations between North Korea and the
rest of the world seemed to be improving.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, North Korea has engaged in talks with officials
from the United States, Japan and Europe in what appears to be an
effort to improve its foreign relations, after decades of isolation
and hostility.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo Suk-ryul, a defense expert for the Korea Institute for
Foreign Affairs and National Security, said that North Korea's vast
arsenal of chemical weapons posed a great threat that should not be
underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo said that since foreign governments had already persuaded
North Korea to abandon its nuclear and long-range missile programs
in exchange for concessions, chemical weapons were now likely to
become the major issue in dealing with the Stalinist country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North has plenty of weapons, and if they decided to use
them, many South Korean people would be sacrificed,'' Yoo said.
``The bottom line is that everyone needs to be prepared to use a
gas mask.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
