near several 30-something men in black-tie, who quietly questioned
whether her high cheekbones were real. And Michele Herbert, a Park
Avenue socialite, kissed Basso in gratitude for her $20,000
hand-beaded Russian broadtail suit.
</P>
<P>
   Even Locust Valley, N.Y., the capital of lockjaw and faded
chintz, has lost its bearings. The parking lot of the Piping Rock
Club, once filled with members' 10-year-old ``beater'' paneled
station wagons, now fills up with 3-year-old BMWs instead (and the
children own Porsches).
</P>
<P>
   Is it a new Gilded Age, with many thousands of robber barons,
instead of just a few dozen?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are striking parallels,'' said Jean Strouse, the author
of ``Morgan: American Financier'' (Random House, 1999), who spent
15 years writing and researching the biography of J.P. Morgan
(1837-1913). ``The Internet is very parallel to the building of the
railroads, the telegraph system, the transatlantic cable. People
were buying and building yachts. Enormous floating palaces.
Elaborate houses in Newport. It was an unbelievably lavish time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an unbelievably lavish time now. ``People seem to be
shopping at two in the morning, three in the morning. That's when
they buy the expensive items,'' said James Finkelstein, the founder
of Luxuryfinder.com, an online merchant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sold out of pashmina blankets at $995 apiece,'' he said.
``We sold out of pashmina pillows for $335. We sold a lot of
