<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8834 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MEAT-HACCP-$ADV26-COX     12-25 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-HACCP-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEAT AND POULTRY PLANTS REMAIN OPEN DESPITE HUNDREDS OF FOOD
SAFETY VIOLATIONS
 &HT;    EDS: 980 and add. For release Sunday, Dec. 26
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN and SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, who two years
ago pledged a crackdown on unsanitary meat and poultry processing
facilities, has instead let plants with hundreds of food safety
violations continue to sell their products to the public.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 18, 1998 speech to the families of victims of
food-borne illness, Glickman said the department's new
``science-based'' inspection program would increase food safety. He
also promised to close plants producing ``dirty product.''
</P>
<P>
   On that same day a Cox Newspapers investigation had revealed
that plants were still in full production although they had amassed
over 1,000 ``critical'' food safety violations in a single year.
These violations occurred under the old ``poke and sniff''
inspection system that had been used since the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said in his speech that plants monitored under the
department's new inspection program should not ``expect a thousand
chances to get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   But a new Cox computer analysis of Agriculture Department
records shows the same lack of enforcement under the current
inspection system.
</P>
<P>
   According to inspection reports for 1998, the first year for
which complete data are available under the new inspection system,
several large plants were allowed to process food after collecting
nearly 1,000 citations for food safety violations, called
``non-compliance reports'' under the inspection program.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the 10 plants where the government did act in 1998, over
half the time the facilities were closed for 48 hours or less. The
longest closure lasted 9 days. And records show that when
production resumed, so did the almost-daily violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The records indicate these plants have a severe problem, ``
said Felicia Nestor, food safety director of the Government
Accountability Project, a consumer watchdog group in Washington.
``A plant that on hundreds of occasions failed to meet its (food
safety) commitment does not deserve to ship food to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for Glickman said he was not available for
comment. The department's under secretary for food safety,
Catherine Woteki, also was said to be unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   However, Beth Gaston, a spokesperson for the Agriculture
Department's Food Safety and Inspection Service (FSIS), said the
agency was not deviating from the enforcement policy Glickman
promised in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why plants with hundred of violations were allowed to
operate, Gaston said, ``As a result of a non-compliance report,
plants must take corrective action and inspectors, circuit
supervisors and district managers are trained to look for trends
that would indicate a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaston declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Nestor said there is little need to look for trends when
plants have hundreds of violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we may continue to see trends in food poisoning
tragedies,'' Nestor said, ``before (the Agriculture Department)
notices a trend at these plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the few attempts the department made to halt poorly
performing plants are in doubt following a pivotal case in Texas
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 10, a federal district court judge in Dallas issued a
preliminary injunction stopping the government from shutting down a
plant owned by Supreme Beef Processors Inc. The government said it
consistently found salmonella, a disease-causing bacteria, in meat
at the plant. But Judge A. Joe Fish said meat from the plant had
not caused food poisoning and if the plant was closed, it would put
the company out of business.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge's ruling stands, industry observers say it will gut
the new inspection program.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to 1998, federal food safety inspectors approved meat and
poultry if it looked and smelled OK _ so-called ``poke and sniff''
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   But this changed two years ago when the department ordered the
nation's 300 largest meat and poultry plants to switch to the
inelegantly named Hazard Analysis and Critical Control Points
(HACCP) inspection system. Plants are supposed to develop their own
HACCP plan that monitors key points in the production process.
Things such as the temperature in chilling tanks and bacteria
levels are supposed to be constantly monitored to quickly find and
correct problems.
</P>
<P>
   And federal food safety inspectors who once peered over the
shoulder of workers in the slaughter houses and packing plants, now
monitor how well plants carry out their HACCP plan. If a plant
deviates from its plan, inspectors now file non-compliance reports
called ``NRs.''
</P>
<P>
   A computer analysis of the most serious NRs _ those involving
plant sanitation or their HACCP plan _ show that 66 plants
accounted for over half of all the violations recorded in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A Perdue Farms plant in Lewiston, N.C. amassed the worst record
with 959 NRs. Still, the Agriculture Department never closed the
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Just behind the Perdue plant is one run by Tyson Foods, Inc. in
Dardanelles, Ark., which collected 772 violations. It also was
allowed to operate undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson officials declined to return repeated telephone calls to
discuss problems at their Dardanelles plant. Perdue officials,
however, invited reporters to tour the Lewiston facility and
interview Lester Gray, the plant manager.
</P>
<P>
   Gray acknowledged that his facility had had an ``atrocious''
record in 1998 but blamed it partly on a rocky first year trying to
adjust to the new science-based inspection system. He also said
that because he runs one of the nation's largest processing
facilities, there are more inspectors assigned who are able to
write NRs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Agriculture Department records show that under the old
inspection system his plant had a relatively good record.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock,'' Gray said of the time when he and the other
managers had to begin running their own inspection system rather
than rely on federal inspectors to oversee his operation. Despite
months of planning, he acknowledged that his plant was not ready
for the wrenching changes of HACCP.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we understood our roles, then the implementation
lagged.'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he said the failure of employees to wash their
hands after they returned from breaks or during a change of shifts
resulted in several NRs.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said that prior to HACCP, a federal inspector would only
occasionally check if employees where washing their hands.
</P>
<P>
   But under HACCP, Gray said it became his company's
responsibility to check. His first attempt _ simply urging
employees to wash _ was unsuccessful and resulted in an NR.
Subsequent attempts also failed and resulted in additional NRs.
Finally he solved the problem by stationing someone in front of the
wash basins during all breaks and shift changes.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said the plant is now more accustomed to the new system,
has spent $15 million upgrading its equipment to process carcasses
and NR's have declined by 40 percent in 1999 .
</P>
<P>
   While initial confusion over a new inspection system may have
caused problems, Agriculture Department records show that the Tyson
plant which fared poorly under HACCP was also a problem plant in
pre-HACCP days.
</P>
<P>
   During 1996, the Dardanelles plant was among the ten worst in
the county with 922 ``critical'' violations _ the most serious type
of citation a plant can get.
</P>
<P>
   Problems at the Dardanelles plant mirror the company's record of
failed inspections nationally. Although Tyson ranks fourth in sales
among the nation's meat and poultry companies, it led the industry
both before and after HACCP in the number of federal food safety
violations. In 1998, government records show Tyson's plants using
HACCP had 7,560 NRs for sanitation and food safety problems _ more
than double any other company that year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the company's performance, Agriculture Department
records show the government only shut down two of Tyson's 78 plants
in 1998, and then only for a total of 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's poultry processing plant in Waldron, Ark., which led the
country in critical violations in 1996, was in trouble again in
1998, records show. The plant was closed once in January 1998 for
48 hours and again in April for five days. At the time it closed in
April, the government had cited it 38 times that month. When it
reopened, federal records show it continued to collect nearly one
violation every day for the rest of the year. The plant continues
to operate today.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
