<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-POPE-CHRISTMAS-NYT &LR;      12-25 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-CHRISTMAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPE URGES REPENTANCE AND MUTUAL RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ On the first day of the 2000 holy year, Pope John Paul II
delivered a Christmas speech Saturday that called for repentance in
the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must, however, confess that humanity has sometimes sought
the truth elsewhere, invented false certainties, and chased after
deceptive ideologies,'' the pope said in his traditional Christmas
urbi et orbi (to the city and the world) address from his balcony
at St. Peter's Basilica. ``At times people have refused to respect
and love their brothers of a different faith or race, they have
denied fundamental rights to individuals and nations.''
</P>
<P>
   The frail 79-year-old pope, who on Christmas Eve pushed open the
holy door to St. Peter's, the symbol of the beginning of a holy
year, or jubilee, has long urged his followers to use the
millennium jubilee to redress personal wrongs and the misdeeds of
the Roman Catholic Church throughout the centuries. Saturday's
words served as a prelude for the kind of soul-searching in which
he intends to lead the church throughout the year 2000. He said
believers should be ``pilgrims in time,'' and remember the horrors
of the past. ``We visit all the places of grief and war, the
resting places of victims of brutal conflicts and cruel
slaughter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas is one of the most sacred events on the Christian
calendar, and for John Paul II, this year has a special
significance, as it marks what the church views as the 2,000th
anniversary of the birth of Jesus Christ and the start of a holy
year that is the first one at the turn of a millennium. ``This year
there is yet another reason that makes more holy this day of
grace,'' the pope said. ``It is the beginning of the great
jubilee.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of believers gathered in St. Peter's Square
clapped and cheered their approval. All morning, thousands of
believers passed through the bronze holy door that is kept bricked
up until a jubilee, many of them making signs of the cross and
kissing the sculpted panels.
</P>
<P>
   A jubilee, which now takes place every 25 years, is a tradition
that dates back to 1300, when Pope Boniface VIII urged pilgrims to
visit Rome when the Crusades made traveling to the Holy Land too
dangerous. Now, as then, believers make the pilgrimage to seek a
plenary indulgence, a remittance of punishment for sins, which can
be earned by a pilgrimage to Rome or other holy sites. The pope has
broadened the avenue to an indulgence, allowing believers to visit
Jerusalem churches, their own dioceses and even the Rome airport
chapel.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, after his speech, the pope delivered a Christmas
greeting in 58 languages, as he does every Dec. 25. He then blessed
the crowd and granted them _ and those who followed the event on
television and radio _ a plenary indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past three years, the aging pope did not celebrate
Christmas Mass inside the basilica, leaving that task to Cardinal
Angelo Sodano, his secretary of state. But to emphasize the special
nature of this Holy Year, the pope broke with tradition and decided
to open the holy doors of the four main basilicas in Rome
personally. Saturday evening, the pope was expected to open the
holy door of St. John Lateran, the original church of the popes
before St. Peter's was built. He will open the doors at the other
two basilicas in January.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday night, the pope needed help climbing the steps to the
holy door, but by the end of the midnight Mass, he was clearly
invigorated. As he walked down the aisle to leave, he smiled,
stroked the heads of small children, and blessed the faithful who
grabbed at his sleeve and touched his robe. At one point, he
playfully snatched back his hand from the outstretched hand of one
person in the aisle, smiling mischievously.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the pope sounded a more somber note, lamenting in
strong words the arms race, abortion and euthanasia. ``At times,
the world neither respects nor loves life,'' he said, asking that
God enlighten people ``so that legislators and political leaders,
men and women, of goodwill, may be committed to welcoming human
life as a precious gift.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas celebrations were a personal milestone for this
pope, who has been planning the 2000 holy year ever since he was
elected in 1978. At times, through sheer willpower, he has overcome
his numerous physical ailments to press an agenda that would
exhaust a far younger, healthier man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christ, you are the door,'' the pope said in closing his
remarks on Friday night. ``Through you, in the power of the Holy
Spirit, we wish to enter the third millennium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
