<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8837 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-650&AMP;A     12-25 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S ARMY OPENS FIGHT TO CONTROL CHECHEN CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian forces advanced into Grozny on Saturday, as
what was billed as the decisive battle for the capital of Chechnya
got under way.
</P>
<P>
   After a night of furious shelling, Russian Interior Ministry
troops and Chechen forces loyal to Moscow began to move into the
city from several directions, according to Russian news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's immediate goal is to establish control over key
junctions in the city and to prevent the militants from moving
freely within the town. The longer-term objective is to use
Russia's overwhelming advantage in firepower and take the city back
neighborhood by neighborhood in what promises to be a new, intense
stage of the 3-month-old war.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Russian soldiers died in street battles in Grozny
in the 1994-96 war in Chechnya. Russia has vowed not to repeat the
mistakes of that war, in which Russian soldiers rushed to the
center of Grozny at the outset of the fighting. That war left the
status of the officially Russian republic in limbo, with Islamic
militants determined to fight for Chechnya's independence.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the military says it will move more cautiously to
take back the city and flush out the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night there were reports of firefights at key
intersections and highways, including points deep inside the city.
Grozny was said to be under heavy shelling from Russian tanks and
artillery, as Russian troops advanced under smoke screens.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the information about the assault came from the Russian
military or officials, or semiofficial Russian news media. Very few
Western reporters have permission to visit Chechnya, and the
Foreign Ministry warned Saturday that any foreign reporters caught
in the region without permission would be committing a criminal
offense.
</P>
<P>
   There were no official casualty figures from the fighting
Saturday. In general, the Russian government has sought to reassure
its public during this war by avoiding mention of military
casualties in any detail and by portraying the assault on Grozny as
a commando-style operation that will avoid the huge death toll of
the last war among both military troops and civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military leaders insist their troops are not
``storming'' the city. Rather, they say, Russian forces are
engaging in a ``special operation'' to rid it of rebels who are
blamed for incursions into Chechnya's eastern neighbor, the Russian
republic of Dagestan, in August and then for a series of apartment
bombings that killed almost 300 people in Dagestan and in Russia
proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing terrible is going on in Grozny,'' said Gen. Viktor
Kazantsev, Russia's top military commander in the North Caucasus.
``It is simply the continuation of the operation to free Grozny
from the bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   That distinction, however, may be lost on the tens of thousands
of civilians still trapped in the city. They have already been
pummeled by artillery and airstrikes. Now they are hiding in dark
cellars and basements, hoping to survive the fight on the streets
of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how much the military leaders want it, they won't
capture Grozny by New Year's,'' said Malik Saidullayev, a
millionaire Chechen businessman who is supporting the Kremlin in
the war. ``Both the federal forces and their opponents, along with
civilians, are likely to suffer many casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   Escape no longer appears to be an option for Grozny's civilians.
With much fanfare this month, Russia had opened what it said were
two corridors for civilians to leave Grozny. But the senior
official for Chechnya, Nikolai Koshman, advised civilians on Friday
that it had become too dangerous to try to leave.
</P>
<P>
   He said that up to 50,000 people were still trapped in Grozny
and that only 8,000 had used the corridors to flee. Many of those
who did reported that they were shot at by unidentified gunmen as
they traveled the perilous route.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The onset of Saturday's attack coincided with efforts by the
Russian government to limit information from the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Most accounts of the fighting Saturday took the form of
semiofficial reports on Russian television, which has been
generally sympathetic to the Russian military, and dispatches by
semiofficial Russian news agencies, like Itar-Tass.
</P>
<P>
   Television footage showed columns of Russian troops, commanders
and occasional artillery, but little of the intense fighting said
to be raging on the outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   In warning foreign journalists not to enter Chechnya without
official permission, the Russian Foreign Ministry said in a
statement: ``In some instances, foreign citizens have intentionally
lied about their goals and routes of their visit. They turn up in
Chechnya and practice journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   To the consternation of Moscow, a small vanguard of news service
reporters is already inside Grozny and has been operating beyond
the military's jurisdiction. They have been quoting Chechen
commanders about Russian losses and have been roundly denounced by
Russian spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to put the best face on the fighting, the Russian
military said Saturday that it was carrying out a three-phase
operation to capture the city with minimal losses.
</P>
<P>
   The operation began at midnight Friday, and the first two phases
are already under way, the military said. The first phase involves
intense shelling to weaken the resistance of the rebels in Grozny.
Then Russian Interior Ministry troops, military reconnaissance
units and several hundred Chechen soldiers loyal to Bislan
Gantamirov, the former Grozny mayor, began to enter the city, the
military said.
</P>
<P>
   Gantamirov had been imprisoned for embezzlement but was released
by Russian authorities eager to find allies _ however tainted _
among the Chechens, who have a long history of seeking independence
from Moscow and, like many minority groups in the now defunct
Soviet Union, suffered mass deportation under Stalin.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials told Itar-Tass that the city was to
be divided into 15 areas. The Interior Ministry troops and
Gantamirov's troops would control key junctions, hoping to prevent
the militants from moving freely within the city.
</P>
<P>
   The final phase is the destruction of the rebels in
house-to-house fighting. That is unlikely to happen quickly.
State-owned ORT television said the military hoped to break the
main rebel resistance by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But some Russian military officials said Saturday that clearing
the city of militants could take two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The military has apparently abandoned any plan to evacuate the
city, opting instead for what it says is a plan to create safe
havens for civilians in parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how many armed rebels remain in the city.
Russian officials say there may be as many as 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Movladi Udugov, who has been a spokesman for the rebels,
asserted that there was heavy fighting within the capital and that
Russian troops would run into a wall of resistance as they sought
to take Grozny. Key militants, like Shamil Basayev, however, no
longer appear to be in the capital. When he called reporters
Saturday, Udugov would not say where he was calling from.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
