<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FORGOTTEN-HEROES-NYT &LR;      12-25 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORGOTTEN-HEROES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEWHERE THERE'S A HALL FOR EVERYONE, AND WITH VISITORS, TOO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., R.I., Hawaii, N.J., Calif., Miss., Alaska, Va.)   By VINCENT M. MALLOZZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cooperstown, Canton, Springfield, Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   While many sports fans have been heading to the Baseball, Pro
Football, Basketball and Hockey Halls of Fame for decades, few have
ventured to pay homage to lesser-known heroes from other playing
fields around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   But just like the Bambino, Dr. J and the Great One, the best
athletes you never heard of are celebrated daily at their own
permanent residences. They simply don't hear the doorbell ring as
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people at every level of sport with a passion,''
said Paul Dickson, who wrote ``The Volvo Guide to Halls of Fame''
(Living Planet Press) with Robert Skole in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's most engaging about many lesser-known halls
is that they don't have all the bells and whistles and all the
interactive stuff that the better-known halls have,'' Dickson said.
``And while most of them are hanging on by a thread financially,
they exist simply because someone out there has a passion for that
particular sport.''
</P>
<P>
   So if you and the children happen to be sledding in Knik,
Alaska, any time soon, the Dog Mushers Hall of Fame, located in a
town where dogs outnumber people, might be worth a visit. For $2,
the museum, which is on the route of the 1,150-mile Iditarod Trail
Sled Dog Race from Anchorage to Nome, showcases not only the
world's greatest mushers, but also their sleds and other
musher-related items as well.
</P>
<P>
   One enshrined sled is from a trip to the top of Mount McKinley,
while another is from a 6,000-mile trek. One Hall of Famer, Col.
Norman Vaughn, went to the South Pole with Adm. Richard Byrd and
donated material from the expedition, including an old dog-style
collar.
</P>
<P>
   You won't need that sled to get to the National Jousting Hall of
Fame in Mount Solon, Va., which puts no price at all on seeing its
display of trophies, plaques, photographs and jousting rings.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the ``oldest continually held sporting event in
America,'' jousting made its debut on this side of the Atlantic in
1821, when, according to the local folklore, two young men on
horseback fought for the hand of a maiden by jousting, or trying to
kill each other with lances. Toned down for a much more amateur
field today, the idea now is not to plunge one's lance through
another's heart, but through small rings hanging on a string.
</P>
<P>
   When the door to the Greyhound Hall of Fame in Abilene, Kan.,
swings open, you are greeted by a couple of former greyhound racing
champions, Sharon and her sister, Chig. For the price of a pat on
their heads, you will quickly learn that greyhound racing is
America's sixth-largest spectator sport and that the breed is one
of the oldest and most respected in the canine world. In fact, back
in the 1500s, Queen Elizabeth I inaugurated the Sport of Queens by
initiating the formal rules of greyhound coursing, the pursuit of
hares.
</P>
<P>
   The price of fame is a little higher in Newport, R.I., where for
$6 you can visit the National Croquet Gallery, Hall of Fame and
Archives. On display is a 7-foot Grand Trophy with the names of the
sport's most notable performers, including the legendary comedian
Harpo Marx. Also on display are croquet-related works of art by
Monet, Bonnard, Winslow Homer and Rockwell Kent.
</P>
<P>
   If your passion is racing on wheels, find a parking spot in
Akron, Ohio, home of the Soap Box Derby Hall of Fame, where
legendary soap boxers are honored and vehicles are on display
during the one-week racing season in July. One of the most famous
inductees is a racer named Gilbert Klecan, the 1946 Soap Box Derby
champion, who covered himself with graphite in an effort to
increase his speed.
</P>
<P>
   If fish should become a part of your hall of fame diet, dive
into the memorabilia at the International Game Fish Association's
Museum World Center Fishing Museum and Hall of Fame in Dania Beach,
Fla., which, believe it or not, takes longer to tour than to
pronounce. This $20 million museum honors anglers, captains and
other leaders of the fishing business.
</P>
<P>
   The Ironman Hall of Fame in Kailua-Kona, Hawaii, does not hang
portraits of Lou Gehrig or Cal Ripken Jr., but of triathletes like
Tom Warren, Mark Allen and Paula Newby-Fraser, all of whom have
conquered the physically challenging Ironman race: a 2.4-mile ocean
swim, followed by a 112-mile bike ride, followed by a 26.2-mile
run, followed by a shower and a lot of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, for those who prefer their sports a little more
recreational, admission is free to the National Shuffleboard Hall
of Fame in St. Petersburg, Fla.; the United States Chess Federation
Hall of Fame in Washington; the International Checkers Hall of Fame
in Petal, Miss.; the Marbles Hall of Fame in Wildwood, N.J.; and,
soon to be in the loop, the Yo-Yo Hall of Fame in Chico, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a democracy where everyone is created equally, there are
people within their own realm who become great at certain sports,''
Dickson said. ``Whether it be professional baseball or basketball,
or marbles or chess, there should be a place to honor all of those
people.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
