<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8849 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CHANCELLOR-ASSESS-     12-25 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHANCELLOR-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DAUNTING JOB NOBODY CAN FILL FOR LONG: NEW YORK'S SCHOOL
CHANCELLOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., Mass., Ill., Calif., Ore.)  By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As New York City seeks its 12th schools chancellor in
20 years, one question seems inescapable: Can anybody do this job?
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Crew passed landmark governance changes, set up a
summer-school system to end automatic promotion of students, and
helped end principals' tenure, but his bid for a longer contract
was foiled, it seems, by politics and his own indecision. His
predecessor, Ramon C. Cortines, was beloved by school officials but
run out of town over squabbles with the mayor. Before that, Joseph
A. Fernandez, who had tackled corruption in community districts,
was tossed aside after a fight with an irate Board of Education
over instruction on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, one chancellor quit amid financial scandal and
another died in office of a massive asthma attack. The last person
to resign the post voluntarily, Frank J. Macchiarola, left in 1983,
before nearly all of today's schoolchildren were born.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something inherent in the system that makes it
impossible,'' said Joseph P. Viteritti, a special assistant to
Macchiarola who has advised most of the chancellors since that term
and wrote a book on New York school politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're going to start the next search for a miracle
worker,'' Viteritti said with a sigh. ``What we should be doing is
trying to figure out how to make the system more manageable, so we
can get a talented but normal person to run the school system, so
you're not looking for someone who is a combination of Mother
Teresa and Superman.''
</P>
<P>
   With 1.1 million students and 75,000 teachers in 1,100 schools _
not to mention 3,681 people in the central office and an $11
billion budget _ many people think New York's school system is too
vast for one person to run. Others fault the byzantine governance
structure, in which the mayor controls the purse strings, six
politicians appoint the seven-member Board of Education (which
hires and fires the chancellor), and 32 separate elected school
boards have primary control over elementary and middle schools.
</P>
<P>
   Some say the polyglot challenges of urban education, in schools
overflowing with the children of immigrants and the impoverished,
can themselves be overwhelming, and that the public's passionate
interest in educational issues makes things only more difficult. Or
that leading the nation's largest school system requires more
money.
</P>
<P>
   In part, New York's inability to keep a chancellor reflects a
growing crisis around the country, with the tenure of leaders in
large urban school systems averaging just 2.5 years. (Crew lasted
more than four.) As Chicago, Boston and other cities nationwide
overhaul their school systems to give more control to City Hall _
and places like San Diego, Seattle and Washington hand the reins to
noneducators with military or legal backgrounds _ many in New York
are challenging the current setup, which was put in place 100 years
ago to shield the schools from politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job was devised in the factory age of one wise man at the
top of the pyramid,'' said Diane Ravitch, a New York University
professor who has written a history of the system. ``No modern
organization functions this way. We need a chancellor who's going
to take the lead in changing the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, some experts denounce as preposterous the notion that
the chancellorship is impossible, and point to Crew's
accomplishments in his first three years on the job as proof.
Considering the frequent turnover of mayors and school board
members _ who understandably want to pick their own school chiefs _
perhaps a longer term is unrealistic, they say.
</P>
<P>
   But in that case, even leaders who are successful at first, like
Crew, end up being perceived as failures when they depart, leaving
a trail of turmoil around the chancellor's office. The constant
turnover means frequent changes in strategy for improving skills in
reading and math. With such a short shelf life, how can significant
reform ever stick?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a constant churning,'' said Michael Usdan, president of
the Institute for Educational Leadership in Washington. ``You're
always picking up the seedlings by their roots, and nobody wins.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent national survey of 1,719 school superintendents showed
that 92 percent were worried that ``high turnover in the
superintendency means a serious crisis in keeping strong leaders in
the position.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 18 percent of current superintendents said they would be
interested in running a large urban system; the average tenure at
the helm of school districts overall is 7.25 years, nearly three
times as long as in big cities.
</P>
<P>
   New York, though, is the ``big-city phenomenon, cubed,'' said
James W. Guthrie, an expert in school governance who runs the
Peabody Center for Education Policy at Vanderbilt University. The
distance between the chancellor and the children is too vast,
Guthrie said; he suggested power be returned to local schools and
districts, but warned that such a move would inevitably lead to
more patronage and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a New York chancellor were to visit two schools every
day, it would take three years _ longer than most people last in
the job _ to hit them all. Carol Gresser, a candidate for borough
president of Queens who sat on the Board of Education from 1990 to
1998, said that breakup was the only answer. Staten Island and
Brooklyn have different problems, she said, and need different
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have different entities in each borough for various
things,'' like district attorneys, Ms. Gresser said, suggesting a
similar boroughwide system for schools.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who believe that the system's size is manageable say
the political structure is daunting.
</P>
<P>
   There is the meddling of the mayor, who controls two votes on
the Board of Education as well as the budget, and has a bully
pulpit always available for criticism. Then there are the
personalities of the other five board members and the borough
presidents who appoint them, all of whom are often trying to climb
to higher office. There are also the state legislature, powerful
employee unions and special-interest groups like parents to contend
with.
</P>
<P>
   To offset the authority handed to the 32 local school boards in
1969 _ much of which was undone by a 1997 law for which Crew
lobbied _ chancellors over the years have also built up rolls of
red tape at the headquarters on Livingston Street in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of those good people who are supposedly interested in
reform want major improvements, but they don't want to get behind
major structural changes,'' said Stanley S. Litow, who ran two
chancellor search committees in the 1980's and became Fernandez's
deputy. ``Then the schools chancellors, all of them flawed in some
fashion, stumble, and when they stumble, begin to start looking
more vulnerable. Then that vulnerability allows them to be
subjected to a set of events that ultimately leads to them no
longer having the ability to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So, for Fernandez, the enemies he had made attacking local
principals and superintendents helped to engineer his ouster when
the board balked at his push for AIDS education. With Crew, a
months-old fight with Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani over vouchers
fanned the flames of mini-scandals over cheating, attendance and
test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, most school systems were carved away from City Hall
at the turn of the century, in an effort to shield education from
politics. But politics crept back in through the school boards,
which are lesser known and thus less accountable than mayors. In
recent years, several big-city mayors have tried to wrest control
of those independent school systems, to mollify constituents who
are increasingly worried about the failures of education.
</P>
<P>
   The model, for many experts, is Chicago, where the mayor took
over in 1995, replaced the elected school board with appointees and
named Paul G. Vallas the chief executive. Vallas ousted scores of
entrenched bureaucrats and remade the structure to resemble a
corporation; test scores have begun to climb out of a deep hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really cannot have educators run major school systems,''
said Vallas, who was a teacher for several years before working in
the state legislature and city government. ``They're simply not
trained.''
</P>
<P>
   Vallas said it was crucial to find someone local, who knows the
political terrain and has experience in government finance. Like
the former United States attorney now running the schools in San
Diego, Vallas has a chief educational officer who handles all
instructional issues _ but none of the operational or budget
matters that often bog down other superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   Also essential, Vallas said, is the united political front,
which leaves little room for critics to block change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are they going to go to, the board?'' he asked. ``The
board is there to back me. They going to go to the mayor? I'm the
mayor's guy. We refer to it as the Holy Trinity.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Peterkin, director of a doctoral program at Harvard
University that trains urban school superintendents, said he was
befuddled as to why mayoral involvement in other cities had led to
greater stability, whereas in New York, ``it continues to go in a
destructive way for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New York has had in the last seven years two of the finest
chancellors in the United States,'' he said, about Cortines and
Crew, ``yet they have found a way to make these people unwelcome in
the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Feldman, president of the American Federation of
Teachers, is one of many people fretting that the city will soon be
plunged into yet another political battle over school leadership _
and perhaps a larger debate over governance _ just as
standards-based change is beginning to take root. The timing is
particularly bad because the next chancellor will be picked, in
part, by a mayor who may leave office in a year, depending on the
outcome of his likely Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not very pretty and certainly they're a terrible
diversion from what needs to be going on in the schools,'' Ms.
Feldman said of the frequent chancellor searches. ``I just worry
that you then get into a whole discussion about governance, and
you're distracted from education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
