<SLUG> BC-ROMANIA-RACEANU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFE IN U.S., EX-ENVOY IS HAUNTED BY ROMANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID BINDER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Dec. 23, 1989, at the height of Romania's
blood-soaked revolution, Mircea Raceanu, a diplomat condemned to
death as an American spy, was released under an amnesty as the last
political prisoner of the expiring Communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   He weighed 121 pounds on leaving Bucharest's Rahova Prison, down
46 from his normal weight.
</P>
<P>
   A decade and several governments later, he again finds himself
under a death sentence in Bucharest, despite the amnesty _ although
he is safe in a Washington suburb, an American citizen since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   His sentence was reaffirmed by the Romanian government on June
11, a day after a group of Romanian intellectuals sent a memorandum
to that country's attorney general asking that the sentence be
overturned because Raceanu was ``a committed anti-Communist
fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   But the deputy attorney general declared on national television
that it was ``impossible to rehabilitate Mircea Raceanu.''
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty had been commuted under the Communists to 20
years in prison, but it is not clear whether that commutation
stands.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has asked Romania to clarify the case, a State
Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   Romania has indicated that a response might be provided next
month. A spokesman for the Romanian Embassy here said it had also
sent a query to Bucharest and would respond when an answer came
back.
</P>
<P>
   Now 64, Raceanu was apprehended on a Bucharest street in January
1989 by officers of the state political police, Securitate, as he
was carrying two confidential documents to a reception at the
American ambassador's residence. One document dealt with the
Communist military alliance, the Warsaw Pact, the other with plans
by some journalists for an underground newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He pleaded guilty almost immediately because he was privy to
plans by Grigore Raceanu, his stepfather, and five other longtime
Communists, to distribute a letter protesting the repressive
policies of the Ceausescu regime. He wanted to keep knowledge of
the letter to himself. ``I wanted to protect my stepfather,'' he
recalled. ``So I said, `Okay, I'm a spy.'''
</P>
<P>
   His confession, together with the documents _ which he said were
minimal in the category of state secrets _ constituted the only
evidence for his treason trial.
</P>
<P>
   After threats to his life in the spring of 1990 he sought asylum
in the United States. He is completing a memoir about his
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Raceanu and his friends say they are perplexed by the
reaffirmation of his death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Kirk, who was the American ambassador in Bucharest in the
last years of the Ceausescu dictatorship, said: ``Mircea is a man
whom I knew well who was committed to a free and democratic Romania
and worked to that end even under the Ceausescu regime, and it is a
surprise to me that a government that is committed to those same
ideals should reconstitute and restate a sentence against him. It
seems very much at odds with the ideals that government
professes.''
</P>
<P>
   Raceanu said that ``by embracing without reservation the
conclusion of the Ceausescu regime that I am guilty the present
authorities show the same old mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was an adversary of the totalitarian regime,'' he continued.
``And if they say now that I am guilty then they are saying that
the Communist regime in Romania was right and it was wrong to fight
against it. The spirit of the Securitate still dominates Romanian
society, although the Democratic coalition came to power in
November 1996 under the slogan of breaking radically with the
Communist past. Unfortunately that did not happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
