u w BC-DEFENSE-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      12-25 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFENSE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CALL TO STICK TO THE BUDGET RILES SOME IN THE MILITARY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Flush with this year's first real growth in
military spending in more than a decade, Defense Secretary William
S. Cohen has quietly told all the services that in drawing up this
coming year's spending plan they must live within the limits
imposed in the current budget of more than $285 billion and not
expect additional increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a tacit agreement we would live within the
increases,'' said Kenneth Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The new budget, which will be submitted to Congress in February,
includes $60 billion to buy new weapons systems, a goal long sought
by the Joint Chiefs of Staff, as well as last-minute help from the
White House to cover fuel bills and other expenses that were higher
than expected. But for the last two weeks, the services have been
complaining behind the scenes that some of their pet projects could
be in jeopardy without more money.
</P>
<P>
   Those complaints are especially vexing to the Pentagon's top
officials who feel the Navy, Air Force and Army could be more
gracious in victory. President Clinton and Congress this year
approved a five-year, $112 billion increase, making the military
the biggest beneficiary of the budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done very well the last two years _ it's a real success
story,'' said a senior military official overseeing the budget.
``We are very pleased we're able to modernize.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has already announced that it will need an
additional $2.2 billion over the next five years for the national
missile defense system under development, an increase of nearly 20
percent, but that will have to come out of the next year's budget.
Next summer, Clinton will decide whether to deploy the system,
designed to guard against errant missiles from countries like North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Pentagon officials acknowledge that the Army is wrestling
with how to fit its new vision of creating a lighter, more mobile
Army into existing weapons programs. At least one of those
projects, most likely the Crusader artillery system, will have to
be eliminated, a senior Pentagon official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is great controversy and great confusion in the Army
over the budget,'' the official said. ``The Crusader is one of the
programs contingent on remaining where the Army is and not where it
wants to go.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Navy officials say Congress might well put more
money into their shipbuilding program.
</P>
<P>
   The new budget also includes a new program to improve military
housing bases, another in a string of projects to make military
life more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have, I think, an important initiative that will be
included in the budget,'' Cohen said last week. ``We are going to
focus on getting adequate housing for folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's package of housing programs, which he will announce in
January, will include fixing up or replacing some of the 200,000
housing units the Defense Department says are in need of major
repairs, and help with the cost of housing not on military bases,
said senior officials who refused to give further details.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting remains one of the military's most serious problems.
Last year Congress approved a 4.8 percent pay increase and a change
in retirement pay as part of an effort to win new recruits and
persuade those already in the service to stay. But for the second
year in a row, the Army fell short of its recruitment goal. The Air
Force and the Navy also struggled to meet their goals, despite new
advertising and inducements.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cohen argues that the Pentagon should be pleased with its
new largess, the leading Republican presidential candidates are
saying that even with the increase, the American military is
woefully underfinanced. Even though the military budget is at a
record high, it represents a smaller portion of the gross national
product than at any time since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   One candidate, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, a highly decorated
veteran and former prisoner of war, has routinely derided the
military for paying such low salaries that record numbers of
service members have to rely on food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 12,000 enlisted personnel _ proud young men and
women _ whose low pay has left them with no choice but to accept
food stamps to feed their families,'' McCain said in a recent
speech. ``Substandard housing for military personnel is now
commonplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Both McCain and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican
front-runner, have called for a complete transformation of the
military to meet the demands of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he would add $5 billion to the annual military
budget to give the armed forces another pay increase and to pay
research costs to develop new, modern weapons systems that would
``skip a generation of technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Those campaign pledges have prompted new calls for an increase
in the Pentagon budget even though Clinton effectively reversed
directions last year with his $12 billion increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, the procurement budget should be at $80
billion, not $60 billion,'' said Michael O'Hanlon of the Brookings
Institution. ``The military's problem is very serious. Everything
is wearing out and now they have to replace it.''
</P>
<P>
   The public pressure from the Republican candidates also appears
to have helped persuade the White House to pay some of the
military's outstanding bills. The debate now is over how to spend
the money. This year Congress delayed production of the F-22
fighter jet because of serious cost overruns. In this year's
budget, the Air Force has financed its major modern weapons
programs mindful of the congressional complaints, an official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
