<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: THIS YEAR, SPORTS WENT OVER THE EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something broke this year in sports, but it may not be until
next year or even well into next century before we figure out
exactly what it was and whether it can or should be repaired. It
felt more like the gradual crumbling of a bridge than the snap of
an elevator cable, but the drop was profound and unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   It was as obvious as the snowballs some Denver fans threw at
football players on the field, and as concealed as the batteries
inside those snowballs. Who had changed first, the players or the
fans? Is cause and effect ever that simple?
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it should have been easy to predict that a season
in which Latrell Sprewell replaced Michael Jordan as the signifying
sport's signifying athlete would offer widespread change and
challenge. Not that we can blame either man.
</P>
<P>
   Did Jordan or Sprewell order the umpires to lose their jobs?
Bribe a single Olympic decision-maker? Push Muhammad Ali's daughter
into the ring? And neither of them has ever been found guilty of
the routine transgressions of jock culture _ beating up women, drug
and alcohol abuse, illegal gambling. In fact, beating up women
seems to have become such a routine news event that there is even a
Web site devoted to listing male athletes and coaches who have been
accused of abusing women.
</P>
<P>
   But the transition from the cool, corporate, distanced Michael
to the overheated, individualistic, erratic Spree seemed to
indicate that the center was no longer holding, that sports was
balkanizing, spinning out of control into what will be some new
configuration, less like the vicious socialism of the National
Football League and more like the friendly fascism of pro
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   And what have we learned? If Michael was aberrational, a
one-of-a-kind logo for globalization, does this mean that shoes as
self-expression is over? That's good. There is something pathetic
about the swoosh as self. But does that mean you have to choke your
coach to get our attention? How good do you have to be to actually
injure your coach and still return to the game? Was Michael
important enough to kill his coach and come back?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we also missed an opportunity here to look into
coach-player dynamics; just how emotionally abusive a coach was
P.J. Carlesimo? He always seemed a far more dangerous role model
than Sprewell. Even an obscure coach can salvage or wreck a hundred
lives. Most athletes tend to affect only themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Especially with Jordan gone, it was easy for Muhammad Ali to
emerge this year as the consensus athlete of the century. The pick
that would have seemed breathtakingly radical when he actually was
the world's most famous person now seems a safe bet.
</P>
<P>
   Never as economically important as Jordan and once considered
far more of a moral danger than Sprewell, Ali has been tamed by
disease and new times. He seems to be celebrated mostly for his
nostalgia value rather than his long-gone power to shake up the
world.
</P>
<P>
   While Jordan and Babe Ruth were probably his closest rivals, a
very strong case for the century's MVP could be made for Billie
Jean King. Her impact on sports _ think women, promotion, populism
and professionalism _ has been enormous and unique.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Billie Jean will have to take some indirect blame for
the ring career of Laila Ali. What's that about? Is she hyping a
modeling career, following Dad, integrating a sport, satisfying a
blood lust? Why does women's boxing seem like something that should
be on a jock porn site?
</P>
<P>
   It's one of those can-it-or-should-it-be-repaired questions. But
we'll be asked: How can we ban boxing now that it would be unfair
to women as well as poor boys? Or at least until Mike Tyson gets a
chance to finish his slow-motion public suicide.
</P>
<P>
   What feels so profound and unsettling about that is the
willingness of so many promoters, television executives,
commentators, fans, to go along with it, freely admitting that
Tyson is necessary for the box office. Implicit is that as soon as
he is replaced _ with a pugilistic version of pro wrestling _ he
will be dumped to destroy himself in private.
</P>
<P>
   Every season we have to remind ourselves that all this is
important because sports holds the promise of renewal and
inspiration. The bridge crumbles, we learn to swim the river, the
elevator cable snaps, we get in shape by walking the stairs. Just
as long as we weren't on the bridge or elevator when it broke.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong's victory in the Tour de France was my pick for
best moment in sports this year. Lance, whom I've never met, shares
a type of cancer with me. When he won, I went out and bought a
bicycle. I have so far made my way up to a 35-mile trip. That's not
symbolic. What is symbolic is that, on the eve of a new time,
sports can give me the power to believe I have just begun to pedal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1335EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
