<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EPA-COAL-POWER-1160(2     12-25 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-COAL-POWER-1160(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD PLANTS WITH NEW PARTS PRESENT PROBLEM TO EPA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., Wis.)  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, W.Va. _ In the roaring hot interior of the Philip
Sporn electric plant, giant pulverizers work around the clock to
reduce coal to the consistency of talcum powder. Howling fans then
blow it into giant boilers.
</P>
<P>
   Every second that the plant operates, it grinds and burns 200
pounds of coal. Every second, it produces enough energy to run a
medium-sized city.
</P>
<P>
   To its owner, American Electric Power Corp., Sporn is an
engineering marvel, the first coal plant in the world to produce a
kilowatt-hour of power with less than 10,000 BTUs, which is well
under a pound of the coal it uses. This level of efficiency is far
better than the industry average.
</P>
<P>
   To the Environmental Protection Agency, the problem is that
Sporn set that standard 50 years ago. The plant, environmental
regulators say, is a relic of the era when the symbol of prosperity
was a smokestack spewing a fat black plume; now, they say, it is
time to clean up or shut down.
</P>
<P>
   But Sporn and plants like it are, for now at least, doing
neither. Entering what might have been their twilight years, they
are producing more electricity than ever by running for more hours
every year, as utility deregulation promotes shipment of their
cheap electricity over increasingly long distances, from the banks
of the Ohio River here to the big load centers of the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   And if their owners have their way, plants like this may be
nearly eternal. Rather than being replaced by new generating
stations with younger technology, Sporn may be an example of the
past replacing the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lifetime is 35, 40 or 45 years on many components, but not
all components,'' said Mark Gray, manager of American Electric
Power's environmental services division, during a recent tour of
the plant. ``Some may have an expected design life of 10 years or
15 years,'' he said, but some major parts, with proper painting and
cleaning, will endure ``for centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   And the end of a component's life does not mean the end of a
plant's, he said; it just means time for replacement, and then a
plant can run like new for years.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA emphatically disagrees. ``If you want to treat it as a
newish unit, you should have newish controls,'' Sylvia Lowrance,
the agency's principal deputy assistant administrator, said in an
interview in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Sporn is one of the coal-fired plants cited by the EPA in a suit
filed last month against seven utilities that are charged with
violating the Clean Air Act, in what the agency says is one of the
largest investigations in its history.
</P>
<P>
   When the act was passed in 1970, it set strict emissions limits
for new plants and looser ones for those already running, as long
as no modifications were made. At Sporn and 23 other plants, the
agency alleges, utility companies have quietly rebuilt, bit by bit,
and the plants have lost their grandfathered status.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, many people say they never foresaw the idea of a
50-year-old power plant being viewed as in its prime. Sporn these
days is an interesting hybrid, with high-technology computers
replacing the old control panels in its control rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Clean Air Act has meant big changes for Sporn. The
2-foot-high letters that spell the plant's name are mostly obscured
now by precipitators erected around it to reduce fly ash, and its
stacks now produce only modest white wisps. Its sulfur output is
way down, too, because it has switched to cleaner coal. But it
still emits far more sulfur, which causes acid rain, and nitrogen
oxides, which cause smog, than a new plant would.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1960s, utilities retired old plants, the way people
today replace personal computers, because new ones were cheaper and
better. But by the '70s the pace of progress in generating stations
had slowed, and the new plants were not necessarily better than the
old ones.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental regulations themselves had an effect _ what
David Hawkins, a high-ranking official at the EPA during the Carter
administration, referred to as ``the Heisenberg effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Werner Heisenberg was a physicist who postulated that observing
an experiment would change its outcome. The Clean Air Act, said
Hawkins, who is now with the Natural Resources Defense Council,
also changed the outcome: It created an incentive to avoid the new
rules by never replacing old plants with new ones. The act, he
said, ``had built into it the potential for abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon Billings, who was Edmund Muskie's chief aide on the Senate
Environment and Public Works Committee from 1966 through 1978 and
thus an important player in the debate over the Clean Air Act and
its 1977 amendments, said such legislation created a problem for
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the National Environmental Policy Act, which
requires public hearings and environmental impact statements, as
well as various other legal challenges, building a new power plant
has become an ordeal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a utility manager,'' Billings said, ``you say, `A
new one wouldn't be a whole lot more efficient, and they're not
letting me build nuclear; maybe what I should do is just gussy up
what I've got.'''
</P>
<P>
   And now there is uncertainty over the deregulation of the
utility industry, and over whether new generating technologies will
emerge that make central-station power plants obsolete. As a
result, hardly any new coal plants have been built in the last 10
years. Plants like Sporn are thought of by their owners not as old
but as almost eternal.
</P>
<P>
   And as demand for power has grown, companies like American
Electric Power, operating in an increasingly competitive market,
have found they can maximize their investment by running fewer
plants for more hours, rather than building new ones. ``They're
operating at 80, 90 percent of capacity, instead of 60 percent,''
said Billings, who is now a consultant on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Billings pointed out in an interview that the word
``grandfather'' is not in the 1970 act. What the law did, he said,
was to allow the government to set new controls on old plants
strict enough to solve local pollution problems, and to demand that
new plants use the best available technology at the time they were
built.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, Billings says _ and many people agree _ is that the
EPA dropped the ball and did not pay close attention to changes at
the plants.
</P>
<P>
   The agency did sue, but not until 1989, when it asserted that
Wisconsin Electric Power Co. had modified a plant in a way that
made it subject to the rules for new plants. A court agreed with
most of the agency's arguments, and now officials are arguing that
the utilities have been on notice since then.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials declined to give details about their accusations
against Sporn, because, they said, the company was contending that
some of what it had divulged to regulators was confidential
business information. But there is no dispute about what was done _
only about how to characterize it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For example, surrounding the combustion zone in Sporn's boilers
are pipes, lined up a little like bars on a cell, and inside is
water. At the top and bottom, big metal parts called headers
connect all the pipes, so the water can flow into one larger pipe.
At various times in 1990 and 1991, American Electric Power replaced
headers in four of Sporn's boilers.
</P>
<P>
   After the water has been boiled into steam and run through
turbines, to convert steam energy into the mechanical power of a
turning shaft, the steam must be turned back to water. To do that
involves running the steam through yet more pipes in a device
called a condenser; outside those pipes is water from the Ohio
River. But the pipes corrode over time, and the utility replaced
all the pipes in three condensers in 1990 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
   To engineers here, the issue is simple. Sporn operates with
steam under pressure of 4,500 pounds per square inch and
temperatures at 1,100 degrees, far higher than a nuclear plant, and
produces nearly a million pounds of steam per hour. Consequently,
the engineers do not hesitate to replace heavy metal parts that
show signs of corrosion, or of erosion from steam or water flowing
past at 45 miles an hour, for months on end. Not to do so, they
say, would be suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Ms. Lowrance of the EPA, replacing major
components year after year eventually becomes the equivalent of
building a new plant. Congress set up the rule on modifications,
she said, ``so that life-extension projects don't go on forever.''
If they could go on forever, she said, Congress would never have
agreed to let old plants operate on laxer standards than those
applied to new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Some people agree with her. Gaylord Nelson, a senator from
Wisconsin from 1963 to 1981 and the organizer of the first Earth
Day in 1970, said of the grandfather provisions, ``That compromise
had to be made if you were going to get enough votes to pass the
act.'' But an eventual phase-out was assumed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gray, on the other hand, pointed out that the law does not set
any time limit on the plants; if Congress had wanted one, he said,
it would surely have written one in.
</P>
<P>
   EPA officials say they hope to settle the case, but negotiations
have dragged on for months. If it goes to court, they say, they
will argue that the work constitutes ``modifications'' partly
because it was financed as capital investments, not maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Plant officials say that has no bearing on the nature of the
physical work, and they add that Sporn's construction cost was paid
off in the early 1980s. Every penny of value that Sporn and other
old plants in its system carry on the utility's books, they say, is
postconstruction expenditure.
</P>
<P>
   Among environmentalists and utility experts, there is no
certainty about which side will prevail. The uncertainty also
extends to the plant workers.
</P>
<P>
   In the control room here, Brent Watts, a 31-year-old engineer
who has worked at Sporn for seven years, reflected for a moment on
the idea that the plant was older than he was. ``I hope it gets us
till we get old enough to leave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He looked uncertain, though.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1350EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
