<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8861 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-25 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WAITING FOR ASSAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes you're reading along and a fact just jumps off the
page at you. Like this one, for instance: Syria's economy, its GNP,
is one-seventh the size of Israel's. That means Syria, with 16.5
million people, produces about 15 percent of what the Israeli
economy produces with 5.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
   I toss this out not to embarrass the Syrians. The Syrians
actually have a talented merchant class, which, if unleashed, would
quickly transform the Syrian economy. I toss it out to underscore
the tremendous imbalance of power that exists today between Israel
and Syria _ militarily, economically and technologically.
</P>
<P>
   This imbalance of power is an important backdrop to the current
Syrian-Israeli peace talks. Put simply, Israel, the vastly more
developed and powerful country, is being asked to relinquish a
strategic asset, the Golan Heights, to a weaker Syria, in return
for security guarantees and a still-to-be-determined Syrian
normalization with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting is that despite their power advantage
Israelis aren't just saying: ``Who needs this deal?'' Instead, a
slim majority of Israelis are leaning toward it, because they
believe it has the potential to actually enhance Israel's strength
_ by extracting Israel from its bloody quagmire in south Lebanon,
by turning Syria into a buffer between Israel and Iran instead of a
bridgehead through which Iran bleeds Israel, by transforming Syria
from the vanguard of the Arab ideological struggle against Israel
to a member of the circle of peace around Israel and by enabling
Israelis to drive directly across Syria to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But while a majority of Israelis are leaning in favor, they're
not there yet, because they still need to be convinced by President
Hafez Assad of Syria not only that such benefits actually accrue to
Israel if it relinquishes the Golan, but also that they will be
grounded in a wholly different Syrian approach to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   If a Golan deal is to have a solid majority in Israel, and if it
is to win the support of the American Congress, which will be asked
to help pay for it, Assad is going to have to undertake his own
initiative of reconciliation that says to Israelis this really is a
new day _ and it's not just going to be one day, the day Israel
relinquishes the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   With the parties resuming negotiations in Washington on Jan. 3,
Assad needs to move. If each act of reconciliation toward Israel
that he makes has to be squeezed out of him, if there is no sense
that each comes out of a real willingness to change the
relationship between the Syrian people and Israel, there will be no
impact. When things are squeezed out of you, you may feel as if you
are giving, but the other person will not feel as if he is getting.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar Sadat's genius was that he not only gave to Israelis the
reconciliation they most craved without being squeezed to do so, he
did it before talks even began. Also, by both his actions and his
words, Sadat made Israelis believe that it was a new day _ that
there was no going back for him so therefore there could be no
turning away by Israelis. Assad has done neither yet. Why is Assad
negotiating with Israel now? What is new for him? He has never
explained.
</P>
<P>
   There is going to be an Israeli referendum on this deal, so the
Israeli public will be deciding. Only Assad can tip the balance
firmly in favor, and he can do that best by opening the way, right
now, to contacts between Israelis and Syrians, who want peace and
an opening of Syria to the world every bit as much as Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Assad allowed a reporter from Israel's largest
newspaper, Yediot, to visit Damascus last week, and the reporter's
story in Friday's paper, including a picture of Syrian soldiers
embracing him and his conversations with Syrian students and
businessmen, was the buzz of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more Israelis can feel the Syrian response in the streets,
the more they will be convinced that this isn't just a deal with a
dictator,'' said the Israeli political theorist Yaron Ezrahi.
``Assad doesn't have to democratize Syria today, but he has to
democratize the peace, and he has to do it in a way that Israelis
see comes from his initiative, not something being squeezed out of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Assad has already started conditioning the Syrian public with
the new posters being plastered around Damascus: ``We fought with
honor. We will negotiate with honor. We will make peace with
honor.'' That's a good start. Now he has to condition the Israelis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8862 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-PREDICTIONS-REVIEW-2T     12-25 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREDICTIONS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE MILLENNIUM. TRY TO PREDICT ONE WEEK.
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jw) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six shopping days left until the century cusp, and the average
shopper has stopped ordering bulk shipments of mineral water and
started making lunch dates for January. Pundits who spent the fall
debating portents of doom have begun making predictions about the
next hundred years and the next thousand.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting the apocalypse couldn't have remained a national sport
for long. After all, the whole fun of a national sport is rooting
for some guy, no matter how messed up he is, and wondering whether
he'll prevail against incredible odds. If the Messiah showed up He
would just prevail. What fun is that? The final weeks of most
centuries have been more nerve-racking than the denouement of this
one.
</P>
<P>
   The first time a century ended, members of a desert religious
sect got themselves buried in Qumran with their graves facing north
so they could greet the Messiah when He resurrected them. He didn't
show.
</P>
<P>
   In the 990s, Christian priests took the Vikings to be the
biblical destroyers from Gog and Magog bringing the end of the
world. Turned out they were just Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Today the world is still intact, despite gloomy predictions from
the heavy hitters of prophecy. The mystic Edgar Cayce, who
accurately predicted the stock market crash of 1929, predicted that
the American coasts would flood in 1998. Jeane Dixon, the
astrologer who foresaw John F. Kennedy's assassination, thought a
world war would be fought in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably the world was supposed to explode this past July,
according to Nostradamus, who wrote cryptic prophetic verses in
1555 and usually hated to give a verifiable date. But he liked it
when numbers came in threes, so in one of his rare specific moods
he foretold the Great Fire of 1666: ``The blood of the just will be
required in London/burned by fire in thrice twenty and six.''
</P>
<P>
   In another precise moment, he pinpointed this past July as a
time of war and heaven-sent destruction: ``In the year 1999 seven
months,/From the sky will come a great King of Terror. ... Before
and afterwards Mars rules happily.'' Interpreters of the verse have
seen the King of Terror as a fusion weapon, a nuclear warhead or a
spaceship due to land around Independence Day. (Could he have been
anticipating the movie?)
</P>
<P>
   After July came and went, fans of eschatological prophecy calmed
down a bit. But the big breakthrough came in September, the start
of the academic year, with the arrival of next year's day planners,
the Filofaxes and the art calendars in stationery stores. Ancient
mystics did not have stationery stores and could remain riled up
for longer. Contemporary mystics had to face facts. How could time
both be ending and also be mapped out on so many glossy sheets of
cardboard? Anticipating the end suddenly seemed not a sign of faith
and imagination but just a good excuse to put off one's car
payments.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the mood has changed from predicting the end to
predicting the future, the time frame seems too long term. How can
we think about the next century or the next millennium, when it's
hard enough to tell what's going to happen this week?
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. A round-up of predictions for the coming week
appears below. Unlike predictions for the year 3000, these can be
verified. Just keep this newspaper around until next Sunday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1358EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
