A0831 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-PREDICTIONS-REVIEW-2T     12-25 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PREDICTIONS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE MILLENNIUM. TRY TO PREDICT ONE WEEK.
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(jw) 
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Six shopping days left until the century cusp, and the average
shopper has stopped ordering bulk shipments of mineral water and
started making lunch dates for January. Pundits who spent the fall
debating portents of doom have begun making predictions about the
next hundred years and the next thousand.
</P>
<P>
   Awaiting the apocalypse couldn't have remained a national sport
for long. After all, the whole fun of a national sport is rooting
for some guy, no matter how messed up he is, and wondering whether
he'll prevail against incredible odds. If the Messiah showed up He
would just prevail. What fun is that? The final weeks of most
centuries have been more nerve-racking than the denouement of this
one.
</P>
<P>
   The first time a century ended, members of a desert religious
sect got themselves buried in Qumran with their graves facing north
so they could greet the Messiah when He resurrected them. He didn't
show.
</P>
<P>
   In the 990s, Christian priests took the Vikings to be the
biblical destroyers from Gog and Magog bringing the end of the
world. Turned out they were just Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Today the world is still intact, despite gloomy predictions from
the heavy hitters of prophecy. The mystic Edgar Cayce, who
accurately predicted the stock market crash of 1929, predicted that
the American coasts would flood in 1998. Jeane Dixon, the
astrologer who foresaw John F. Kennedy's assassination, thought a
world war would be fought in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably the world was supposed to explode this past July,
according to Nostradamus, who wrote cryptic prophetic verses in
1555 and usually hated to give a verifiable date. But he liked it
when numbers came in threes, so in one of his rare specific moods
he foretold the Great Fire of 1666: ``The blood of the just will be
required in London/burned by fire in thrice twenty and six.''
</P>
<P>
   In another precise moment, he pinpointed this past July as a
time of war and heaven-sent destruction: ``In the year 1999 seven
months,/From the sky will come a great King of Terror. ... Before
and afterwards Mars rules happily.'' Interpreters of the verse have
seen the King of Terror as a fusion weapon, a nuclear warhead or a
spaceship due to land around Independence Day. (Could he have been
anticipating the movie?)
</P>
<P>
   After July came and went, fans of eschatological prophecy calmed
down a bit. But the big breakthrough came in September, the start
of the academic year, with the arrival of next year's day planners,
the Filofaxes and the art calendars in stationery stores. Ancient
mystics did not have stationery stores and could remain riled up
for longer. Contemporary mystics had to face facts. How could time
both be ending and also be mapped out on so many glossy sheets of
cardboard? Anticipating the end suddenly seemed not a sign of faith
and imagination but just a good excuse to put off one's car
payments.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the mood has changed from predicting the end to
predicting the future, the time frame seems too long term. How can
we think about the next century or the next millennium, when it's
hard enough to tell what's going to happen this week?
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. A round-up of predictions for the coming week
appears below. Unlike predictions for the year 3000, these can be
verified. Just keep this newspaper around until next Sunday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Faith Popcorn, founder, BrainReserve. Author of ``Clicking'' and
``The Popcorn Report.'' Known for predicting the rise of home
businesses, home shopping and organic foods, the rise of four-wheel
drive, and the fall of New Coke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y2K and New Year's Eve both will be a big bust. ... Resort
towns will be full.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major cities will not.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Edward Yardeni, chief global economist and investment
strategist, Deutsche Bank Securities. Predicted the '90s bull
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``My short-term forecast is that the Nasdaq will hit a new
record high on Dec. 30. That's it. It's the only short-term
forecast that I think has any chance of being right.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harry S. Dent Jr., author of ``The Roaring 2000s Investor''
(1999). Also predicted the bull market of the '90s, in his book
``The Great Boom Ahead'' (1992).
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think Y2K is going to be a big problem. To be out of
this market is suicide. I would not be surprised to see in the last
week of December a short, minor pullback. If it did that, I'll
buy.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Twilight, astrologer. Six months before, predicted an
earthquake on the day one occurred in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there'll be some kind of good news on the 28th or the
29th because Mercury and Jupiter are going to be flowing
beautifully, and that's an aspect of forgiveness. Either there
could be some peace accord, or a great push on the individual level
to have peace within people's lives, in their community and
family.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rudnick, playwright and author. Has no major forecasting
credential, but possesses an uncanny ability to anticipate moods.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the week, both orange and pony skin will be so
over, they will return. By the end of the week, Tom Brokaw will
publish `Chicken Soup for the Greatest Generation.' By the end of
the week, that little Cuban boy will be awarded to Rosie
O'Donnell.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Deutsch, former director of the CIA. Predicted many major
events, most of them classified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the world will see any major Y2K electronic
meltdown because a lot of attention has been placed on reducing the
risk. On the other hand I fear we'll see two or three terrorist
incidents around the globe over the millennium weekend.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Andrew McInnis, New York Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Question: How many people will be in Times Square, where 1
million gathered last New Year's Eve?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: ``We're anticipating a larger number, just due to the
fact that it's on the weekend and it's the millennium
celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Next question: Would you like to predict a number?
</P>
<P>
   Next answer: ``We don't predict. It could snow and people could
stay home.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Byron Wien, chief U.S. investment strategist, also of Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. Predicted in January 1999 that the Y2K worry
would be a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a headline that you will see: post-Christmas returns
will set a record, both in actual stores and on the Internet.
Retailers will discover that the people giving gifts don't know
what the recipients want, how big they are, what size they are, or
what colors they like. People are so self-absorbed in this money
society that they don't know anything about anybody else.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ray Kurzweil, author of ``The Age of Spiritual Machines: When
Computers Exceed Human Intelligence.'' Predicted the emergence of
the World Wide Web and the 1998 taking of the world chess
championship by a computer in his book ``The Age of Intelligent
Machines'' (1990) written in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have developed a mathematical model (which I have called the
law of accelerating returns) which describes the processes
underlying the double exponential growth of certain technological
capabilities, such as computer speed and price-performance;
computer memory capacities; the speed, resolution, and bandwidth of
brain scanning. ... The predictions I made during the 1980s, for
the 1990s, turned out to be very accurate. ... But the methods I've
developed don't apply to predicting short-term incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make the kinds of predictions you're asking, either one
would have (1) to be a soothsayer (which I don't claim to be), or
(2) to be willing to make predictions that are likely to be wrong.
There seem to be a lot of people in the second category, but I
prefer to make predictions where I have a reasonable basis. ... I'm
just not in the guessing game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best,
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray
</P>
<P>
   ``P.S. I'm not flying on Jan. 1, but I do have a flight
scheduled on Jan. 2!'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Avery, manager, business development, IBM. Correctly
predicted the decline of CD-ROMs but says ``everyone did.'' Has no
weather forecasting credentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average temperature is going to be warmer than any other
week between Christmas and New Year's thus far. In fact it's
feeling kind of hot right now.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Seltman, occult scientist. Known for hand analysis
(palm-reading).
</P>
<P>
   ``On the third of January you'll wake up, brush your teeth, and
go to work.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Celente, founder of the Trends Research Institute.
Predicted the 1987 stock market crash and the demise of the Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young people are going to party much more intensely than
the older folks. ... In Europe the millennial celebrations are
going to be much greater than in the U.S. ... Times Square will
have record numbers. Record numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions: And who will win the Rose Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: ``I don't do sports or weather.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
