<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     12-25 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JOHN ROCKER'S PERSONA AND `CORPORATE SYNERGY'  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been mulling over rational explanations for why John Rocker
would so willingly stand up in front of the world to model the
naked truth about his fundamental life tenets, if that's what they
really are. I've been wondering what _ besides stupidity that is
almost beyond belief _ would induce a young man on the brink of
stardom to volunteer his neck for a national tomahawk chop?
</P>
<P>
   Could it have been that Rocker was saying what he thought people
wanted to hear? Could he, as so many late-20th-century athletes are
wont to do, have mistaken a news media forum for the grand stage of
the bizarre?
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: every time Rocker opened his mouth to spew some
garbage back at the equally foul New York City baseball fans last
fall, more salivating reporters came charging his way. Every time
he stuck his tongue out like some fifth-grade bully in the
elementary school cafeteria, the picture went directly into the
paper. Every time Rocker acted like a jerk to bring attention to
him, that's exactly what he got.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public monster Rocker created during the playoffs appears
to have consumed him,'' Michael A. Lough, assistant sports editor
of The Telegraph, Rocker's hometown newspaper in Macon, Ga., wrote
Friday. ``Something seems to have consumed him, for the John Rocker
of late 1999 doesn't seem to be the same one of a year earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't pretend to know, either. But I am familiar with what a
25-year-old athlete whose emotional development was most likely
stunted at 15 has been conditioned to think is potentially
profitable, and cool. Interestingly, Lough, who covered Rocker in
high school, wrote that the Rocker whose xenophobic bile appeared
in the latest issue of Sports Illustrated does not seem to
recognize the differences between a ``rasslin' show and real
life.''
</P>
<P>
   What a surprise, that the public persona Rocker has been
cultivating _ madman out of the bullpen _ would bear so much
resemblance to the stark ravings of the wrestling industry that
provides stellar ratings and revenue for, among others, the cable
network Ted Turner started. What a revelation, that someone might
be inclined to follow the path to commercials and film blazed by a
rasslin' role model named Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   What flaming hypocrites we are here in New York, city of
Sprewell, starting with our dueling candidates for Senate, who
jumped at the first opportunity to use Rocker to promote their
campaigns. The mayor should find his heart for the homeless and
repair his corrupt, crumbling schools before he worries about
fixing Rocker. The first lady might wish to recall which syndicated
radio show that soars on the wings of insensitive ethnic humor her
husband, and countless other politicians, have repeatedly phoned
into when they want to plug into the desired demographic market.
</P>
<P>
   When a microphone is thrust into the face of a John Rocker, does
he have the maturity or common sense to know if he is being judged
by the different standards of entertainment and sports?
</P>
<P>
   In one industry, anything usually goes. In the other, terms of
morality are loosely and self-righteously applied. In these days of
corporate synergy, when the same company (Time Warner) that owns
Rocker's team also publishes the magazine doing the interview, does
he even know anymore which role comes first?
</P>
<P>
   It is not terribly difficult to imagine Rocker riding in the car
with his interviewer, the tape recorder running, his mind racing,
his juices flowing. Knowing what athletes know about the harmonic
nature of locker room banter and drive-time humor, it is easy to
imagine this silly man suddenly casting himself as one of the guys
cracking wise with Don Imus or Howard Stern.
</P>
<P>
   I've said this before, and I'll keep saying it, too. In what
borders on insanity, there has been a greater national uproar over
Rocker's rock-headedness than over the murder allegations against
Rae Carruth and the calamitous cycle of athletes' violence against
women. More people keep popping out of Carruth's past to defend his
poetic and gentle character, to insist that these horrific charges
do not define the man. And while we must hedge our comments on
Carruth on the fair presumption of innocence, here is a national
posse ready to run Rocker out of baseball before anyone has
produced compelling evidence that indicates he practices what he
preached.
</P>
<P>
   Some athletes persuade us with words that bear little relation
to their actions. Latrell Sprewell, notorious coach-choker,
followed up that offense by racing his car up the exit ramp of a
California freeway, nearly killing two people. Many of the same
folks now calling for Rocker's scalp buy Sprewell jerseys for their
kids. Sprewell's rebel-without-a-cause reputation has surely played
a role in his redemption. Do Sprewell and Rodman and Stone Cold
Steve Austin factor into this Rocker story? I don't know. That is
for the Braves to find out.
</P>
<P>
   It is for the Braves to figure out if Rocker's comments were
heartfelt as, say, Reggie White's homophobic remarks of a few years
ago that went, by the way, unpunished. They know him better than we
do. Andruw Jones, out of Curacao, one of ``those people'' who got
into the country, roomed with Rocker when they played for the
Braves' farm team in Macon. The Braves' players who come from a
variety of Latin and Caribbean nations have idled away the hours
with Rocker in the clubhouse. They can better determine if what
Rocker said is in his heart, or if he is just another Frankenstein
reflection of the shock culture that diminishes us more than anyone
on the No. 7 train ever could. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
