<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-NYT     12-25 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PARCELLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS RATES   A GAME BALL   FOR THE SEASON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Jets are merely 6-8 as they near the end of a season in
which they were supposed to contend for the Super Bowl. Yet getting
to 6-8 has been one of the finest achievements in Bill Parcells'
coaching career, a career that includes three Super Bowl
appearances and two championships.
</P>
<P>
   After their 1-6 start, the Jets have been more than competitive.
They are 5-2 over their last seven games, the second-best record in
that stretch among American Conference teams.
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishing this turnaround, even with their playoff hopes all
but dead, has actually energized Parcells. He has kept off weight.
He runs three miles two or three days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more tired last year with a winning team than I am this
year,'' he said last week while preparing the Jets for their Monday
night game against the Dolphins in Miami. ``I've tried to be
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   He describes it as something like teaching _ if you've got the
right students, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being a schoolteacher,'' Parcells said. ``When you
have pupils that are eager to learn, it's easier to teach. You may
have seen films of me yelling on the sidelines. In one of them, I'm
telling Phil Simms, `Pay attention!'''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' fresh outlook indicates to some observers that he will
probably return. Certainly, his players feel that way _ especially
with quarterback Ray Lucas turning into one of the league's
surprise players, a new owner coming within a few weeks, and the
Jets playing more like the contenders they thought they would be
than the spoilers they are now.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, since arriving in 1997, Parcells has kept the Jets
steady, through good times and bad. By comparison, just look at how
the Jets collapsed the two years before he arrived _ no December
victories in the Rich Kotite era, players mumbling, the front
office in disarray, everyone, it seemed, pointing fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, though, have won their last two December games, giving
Parcells' Giants, Patriots and Jets teams a 38-21 mark during the
month. Over all, the Jets are 7-3 in December with Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more of a positive feeling around the locker room,''
said linebacker Chad Cascadden, who has been a Jet since 1995.
``Also, we were successful last year. I think this team has adopted
Bill's personality of not quitting. When Richie was here, I'm not
sure the team reflected his personality. Some guys were on their
own program.''
</P>
<P>
   Those players are gone. Those that remain _ there are 14 who
were here in 1996 _ have given Parcells few problems. There are no
locker-room dissidents, even though most will grumble from time to
time about the Parcells style.
</P>
<P>
   Jumbo Elliott has had a love-hate relationship with Parcells
going back to their Giants days. Parcells saw Elliott go to the Pro
Bowl as a Giant in 1993, but fined him as a Jet for being late to a
practice this season when Elliott had a stomach virus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill's always been very good in getting your focus back very
quickly, whether you've won or lost,'' Elliott said. ``If you win,
he doesn't let you think you're invincible; if you've lost, he gets
you to move on. But that 1-6 start could easily have been a 5-2. We
made some blunders at the ends of games. I've been around a lot of
teams with him and he's done a great job. Just this year he had to
change the game plan for the season.''
</P>
<P>
   That was no mean feat. ``One of the hardest things I had to do
this year is figure, how do you win?'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   He wondered what the club could do when its scoring was
compromised with the season-ending injury to Vinny Testaverde in
the opening game. Testaverde's absence compounded the injury to the
clutch receiver Wayne Chrebet, who missed the first five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you can't win,'' Parcells concluded. ``You saw it: 16-13
to the Colts, 16-6 to Jacksonville. A key penalty, a turnover on
offense the opening game. You put your hands down and say, `Look,
boys, this is what we've got to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   What the Jets did, among other things, was reassess their
strengths. In the process, Parcells turned the Jets into a team of
attrition rather than one that could make the big play to
complement the running of Curtis Martin. Every day Parcells put
players through fumble-recovery drills, interception drills,
holding-onto-the-ball drills, special-teams drills.
</P>
<P>
   The offense during Lucas' early tutoring did not even see a pass
carry 20 yards. The idea was not to make a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   This subtle transformation in the depleted Jets took place
against what has proved to be the league's toughest schedule. Jets'
opponents have a combined won-lost mark of 82-58.
</P>
<P>
   The results of Parcells' attention to detail, and his
acquisition of tenacious players, show in many ways. The Jets rank
fourth in the NFL in takeaway-giveaway differential. The only clubs
ahead of them are Jacksonville (13-1), Tennessee (11-3) and Kansas
City (9-5). Lucas, who has started seven times in his career, has
the lowest interception rate in pro football. The Jets rank fourth
in the conference in keeping opponents pinned back after kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we don't win these next two games,'' said Parcells,
``I think the team has improved, so I can look positively upon
that. But right now all I'm concerned about is that Miami will be
prepared to counter the things we did the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, forget about that 28-20 victory two weeks ago.
Today's game hasn't been won yet. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
