<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Dec. 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call 212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The unusually dry weather pattern will persist as jet stream
winds blow from the northwest in most sections east of the Rockies.
A vigorous disturbance moving through central Ontario will direct a
fresh supply of frigid air into the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The leading edge of the colder weather will move from the
Appalachians to the coast during the afternoon. A gusty breeze from
the southwest will draw more seasonable conditions into the Middle
Atlantic region and coastal Northeast, though clouds will thicken
in New England.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp wind from the northwest will transport gelid air across
the Great Lakes resulting in snow showers from northern Michigan
and Wisconsin to central New York and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The South will be bright and noticeably milder, however the
chilly air will return Monday. Some clouds will cover southern
Florida and it will not be as cold as Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure in north Texas will circulate moisture from the
Gulf of Mexico into the upper Rio Grande Valley producing drizzle
and fog. A disturbance migrating westward across Arizona will force
the moistened air to ascend the southern Rockies. Bands of showers
will dampen New Mexico and northern Arizona with wet snow in the
higher elevations.
</P>
<P>
   An enormous high pressure system, with central pressure still
near 31 inches of mercury, will control the weather west of the
Mississippi Valley. Stagnant conditions with thick fog and
accumulating pollutants will persist over the interior Northwest,
but it will be dry.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WAITING FOR THE SNOW
</P>
<P>
   Not a flake of snow has been seen in Boston since March 15.
Besides being the latest date ever for the first trace of snow,
this 283 day period also marks the longest time that the city has
gone without any snowfall. Oddly, last year had established the
previous record when 274 days passed without any snow. The first
trace of snow occurred on December 22 in 1998. While these records
are impressive for the lack of snow in eastern New England, in the
winter of 1891-92, the first measurable snow, when 0.1 inches was
noted, did not happen until January 6 that season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
