<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL _ PANAMA CITY _ After 85 years, the U.S. hands over
the Panama Canal at noon on Dec. 31 in a ceremony sure to kick up a
new round of debate among worried conservatives. Critics have never
been comfortable with the deal brokered 22 years ago by then-U.S.
President Jimmy Carter, fearing the Panamanians will overcharge
ships using the canal and possibly hamstring the U.S. military.
Lately, they've been outraged at a deal cut by the Panamanians to
let a Hong Kong company run the busy ports at either end of the
50-mile-long canal, saying the company is a front for the Chinese
military. Meanwhile Panamanians plan elaborate ceremonies for an
event they believe will showcase their emergence on the world stage
and symbolize their autonomy after decades of U.S. domination.
(MWilliams, Cox News Service). 30. WITH GRAPHIC: Info-graphic being
prepared by Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CANAL-SECURITY _ PANAMA CITY, Panama _ A terrorist with a
suitcase full of explosives could probably shut down the Panama
Canal for years, American conservatives warn, crippling a vital
U.S. commercial and military link. How real is the threat, how
important is the canal to the U.S. and how vulnerable is the
waterway now that the U.S. military has closed its bases in Panama?
Critics also charge that a company with contracts to run ports at
both ends of the canal is a front for the Chinese military _
charges that Pentagon officials deny. We explore the issue with
comments from conservative activists and canal administrators.
(MWilliams, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   CANAL-WORKERS _ PANAMA CITY, Panama _ American school kids are
taught that the Panama Canal is one of America's proudest
achievements, an engineering marvel that ushered in the American
Century. But probably few people realize that it was the sweat,
muscle and blood of black Caribbean laborers that actually dug the
50-mile-long ditch. Of 5,000 workers who died during the American
effort, 4,500 were black West Indians, who endured segregated
living quarters, unequal pay scales and the terrible dangers of the
backbreaking job. We interview an 86-year-old black canal worker
whose father and grandfather labored on the project, telling the
story through his eyes. Will seek comments from other black
workers, as well. (MWilliams, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTONMEAT-HACCP _ WASHINGTON _ Despite Agriculture
Secretary Dan Glickman's public vow two years ago to close down
meat and poultry plants ``producing dirty product,'' his
department's records show companies are allowed to operate even as
they collect hundreds of federal food safety violations.
(Jaspin/Montgomery, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-MALL _ WASHINGTON _ Organizers of President Clinton's giant
millennium party
</P>
<P>
   on the National Mall are wrestling with security and logistical
concerns as New Year's Eve bash approaches. A rundown of
preparations for the event. (Nesmith, Cox News Service).
</P>
