<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAFEAT26-COX     12-25 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFEAT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gugliotta medical riddle
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Gugliotta might play tonight when the Phoenix Suns are home
against Golden State. That in itself is wonderful holiday story.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-10 forward who starred at N.C. State has been cleared by
doctors to return to action after suffering a life-threatening
seizure only nine days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who suffer seizures only experience them once,''
Suns doctor Richard Emerson said. ``I feel very confident that this
is a single, isolated incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is what happened to Gugliotta minutes after scoring 17
points, grabbing 14 rebounds in a 110-102 Suns victory at Portland
Dec. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta, then a few days shy of his 30th birthday, took a seat
in the middle of the team bus for the ride to the airport and the
flight home. He had a drink in one hand while he talked with his
wife on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly, he slammed the drink down, prompting young teammate
Toby Bailey to ask, ``What's up?''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta didn't respond, and another teammate and former Hawks
player Randy Livingston noticed Gugliotta held the soda can to his
ear, as if he were using it as a phone. ``Like he'd lost control of
his motor skills,'' Livingston related.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, something was wrong. Julie Fie, the team's vice
president for communications, was about to board the bus when new
coach Scott Skiles leaped off and screamed, ``We need a doctor!''
</P>
<P>
   They found a Portland team physician in the Blazers locker room.
Meanwhile, Livingston ran to an emergency medical truck parked
nearby. Doctor and paramedics scrambled aboard, checked Gugliotta
and immediately transported him to a nearby hospital. He was
unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   During the ordeal, Gugliotta's breathing ``became shallow and
required assistance,'' Emerson said. He awakened at 4 a.m. in the
intensive care unit, completely unaware of the incident, and the
battery of tests performed on him have revealed no damage. The only
side effect was severe headache pain apparently caused by a spinal
tap procedure performed as part of post-seizure testing. That was
relieved with an outpatient visit.
</P>
<P>
   In general, a seizure is ``an electrical phenomenon in the
brain'' that could have any of a number of causes, Emerson said.
``Despite all our high technology, sometimes we never know why.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is completely normal,'' Emerson said. There is no
evidence of a tumor or other invasive mass in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta's wife Nikki said they were lucky, ``If it had
happened when they were in the air, he could have been in a lot of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns doctor would not speculate on the outcome had Gugliotta
been stricken after the Suns' charter took off.
</P>
<P>
   NBA teams already are now in the process of putting in
defibrillators aboard team planes for use in the event of a heart
attack. However, Gugliotta would have needed an intubation device
to clear his airways and aid in breathing. That requires specific
training and the Suns might have to deal with that, owner Jerry
Colangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
