<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAITEMS26-COX     12-25 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAITEMS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA NOTES: McGrady a wanted man
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the budding free agents the Chicago Bulls are said to
covet is Toronto forward Tracy McGrady. Raptors coach Butch Carter
says forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that Tracy is going to leave the Raptors,''
Carter said. ``I believe we will re-sign him. But if he does go
somewhere else, I'll be willing to bet you it won't be Chicago.
Tracy hates losing.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrady has flirted with the prospect of signing elsewhere when
he becomes a free agent this summer. He rejected a six-year, $64
million extension to re-sign with the Raptors last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, McGrady publicly considered his options.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to come (to Philadelphia), and I definitely would
love to play with Allen Iverson,'' he told the Philadelphia
Inquirer. ``I don't have any control over all the other stuff that
factors into it, like my contract and all of that. But if I ended
up playing in Philadelphia, you wouldn't see me crying about it. Me
and (Iverson) _just think about that. Whew! I'd love it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrady can see past Philadelphia, however. ``I wouldn't mind
playing with Kobe (Bryant). I wouldn't mind playing with Shaq
(O'Neal). That's not like me saying I want to play with another
team. That's just the players.''
</P>
<P>
   But, how about those Bulls?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I didn't call anybody's name who is on the Bulls, did
I?'' McGrady said.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen vs. Barkley
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, Scottie Pippen does have a kind word or two
for former Houston teammate Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Regretting his harsh preseason assessment of Barkley now that
the Round Mound has left the stage for good, Pippen says, ``that
was then, this is now'' and admits a personality conflict with
Barkley, ``a little bit of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't handle things _ and maybe myself more than anybody _
the way we should have. We probably should have spoken
person-to-person and handled it that way. I personally like Charles
and I enjoyed being around him. He's a character. He's like being
with a comedian or something. But he's a good-hearted person. I
hate that things got ticked off like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his first game back in Houston, the Portland star said,
Barkley's injury had an emotional impact on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're human, and things like that can be very emotional, not
being able to walk away from the game. Charles was looking forward
to playing this season. No matter how you look at it, he was
looking forward to going around and being taunted (by the fans) _
all those things he's really going to miss. People hate him so much
that everybody loves (to taunt) him. Everybody loves to hear what
he has to say, get a laugh from him or get him talking about
whatever. It would be tough for any athlete to go that way. He
wanted to go away on his own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs up
</P>
<P>
   With teammate Tom Gugliotta hit by a seizure and the Suns
recovering from the turmoil of a coaching change _ Scott Skiles in;
Danny Ainge out _ Jason Kidd stepped up and delivered three
consecutive triple doubles as the Suns won four in a row before an
overtime loss to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down
</P>
<P>
   Stubborn, Kevin McHale's refusal to trade Gugliotta to the
Lakers has left Minnesota as a playoff wannabe this season. The
Lakers offered Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell. Put them with Kevin
Garnett, Joe Smith and Terrell Brandon and the Wolves would be on
the prowl.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to NBA?
</P>
<P>
   Dave Cowens worked two games as analyst for Sunshine Network
games at his alma mater Florida State. Cowens won't why he resigned
in Charlotte last winter, laughed when he was asked if he would
like to do TV work on a regular basis. ``That's not gonna happen.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he studied four game tapes before going to work. But he
wants to coach again and he will listen if an NBA team or a college
calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``College? Oh, sure, I'd be interested. Absolutely,'' he
responded. ``I'm on hold this particular year. When changes are
made, hopefully something good will happen for me and my family.
But whether pro or college, instead of going and taking a job just
any place, what you want to do is get involved in a good
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
