<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLEAST26-COX     12-25 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL East notes
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trade talk
</P>
<P>
   Florida needs a goalie, though general manager Bryan Murray
won't know how desperate the situation is for two weeks, when
Trevor Kidd determines whether he needs season-ending shoulder
surgery. Kidd said that's a ``90-percent'' certainty, but might
have been trying to douse the high expectations created when Murray
was quoted the day before as saying Kidd's return was imminent.
There has been several rumors as to which direction Murray would go
for a replacement. The most-often heard rumor: Vancouver's Garth
Snow, who is expendable now that the Canucks have Felix Potvin.
Here's the problem with that scenario: The Canucks own the
Panthers' first-round draft pick next year from the Pavel Bure
trade. The worse Florida does, the better for Vancouver. If you're
Canucks GM Brian Burke, do you make a deal that could improve the
Panthers playoff positioning? Phoenix goalie Nikolai Khabibulin
remains an unrestricted free agent, but may cost more than the
Panthers are willing to pay _ in players and salary.
</P>
<P>
   Pleased in Pittsburgh
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh has cooled off, but the returns on coach Herb Brooks
remain positive. Jaromir Jagr, who openly feuded with the fired
Kevin Constantine, said the change to Brooks' wide-open style of
play, ``is like going from Siberia to Florida.'' Owner Mario
Lemieux, who didn't support Constantine's hiring, said, ``The
offense is back in the organization and that's going to be exciting
for all of us to watch. It's a different game out there. The puck
is moving a lot quicker. There's a lot more movement on the ice,
and with the type of team we have, that's what we need. That's how
I played all my life.'' Lemieux said he felt a high-scoring team
was needed to attract fans to an outdated arena in a poor economy.
The Penguins were averaging 14,496 through 15 home games.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia general manager Bob Clarke needs to move a forward
now that Rod Brind'Amour is back from a broken foot. But Clarke
said he will not make any moves while coach Roger Nielson is
undergoing chemotherapy for bone marrow cancer. Mikael Renberg
seemed upset about being a healthy scratch when Brind'Amour came
back Wednesday against New Jersey but suited up for the Thrashers'
game Thursday night and had a goal and an assist. ... New Jersey
general manager Lou Lamoriello on reports that the Devils may be
purchased by the new YankeesNets entity: ``These things just go
around and around. We're staying away from these things like the
plague.'' ... The Devils' Patrik Elias scored one goal in his first
28 games, five in the next five. ... New Jersey's Brendan Morrison
remains upset Lamoriello has not fulfilled his trade wishes. He has
one goal and five assists in 17 games. He's been scratched for four
of the past seven and has upset teammates with his attitude. ...
Ray Sheppard got back in the lineup in Florida after being benched
seven games for mouthing about his limited time on the ice. ``I had
to do something to get his attention,'' coach Terry Murray said.
``Obviously the offensive part of his game wasn't falling into
place like we hoped. I hope there's a good reaction to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
