<HEADER>
A8879 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-NHLWEST26-C0X     12-25 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST26-C0X </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL West notes
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early returns
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's signing of Pat Verbeek, known to some as ``The Little
Ball of Hate,'' has paid off. Verbeek is playing on the Red Wings'
top line with Brendan Shanahan and Steve Yzerman, and the three
have combined for 26 goals in 14 games. Shanahan, who is in a
salary drive, has five goals in the past five games and has hit 20
for the 12th consecutive season. Said the rarely complimentary
Scotty Bowman, ``That line has been strong. We kept trying to get
somebody to play right wing, and we tried different guys and
(nobody) seemed to be as good as Pat Verbeek. He's been solid. He
complements the way we play. He's a strong cornerman, and he's good
in his own end and it's resulting in the stats.'' Verbeek, who was
considered by the Thrashers before they signed Ray Ferraro and
Nelson Emerson as unrestricted free agents, has five goals and 10
assists and is a plus 17 in 21 games.
</P>
<P>
   Cautiously optimistic
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis' record through 34 games (21-9-4) was the best start
in franchise history, but several players were being cautious with
their comments. Why? The Blues are 13-0-3 against sub .500 teams
and 8-9-1 against winning clubs, including 4-6-1 within the
conference. ``Our record against the top teams has to improve if we
want to go to the next step,'' said center Jamal Mayers. The
biggest reason for the Blues' hot play of late (4-0-2) is goalie
Roman Turek, who posted consecutive shutouts but lost the scoreless
string 58 seconds into a game at Nashville on Thursday night. The
streak reached 1:54:56.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Like the Thrashers, Vancouver has played nine different rookies
this season, eight of whom hadn't played an NHL game. ``I can't
believe the difference,'' veteran defenseman Murray Baron said.
``When I broke in, I didn't say a word because I was petrified.
These guys are enjoying it. There's no such thing as hazing
anymore. The only way to get them is the rookie dinner. It's not
good.'' ... Goalie Grant Fuhr, who has struggled since being
acquired by Calgary, underwent knee surgery to remove some scar
tissue and will be sidelined at least a month. The Flames said the
irritation in the knee is what caused Fuhr's slow start (5-9-2,
3.66, .858). Fuhr said he didn't need the surgery. ... Colorado's
Joe Sakic, who has missed 13 consecutive games and 18 of the past
20 with torn cartilage in his ribs, hopes to return Monday against
St. Louis. He is one point short of 1,000 in his career. ...
Avalanche defenseman Adam Foote rented a bus for $600 to transport
30 family members from Toronto to Buffalo for a game Thursday
night, then rode the bus back with them after the game. ... Detroit
remains far apart on contract talks with center Igor Larinov. ...
File this under atypical athlete injuries: Phoenix winger Greg
Adams had to undergo surgery to repair a deviated septum because an
infection had developed. He is the Coyotes' leading scorer with 33
points but will be out two to three weeks. ... Nashville goalie
Mike Dunham has started 11 of the past 12 games and is answering
the questions about his durability after being limited to 44 games
last season with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
