<P>
   FOOTBALL/COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-BOWLS-MAIN _ They generate millions of dollars annually,
enjoy nonprofit status and, while some are designated for charity,
at least 75 percent of the revenue goes back to the participating
colleges. Very little, if any, is given to legitimate charitable
causes. The rest is spent entertaining, building relationships with
colleges that will make it tough to pull the plug on bowl system
for the football college platoff that so many fans want. (Fish,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BOWLS-PLAYOFFS _ While groups are working on playoff proposals,
don't hold your breath. Bowls are campaigning against a move to a
playoff, and they are well-entrenched to ward one off. Still, other
say a playoff will happen someday. (Fish, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOWLS-REPS _ Now that the IOC has cleaned up its act, being a
bowl representative may be the best non-paying job in sports. You
get to go college games each Saturday, get treated royally and
hobnob with important people. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
18. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOWLS-PEACH _ The Peach Bowl has gone from rags to riches, from
an unattractive game played in the old outdoor Alanta-Fulton County
Stadium to one of the up-and-coming bowls in the Georgia Dome. It
has gone from being on the edge of bankruptcy to reserves of over
$3 million. Now it tries to position itself for next level, maybe a
BCS spot. (Fish, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18. MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
