<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL OWNER SWINGS WITH HIS CHECKBOOK; PLUS ITEMS ON JEFF JUDEN,
JIM LEYRITZ, ADRIAN BELTRE, RUSS DAVIS AND RUDOLPH W. GIULIANI  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeffrey Loria was on the telephone to Japan one night last week.
Nothing unusual about an international call for him. But the person
on the other end and the reason for the long-distance call?
Definitely a change of pace for the new owner of the Montreal
Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were doing this thing with Irabu,'' Loria said, ``I
had to stop and remind myself I was dealing with a baseball player
and not an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu and Graeme Lloyd, an Australian, represent the
major acquisitions Loria has made in the early days of his expanded
life. Previously, his major acquisitions had names on them like
Marc Chagall, Fernand Leger, Henry Moore, Larry Rivers, Roy
Lichtenstein and Pablo Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   Loria, 58 years old, is a New York art dealer, for whom the
modern masters have been as rewarding as Derek Jeter, Mariano
Rivera and Bernie Williams have been for a different kind of New
York dealer. Those masters have enabled Loria to assume control of
the Expos with a promise to remove the exit signs from the
clubhouse and raise the airtight ceiling on the team's payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to strengthen this team in as many areas as I can,''
Loria said. ``As the new owner here, I feel I have an obligation to
move things forward. No more business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   With a shrinking attendance and a payroll that perennially has
been at or near the bottom, the Expos had become a prime candidate
to become the first major league team to move in more than a
quarter century. They gained a reputation for developing good
players but then trading them or letting them leave as free agents
because they said they didn't have the money to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   The roll call of former players resembles an all-star array:
Larry Walker, Moises Alou, Pedro Martinez, Marquis Grissom, John
Wetteland, Jeff Fassero, Ken Hill, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Loria, who earlier in the '90s owned a part of the Oklahoma City
Class AAA minor league team and then tried unsuccessfully to win
the Baltimore Orioles at auction, did not stumble into his
ownership role with the Expos. No one sidled up to him on 42nd
Street in Manhattan and sold him baseball's version of a fake
Rolex. So why the Expos?
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all I think they have a terrific organization,'' he
said. ``Player development there has always been first rate. The
city's a beautiful city. They've had a history of strong fan
support for baseball. One of the problems in recent years was the
team wasn't a winning team. They weren't a strong club, and players
were in flight.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he plan to turn all of those negatives into positives?
</P>
<P>
   ``By establishing stability, commencing a new marketing program
and bringing in a winning attitude and winning players,'' Loria
said, ``we can build this franchise to where it was in the '80s and
the early '90s. In '94 they were on track to win the pennant when
the strike came.''
</P>
<P>
   The Expos will not have the lowest payroll in the majors next
season. In fact, their $16 million payroll of 1999 could double.
The acquisition of Irabu, a starting pitcher, and the willingness
to guarantee an option-year salary for as much as $4 million, plus
the signing of Lloyd, a reliever, for $3 million a year for three
years, testifies to Loria's intentions. Some other baseball
officials questioned the amount of Lloyd's contract, but Loria
believes the left-hander can make Ugueth Urbina an even more
effective closer and that step, in turn, can only make the Expos
more successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid to acquire or trade players as long as it
improves the club,'' Loria said. ``What I'm about is quality
players and quality people, whether it's in the art world or the
baseball world. It's about quality. It's about trying to mix and
match the best and the ability to complement artists with other
artists in a collection or players with other players on the field
while still being fiscally responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Loria gained a hands-on reputation when he had the Oklahoma City
club, and he readily acknowledged his style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hands-on person and I'm going to be spending a lot of
time back and forth between New York and Montreal,'' he said. ``But
it's hands-on in consultation with your baseball advisors. The
decision to do the transaction with the Yankees was something that
I perhaps started in my mind, but our general manager and David
were right there in the decision-making process.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beattie, the former Yankees' pitcher, is the Expos' general
manager, and David Samson, Loria's 31-year-old son, is the new
executive vice president, having been lured away from his position
with Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do what you think you have to do to make things better,''
Loria said. At least he didn't say, as George Steinbrenner did when
he bought the Yankees, that he wouldn't be involved in the daily
operation of the team because he has too much to oversee in his
other business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a different style,'' Loria said, alluding to
Steinbrenner, whom he has known and liked for perhaps 25 years.
``Ultimately George has proven that energy doesn't hurt. Not only
has he proven that energy is necessary, but it helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides giving Beattie more money to work with and manager
Felipe Alou better players to work with, Loria is intent on selling
Montreal and Quebec on a new ball park. ``We're working on it right
now with the government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always optimistic. I'm a New Yorker. But Montrealers don't
like losing either.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much fun or success he has with the Expos, Loria
said he doesn't plan to give up his day job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been an art dealer all of my professional life,'' he
said. ``I have absolutely no interest in giving it up. I am still
enthusiastic about what I do in the art world. I'm still looking
for major outdoor sculptures and important paintings and sculptures
by the artists I love.''
</P>
<P>
   Victories and, ultimately, championships by the team he now
loves, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK YANKEES, THE TAMPA YANKEES
</P>
<P>
   By winning 12 successive World Series games, the Yankees of the
last four years have demonstrated how good they are. But they have
to be good to overcome the two-headed monster that competes in
their decision-making process, New York and Tampa. Because George
Steinbrenner spends most of his time in Tampa, the front-office
team there often prevails over the New York front-office team.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the input of general manager Brian Cashman, with
support from manager Joe Torre, the Yankees have signed two players
to major league contracts for next season who can only get in the
way of more sensible planning. Based more on Steinbrenner's desire
than anything else, the Yankees gave Jim Leyritz a contract. The
New York faction believes Leyritz is finished as a contributing
player.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the Yankees signed Jeff Juden, a pitcher who quickly
makes himself an outcast wherever he goes. When Juden played for
Montreal a couple of years ago, some players said they wouldn't
play if the Expos didn't release him. The Expos, the fourth team
Juden played for, traded him. The Yankees last season became the
eighth major league team he has played for in 10 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSS DAVIS, FREE AGENT WITH POWER
</P>
<P>
   While teams wait to learn if Adrian Beltre will become a
free-agent third baseman sometime before next season, Russ Davis is
a free-agent third baseman right now.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, whom Commissioner Bud Selig allowed the Los Angeles
Dodgers to retain even though he found they signed him a year
early, can become a free agent only if the Players Association
files a grievance and wins. Davis is already a free agent because
the Seattle Mariners didn't tender him a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who went to the Mariners from the Yankees four years ago
in the Tino Martinez trade, was one of 28 players who were not
tendered contracts by last Monday's deadline. Butch Huskey (Boston)
and Ricky Bottalico (St. Louis) were others.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mariners were going to drop Davis, they might have done
it a year earlier, after he committed an American League-high 32
errors at third. But he reverted to defensive form last season,
making only 12 errors, second fewest among A.L. third basemen who
played 100 games or more (Eric Chavez of Oakland had 9).
</P>
<P>
   Last season Davis also maintained his home run-hitting
consistency with 21. In each of the previous two seasons, he hit
20. He is one of 43 players who has hit 20 or more home runs in
each of the last three seasons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRITIC'S REMARKS OFF BASE, TOO
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker's published remarks about Mets fans, New York
residents and assorted other groups, including immigrants and
foreigners, were dreadful enough without instant critics
compounding the matter. One of those critics was the New York
mayor, Rudolph W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   At one of his daily news conferences, Giuliani linked Rocker's
attitude to the Atlanta Braves' ability to win only one World
Series in the '90s, even though they dominated the National League
in the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Braves have some great players who are immigrants and
foreigners,'' Giuliani said, ``so maybe that kind of tension
created on a team is the reason why the team underperformed in the
World Series throughout the decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to the mayor: Rocker played on only the last two of the
Braves' eight consecutive division championship teams in the
decade.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
