<HEADLINE>
EWING'S FINES, OPENINGS ON THE OLYMPIC TEAM AND BALLOTING FOR THE
MAN OF THE YEAR AWARD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Fla., Calif., Utah, Canada, Australia)  
 McGRADY HAS FUTURE, MAYBE NOT IN TORONTO; PLUS ITEMS ON PATRICK By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He can do things in midair that most people would have trouble
doing on the ground. He is young, impossibly talented and a huge
reason everyone in the National Basketball Association believes a
Canadian expansion team can qualify for the playoffs for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   But Tracy McGrady is also the subject of numerous trade rumors,
from Philadelphia to Orlando. He plays alongside Vince Carter,
thereby ensuring that McGrady will not be a franchise player if he
remains a Raptor. And although Carter is easily McGrady's best
friend on the team, the relentless pursuit of marketing dollars by
Carter's management team has left scraps for McGrady, perhaps the
second-most exciting young player in the league.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee that Toronto will re-sign McGrady, a free
agent to be whose contract situation has created a stir among his
teammates. Toronto made an offer to McGrady last summer, which fell
far short of the maximum allowed under the collective bargaining
agreement. He will be able to make as much as $86 million over
seven years, but it is still more likely that the Raptors will try
to sign him for less, with incentive clauses, if McGrady decides to
stay. In many ways, at the ripe old age of 20, he is the odd man
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like that aren't good for the team,'' said Charles
Oakley, the veteran forward and McGrady's and Carter's teammate.
``You never know what's going through his mind. How can you play
with a guy that management doesn't know what it's going to do and
he doesn't know what he's going to do? It makes it harder for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Raptors' below-the-maximum contract offer, Oakley added:
``Why do they do that? That's like bringing eggs to a barbecue.
Useless.''
</P>
<P>
   Butch Carter, the Raptors' coach, has been in the most
precarious situation. He has elected to bring the 6-foot-8-inch
McGrady off the bench despite the fact that the young forward wants
more minutes during a season in which he needs to increase his
market value. He has had to try to keep an athletic young player
from trying to do too much too fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fight that less with Vince than I do with Tracy,'' Butch
Carter said. ``Not the contract issue, but I think he wants to play
a lot. And I really don't have anything in my plan that's going to
allow him to shoot the ball 20 times and him score a lot of points
and us lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's a much bigger fight mentally than I've ever had with
Vince. Vince is easier to rein in, because Tracy doesn't have a
go-to move. So it's a lot harder to get a guy like that going when
you don't have a great point guard to get you consistent shots. So
Tracy suffers for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who is in his second season, averages 36.5 minutes and
23.5 points a game, ranking sixth in the league in scoring.
McGrady, who is in his third season, has played 26 minutes a game
and is second on the Raptors in scoring with an average of 13.1
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for Tracy,'' Butch Carter said. ``I feel bad for
him, but I got to do what I got to do. He's a great person, but
this team right now can't allow him to shoot and do what he wants
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrady may have other things on his mind, too. Butch Carter
said he wished McGrady's representatives would do more to promote
their client, the way Vince Carter's management team promotes him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's created all kind of opportunities for the kid,'' Butch
Carter said of Vince Carter. ``That's something that's hurt Tracy.
No one has been up here to help Tracy land endorsement deals, so
it's hard for him to understand, `Why does Vince have billboards?'
Well, Tank Black came up here and paid for those billboards,''
Carter said, referring to Vince Carter's agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put out a little bit to get something coming back. Tracy
is caught up in a cycle of people of telling him, `It's just
supposed to come to you.' It doesn't just come to you.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrady's agent, Arn Tellem, butted heads with Butch Carter and
Raptors management last summer when he accused the coach of not
showcasing McGrady enough. The two sides have been amicable for the
most part, but it should get interesting in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   It might be too much to ask McGrady, at his age and with his
prospects, to be patient. But there could be benefits to staying in
Toronto and building the team with Vince Carter. The two put on an
informal, abbreviated dunk contest before last Wednesday's game
against the Knicks, and it was as thrilling a pregame event as
there had been in a while at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been blocking it out, trying to concentrate on just
basketball,'' McGrady said last week. ``Something like that, you
can't control. I've tried to look at it like, the only thing I can
control is how I play on the court right now.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTING EWING'S FINES
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Latrell Sprewell, of all people, Patrick Ewing is
probably going to get back some of the money he lost two weeks ago
for not speaking to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association levied fines of $10,000
against Ewing and $25,000 against the Knicks on Dec. 8, and on Dec.
9 the Knicks fined Ewing another $10,000. Last Thursday, the
National Basketball Players Association filed a grievance on behalf
of Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   The grievance contends that the penalties amount to double
discipline, the same kind meted out to Sprewell when he choked P.J.
Carlesimo in December 1997. In that instance, the league suspended
Sprewell for a year and the Golden State Warriors terminated his
contract. Eventually, his suspension was reduced and his contract
reinstated when an arbitrator found that Sprewell was essentially
punished twice for the same transgression.
</P>
<P>
   The players then bargained for a double-discipline clause in the
new labor agreement that was signed last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a classic case of it in Patrick's case,'' said Ron
Klempner, a players union lawyer. ``The league acted one day and
the team the next. I've got to think he's got a good shot at
winning this one.`
</P>
<P>
   Credit another assist to Sprewell. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHAQ WON'T BE PACKING FOR AUSTRALIA
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of comments Shaquille O'Neal made last week in
Toronto, Alonzo Mourning should pack his bags for Sydney,
Australia. O'Neal reaffirmed his decision not to compete in the
Olympic Games, saying: ``I'm not playing. I've already got two gold
medals from international play. That's enough. It's time to give
someone else a chance and take some time off.''
</P>
<P>
   Before O'Neal's most recent comments, Rod Thorn, the National
Basketball Association's senior vice president for operations and
chairman of the USA Basketball selection committee, had not given
up hope on his playing. Responding to a report in The Sacramento
Bee this month that O'Neal would surrender his spot, Thorn said
last week: ``Shaq says a lot of things, we'll have to ascertain if
this one is true. He never told us that. Until I hear definitively,
he's still being considered.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to those comments, O'Neal said: ``I don't plan to
call the league and inform anyone. I'm not playing. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mourning fills the vacancy at center, there will still be two
slots to fill on the 12-man roster. Thorn hopes to announce the
selections the first week of January. Grant Hill seems like a
shoo-in for one spot, but there will keen competition for the 12th
spot. Eddie Jones, Ray Allen, Kobe Bryant and Shareef Abdur-Rahim
seemed to be the favorites until Raptors officials began lobbying
hard for Vince Carter. If marketing potential is a deciding factor,
then Bryant and Carter may already be the finalists. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S DOING THIS VOTING?
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby, the Knicks' dynamic young forward, is maturing
into a great role player, enough so that he could win the league's
sixth man of the year award if he does not become a starter. But
something is askew in the fan balloting when Camby receives the
fourth-most votes (76,349) among Eastern Conference forwards for
the All-Star Game and Karl Malone receives the sixth-most votes
among Western Conference forwards (50,932). Another sign of the
times: Sacramento point guard Jason Williams had 140,432 votes when
the first results were released last week, good for fourth among
West guards. John Stockton, who is quietly having a great year at
the age of 37, was sixth in the balloting, with 42,151 votes. More
people listed Vlade Divac and Lamar Odom on their ballots than they
did Stockton, a future Hall of Famer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1442EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     12-25 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY TOUCHDOWNS RATE 6 POINTS AND `R' FOR CELEBRATION; PLUS
ITEMS ON CHAD BRADZKE AND OTHERS   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ga., Md. , Ind. , Minn. , Ky., Tenn.)   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philadelphia Eagles quarterback Koy Detmer celebrated each of
his three touchdown passes last week in an unusual way. After every
touchdown Detmer would, while standing, simulate what could only be
seen as a sexual act. On the field. During the game.
</P>
<P>
   Detmer calls the move the ``whuppin' stick'' and says the
action, which includes the swaying of his hips, is his way of
dancing. Detmer's little post-touchdown show isn't original. It's
been done on some of the more raunchy music videos for years. Only
now has the move made its way to the football field. A National
Football League team official who saw Detmer's ``dance'' on a cable
sports highlights show thought, as the broadcasters did, that the
act was inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Detmer is not the only player celebrating in ways that some NFL
executives think is excessive. According to a league official, the
NFL is so concerned about an increasing number of on-field
celebrations by players _ some innocuous, others rated R _ that it
is planning to send a memo to teams in the coming days warning that
excessive celebrations will no longer be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   Game officials might then begin flagging players for dances and
other forms of celebrations more routinely, the executive said.
There may even be fines. The newer restrictions could begin in time
for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The league's competition committee might explore strengthening
already existing rules regarding celebration, or adding new ones,
no later than this off-season.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL recently banned the crude throat-slashing gesture that
was spreading like a virus. Now, the NFL feels that other forms of
celebrating are too graphic or becoming too numerous and need to be
corralled.
</P>
<P>
   In the three weekends since the NFL began fining players if they
made the throat-slashing move, it seems, anecdotally at least, that
the number of celebrations by players after touchdowns or other big
plays has increased significantly. One NFC Central player said he
had been told by teammates that players felt the NFL was constantly
trying to control their actions, and they hated it. The recent
increase in celebrations, the player speculated, was a way to
``stick it to the league'' in light of the ban on throat-slashing
gestures.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL may be criticized if it begins punishing players for
celebrating. That happened earlier this decade, when _ irritated,
as it is now, by excessive celebrations _ the league began to take
stronger measures, mainly flagging players, and members of the news
media called the NFL the ``No Fun League.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time the league should not be criticized, because
celebratory acts are spinning out of control. Some recent examples
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Atlanta several weeks ago, Falcons defensive back Ray
Buchanan intercepted a pass and returned it for a touchdown,
high-stepping all the way. He must have forgotten that the Falcons
have won only three games this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Against New Orleans last week, Baltimore Ravens defensive back
Corey Harris returned an interception 24 yards for a touchdown and,
before going into the end zone, taunted the player chasing him by
holding out the ball; it was almost stolen away. In the same game,
Ravens running back Priest Holmes excitedly threw his helmet to the
ground after scoring a touchdown. He was penalized for
unsportsmanlike conduct.
</P>
<P>
   _ Against Philadelphia, a New England player blocked a punt and
began celebrating. Meanwhile, an Eagles player picked up the nearby
ball and ran for a first down.
</P>
<P>
   _ Players are getting around the throat-slashing ban by putting
a hand to their necks, then not making the cutting motion.
</P>
<P>
   _ There are more and more group celebrations. In one being used
by an increasing number of teams after touchdowns, a half-dozen or
so players take a football, toss it in the air and fall down, as if
the ball had exploded.
</P>
<P>
   If players do not want these dances to cost them cash in the
near future, they had better get their celebrating out of their
systems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   THE GIANTS' EXTRA FAN
</P>
<P>
   There have been moments this season when Chad Bratzke has stood
on the sideline and, between glances at his breathtaking teammates
on the Indianapolis Colts' offense, stared at the scoreboard,
wondering how his old team, the Giants, was faring. Bratzke's body
may be in Indiana, but his heart, in a way, remains at the
Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   This week Bratzke, a defensive end, is sure to scoreboard surf
again. He knows how big Sunday's game is for his old team. New York
plays host to Minnesota in a game the Giants must win to keep their
slim playoff hopes alive. Bratzke has no such worries because his
team is in. His team won the American Football Conference East. His
team might win the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the twists of professional football. When Bratzke
signed with the Colts as a free agent after the 1998 season, there
were many in the sport who felt that Bratzke was nothing more than
a blue-collar player with a good attitude.
</P>
<P>
   He was never, ever, supposed to be any good without his former
teammate, the premier defensive end Michael Strahan.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of becoming a cautionary tale, however, Bratzke has
developed into a top pass rusher. This season he set the Colts'
single-season record for sacks with 12. There is nothing
blue-collar about Bratzke anymore.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much he loves his new team, a part of Bratzke will
always be indebted to the Giants. It goes beyond the fact that he
remains close to a number of players and other people throughout
the organization. Bratzke says the Giants saved his career after a
devastating knee injury, and it was Giants players who kept his
spirits high during the excruciating rehabilitation process.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants signed Bratzke out of Eastern Kentucky University as
a free agent in 1994. Each day, and each game, he got better,
eventually working his way into the starting lineup. The tough part
for Bratzke came in 1997. That year, under Jim Fassel, the Giants
made the playoffs but Bratzke missed most of the season with the
severe leg injury that almost ended his career. As the Giants
marched on to the playoffs, Bratzke sank into a state of near
depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got hurt, I thought my career was over,'' said Bratzke.
``I had torn ligaments, a fractured leg, and some nerve damage in
my leg as well. My thoughts were, `I'm done.' But Ronnie Barnes,
the trainer, and Dr. Russell Warren put me back together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough time for me because the team was winning, and
the team didn't want me on the sideline during the games, because
they thought with me on crutches, I might fall, or someone might
accidentally run into me and my knee would be destroyed. It was
that fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratzke added: ``I didn't want anyone feeling sorry for me, or
seeing me so hurt, so I did my rehab workouts when the players were
in meetings or on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates realized Bratzke's state of mind and did everything
they could to cheer him, especially Strahan and linebacker Jessie
Armstead. ``Guys went out of their way to make me feel
comfortable,'' Bratzke said. ``My leg was so bad I couldn't drive.
I had a car service. One day I was leaving the stadium, and Jessie
leaned into the rear car window and said, `Don't ever forget,
you're a part of us.' He reached in and hugged me. Michael Strahan
was great, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That year, the Giants won the division, and although Bratzke was
happy  team, he did not feel like a contributor because of
his injury. That may be why Bratzke took an extra victory lap
around the RCA Dome after Indianapolis clinched the AFC East on
Dec. 19 by beating Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember where I was, so winning a division title here is
sweet, very sweet,'' said Bratzke. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW PLAYOFF TERRITORY
</P>
<P>
   This year some playoff games will be held in unusual territory.
St. Louis, which this past week secured home-field advantage
throughout the postseason, has never been host to a playoff game,
not even when the Cardinals played there.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis has at least a first-round bye and a home playoff
game, and has also never been host to a playoff contest. Tennessee
will most likely be host for a postseason game, which would be a
first for Nashville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
