<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-GIANTS-VIKINGS-NY     12-25 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-VIKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS FIGHT THE DEMONS OF A DEBACLE AGAINST THE VIKINGS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Giants' primary focus may be on the tangible goal
of a playoff berth and the two victories that would earn it, but
it's hard to ignore the symbolism of the Minnesota Vikings' visit
to Giants Stadium Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It is one day short of the two-year anniversary of the Giants'
nationally televised implosion there in the final 90 seconds of a
playoff game against the Vikings, a devastating 23-22 defeat that
in many ways the franchise has yet to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the 1999 Giants Sunday can expunge some of the
lingering demons of that debacle, a collapse so swift, dramatic and
fraught with mischance that you would have thought the Giants were
wearing Boston Red Sox uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants lost a 9-point lead in the final minute and a half,
then walked trancelike off the Giants Stadium field in a chilling,
freezing rain.
</P>
<P>
   Had they won, the Giants would have been headed to Green Bay to
play the defending Super Bowl champions, which, win or lose, would
have been an invaluable maturation experience for what was then the
National Football League's youngest roster. Instead, for weeks,
even months after the Viking loss, the Giants seemed a wayward
team, wondering what hit them after a season of so much promise.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to note that little of that promise was
fulfilled. The Vikings playoff game was not just a loss, it was a
wound to the team's youthful feeling of invulnerability. What hurt
most was that it was the Giants' defense, which had risen
throughout 1997 as the leadership core of the team, that failed on
several levels in the end.
</P>
<P>
   In the final quarter against the Vikings two years ago, the
defense came apart for all to see. First the players quarreled,
then they played soft, then they missed assignments and then they
simply could not stop the Vikings when given several chances.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the defense did not have accomplices in its downfall.
The Giants' offense, led by quarterback Danny Kanell, could not run
out the clock after the Vikings had punted with four minutes left
and the Giants ahead by 22-13. Brad Maynard's ensuing punt traveled
only 26 yards. Minnesota's Jake Reed ran past free safety Tito
Wooten _ whose sole assignment in the prevent defense was to not
let anyone get behind him _ for a touchdown. Then, Giants wide
receiver Chris Calloway, the team's most veteran, sure-handed
player, lost a bouncing onside kick aimed right at him to set up
Minnesota's game-winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   What is also interesting to note is that with the exception of
Maynard, every one of the aforementioned Giants is no longer with
the team.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell never again played like a playoff-caliber quarterback and
lost his job 10 games later. Wooten's play fell off so
precipitously that the Giants shoved him into the expansion draft,
where even the Cleveland Browns did not want him. By the time
Wooten was eventually cut, Calloway had been set free.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had been 90 seconds from a consequential date in
Green Bay, where they would have arrived as the young and eager
National Football Conference East champions fresh off a playoff
victory. Eleven months later, they were 3-7 and reeling.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to know if the Giants have completely lifted
themselves out of the wandering descent that followed the Vikings
loss. But Sunday's game, the first time the Giants and the Vikings
have played in the two intervening years, might go a long way
toward answering that question.
</P>
<P>
   Because the lesson of the Giants' loss on Dec. 27, 1997, was
that those Giants were not ready to play with the league's upper
echelon, something borne out by their play in the months
thereafter. Sunday's game could be the exam that reveals whether
these Giants are finally ready.
</P>
<P>
   There would be something fitting about the Giants greatly
improving their playoff chances with a victory over the Vikings at
Giants Stadium _ almost exactly two years after the Vikings had
stomped on the dawning feel-good foundation of the Jim Fassel era.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sentiment not lost on some Giants. They know what they
lost two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could recapture that magic from 1997,'' said
defensive tackle Keith Hamilton, an elder of the team in his eighth
NFL season and one of the most candid of all Giants. ``That was
special.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested to Hamilton that the Vikings had ruined
the 1997 season, Hamilton said: ``They didn't ruin it. We ruined
it. We came apart at the wrong time. We unraveled. I've never seen
anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Strahan, the Giants' three-time Pro Bowler at defensive
end, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame Minnesota,'' he said. ``That's our loss. We let
it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, the Giants' coach, conceded that the 1997 loss to the
Vikings still bothered him, but he did not consider it a motivating
factor for Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a game that still sits there with me,'' he said. ``But I
don't think of this as a grudge rematch. You look on the field and
it's not the same guys.''
</P>
<P>
   On defense for the Giants, the missing include not only Wooten,
but also cornerbacks Jason Sehorn and Phillippi Sparks, who are out
with injuries, and the injured defensive tackle Robert Harris.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, there are a new quarterback and running back, three
new wide receivers and two new linemen.
</P>
<P>
   The big Minnesota passing combination is no longer Randall
Cunningham to Reed, but Jeff George to Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the last time Fassel's team was tested in a playoff
atmosphere _ which is what one can expect Sunday at Giants Stadium
_ it was two years ago against Minnesota. What has changed?
</P>
<P>
   As Hamilton said: ``We're not the youngest team in the league
anymore and we're running out of excuses. Now, we've got to decide
if we're an 8-8 team like last year or whether we're getting any
better.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, are the Giants picking up where they left off
the last time Minnesota came to visit just after Christmas, or are
they putting the past behind them to build a new era of prosperity?
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
