<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8894 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LABOR-FIGHT-ART-2TAKE     12-25 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABOR-FIGHT-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
15-MONTH LABOR DISPUTE AT KAISER TURNS INTO WAR OF ATTRITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Texas, Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 4 and 5 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPOKANE, Wash. _ The 15-month struggle between Kaiser Aluminum
and the United Steelworkers of America is one of the biggest,
longest and fiercest labor disputes in years, but it is far more
than an old-fashioned labor war. It is a war of attrition, a test
of wills and a propaganda war against the billionaire Texan who
controls Kaiser, a man the union denounces as a latter-day robber
baron.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a battle over two clashing visions of the future of
the American workplace. Kaiser's workers say they deserve job
security in return for their hard work, while management favors
contracting out hundreds of jobs as part of a drive to minimize
costs and increase competitiveness, even if it means dropping
longtime employees.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 15, 1998, the steelworkers' union went on strike
against Kaiser's five aluminum plants after rejecting the company's
demand to cut health benefits and eliminate 240 jobs by contracting
work to lower-paying nonunion companies. Then in January, with the
strikers disheartened from four months without a paycheck, union
leaders told Kaiser that the strikers wanted to go back to work
while the two sides continued negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaiser took an unusual step, imposing a lockout and refusing
to let any of the union's members return unless the union accepted
Kaiser's demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a slap in the face,'' said Dean Wise, a 21-year veteran
of the mills whose family is scraping by thanks to his wife's job
at Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   The company lockout was also a severe blow to Spokane, a
blue-collar city of 180,000, where Kaiser is the second-largest
private employer. Two of Kaiser's five aluminum plants and 2,000 of
its unionized 2,900 workers are based in this city, which is known
for bloody union battles early this century.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two mornings each week, in the shadow of the
evergreen-covered Mica Mountains, Wise braves the biting dawn chill
and pickets outside a gigantic erector set of a mill that heats
aluminum, stretches it out and rolls it smooth. Huddled next to an
oil drum filled with burning firewood, the pickets use bullhorns to
heap abuse on the replacement workers as they drive in and out,
calling them ``scabs'' and worse. Under federal rules, Kaiser's
lockout bars any union members from working.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who showed me pictures when their kids were born, now
they're crossing the picket line,'' said his wife, Wendy Wise, a
leader of a support group called Spouses of Steel. ``It's real
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers complain about how much the company has changed
since its glory days under Henry Kaiser, the industrialist who
built Hoover Dam, Grand Coulee Dam and many of the ships in the
World War II Navy. He was renowned for his generosity toward
employees and for being a pioneer in providing employer-financed
health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser is now controlled by a very different man, Charles E.
Hurwitz, whose Houston-based holding company, Maxxam Inc., controls
63 percent of Kaiser's shares. In the 1980s, he rocketed to
prominence as a corporate raider, acquiring Simplicity Patterns and
Pacific Lumber _ the target of thousands of environmental
protesters because of its aggressive cutting of California
redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is suing Hurwitz, seeking $820 million,
saying that he and his company contributed to the collapse of the
United Savings Association of Texas in 1988. The bailout of the
savings and loan cost taxpayers $1.6 billion and was the
third-largest in the nation's history. Hurwitz's spokesmen say that
the suit is unfounded and that the savings and loan collapsed not
because of mismanagement, but because of Texas' economic problems
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Hurwitz acquired control of Kaiser in 1987, and labor relations
have soured ever since as Kaiser has sought to reduce its work
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry J. Kaiser believed that the people who ran the plant
were valuable assets, and he treated them that way,'' said Tim
Charboneau, a millworker. ``Hurwitz just seems to want to throw
people away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Milchovich, Kaiser's chief executive, defended the company's
cost cutting, insisting that it aimed not just to increase profits,
but to preserve jobs long-term by keeping the company in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are high-cost plants battling for survival in a very
competitive industry,'' he said. ``To sit and argue over what level
of slop, what level of lack of productivity is appropriate in the
year 2000 and beyond in a very competitive business is ridiculous.
Who does that benefit? It certainly doesn't benefit employees, and
it certainly doesn't benefit the shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   For many workers, the lockout has cast a pall over the holiday
season, even with the union giving everyone $140 a week, running a
foodbank and providing emergency payments to make sure no families
lose their homes or primary vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some workers have stopped giving allowances to their teen-agers
because they can no longer afford it. Many families have been
forced to sell their second cars. And many workers grumble about
not being able to afford presents for their children or
grandchildren, although the United Steelworkers, with donations
from other unions, has arranged a $25 gift certificate for each
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm barely making it,'' said Rolfe Lauren, a machine operator.
``I've had to take $8,000 to $9,000 out of my savings to pay my
bills. It's tough right now. But sacrifices have to be made to win
this fight, and that's fine by me.''
</P>
<P>
   Children are also pitching in. Dan Giachetti, a metal
transporter, said, ``My 15-year-old daughter is doing a lot of
baby-sitting. She's doing this to help the family out anyway she
can. I'm humbled to tears. I don't tell her no because it's her way
of helping.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, though, some workers insist that Christmas 1999 is
their best holiday ever, offering reasons that are hard for
outsiders to appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   Many workers have marveled not only at their own fortitude, but
at that of their friends. They say the struggle has forged lasting
friendships the way war does. And they are amazed that co-workers
they once dismissed as muscle-bound grunts have turned into leaders
and sometimes heroes.
</P>
<P>
   For many workers, this is a Christmas when solidarity and
togetherness are the most precious gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Viebrock, a data-entry worker, offered a bittersweet smile
when she acknowledged not being able to buy gifts for her two
daughters this Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about getting back to basics,'' she said. ``We've
talked about what Christmas really means, and materialism isn't
where it's at. It's about singing Christmas carols and making
Christmas cookies.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The workers, who average about $14 an hour, voice a sense of
betrayal. They say that in 1984 they accepted a $4.50-an-hour cut
in wages and benefits to keep Kaiser competitive, with an implicit
promise that those concessions would be made up in good times,
something they say has never happened. A decade later, in 1994, the
workers agreed to new concessions, worth $50 million, under which
each worker took on more responsibilities, a move that resulted in
cutting the work force at one Spokane mill to 1,100 from 1,400.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked with them to trim jobs and combine jobs and they
said there'd be no more cuts,'' said Wes Beck, president of that
mill's union local. ``They said they wouldn't throw any more of the
work over the fence, and now they come back and say they want to
throw all these other jobs over the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser officials insist that the company made no such promises.
``The argument that there have been some broken promises or broken
trust is a false accusation,'' said Jeremy Sherman, Kaiser's chief
labor negotiator. He said the company would cut the number of
employees at the plants largely through attrition, and was offering
the workers a $3.13-an-hour wage increase over five years in
exchange for increased productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives say Kaiser needs to reduce costs continually
to compete with larger rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcoa is far stronger than Kaiser is,'' Sherman said. ``Its
plants are newer, larger and operate with far greater efficiency.
Unless Kaiser can find ways to compete more effectively, the world
of the future will not treat companies like Kaiser kindly.''
</P>
<P>
   But union leaders say that Kaiser was already prospering before
the strike, thanks to their concessions.
</P>
<P>
   To squeeze the company, the steelworkers have formed an unusual
alliance with environmentalists, backing their efforts to stop
Hurwitz's cutting of California redwoods. Together, they crowded
into Maxxam's shareholders meeting outside Houston in May, and they
ran two candidates, Howard Metzenbaum, former U.S. senator, and
Abner Mikva, a former White House counsel, for seats on Maxxam's
board. The union candidates lost, but they received 40 percent of
the votes not controlled by Hurwitz.
</P>
<P>
   The union has dispatched more than a dozen workers around the
country to urge Kaiser customers to stop buying aluminum from
Kaiser until it ends the lockout. In a blow to Kaiser, Pepsi
Bottling Co. announced this fall that it would stop buying Kaiser
aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the union is playing what could prove to be its
trump card. The union, with its environmental friends and its
allies in state legislatures and in Congress, is urging Bonneville
Power Administration to stop providing Kaiser with low-cost,
subsidized hydroelectric power on the ground that it is not a good
corporate citizen.
</P>
<P>
   If the union could persuade the power authority, a federal
agency, Kaiser's electricity rates would soar, making the company
immediately uncompetitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying that people who receive preferred rates
subsidized by everyone else should be held accountable,'' said
Larry Strom, a smelter worker. ``They shouldn't be locking out
their work force or trashing the environment. What's going on now
is not right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
