<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-OCONNOR-MASS-ART-N     12-25 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OCONNOR-MASS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MIDNIGHT , CARDINAL O'CONNOR FINDS STRENGTH FOR ONE MORE
CHRISTMAS MASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo, NYT11, has been sent. Non-subscribers can
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JANE GROSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Weakened by illness and close to retirement, Cardinal
John O'Connor was determined to celebrate midnight Mass with New
Yorkers Friday, perhaps for the last time, and so all week he
conserved his limited energy.
</P>
<P>
   His legs were weak, his speech slurred and his face puffy from
the side effects of treatment for a brain tumor. But the cardinal
found a way, nonetheless, to play his accustomed role on one of the
holiest nights of the Christian calendar.
</P>
<P>
   In the vaulted spaces of St. Patrick's Cathedral, decked with
wreaths and sweet with incense, the spiritual leader of New York's
2.4 million Roman Catholics sat in a chair for his homily rather
than climbing to the marble pulpit. From that plain perch, his
voice strong, he offered a tentative goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much time will be granted me here in New York, I don't
know,'' O'Connor said to more than 3,000 worshipers, referring to
his impending retirement more than his brush with mortality. ``I
must use this opportunity to thank every single one of you for the
privilege of trying to serve you to the best of my abilities,
limited though that has been.''
</P>
<P>
   Was the cardinal, who holds the church's most visible post in
the United States, being modest about his 15-year tenure as
archbishop of the New York archdiocese? Or was he referring to the
four months of his illness, when he has been forced to skip several
Sunday Masses or limit himself to a brief homily? It was impossible
to tell, but of little interest to the worshipers, who were simply
glad to see him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was praying he would make Christmas Mass because he wanted
it so badly,'' said Alice Krause, in a pew with her three children
while her husband served as an usher.
</P>
<P>
   According to Joseph Zwilling, spokesman for the archdiocese,
O'Connor followed doctor's instructions ``not to overextend
himself'' in the days before Christmas, conserving his energy in
the hope that he could celebrate the 90-minute Mass, including long
periods on his feet preparing the Eucharist.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal's condition since his brain surgery has been up and
down, good one day, bad the next. ``He had the mindset he would be
able to do it,'' Zwilling said. ``But there are also physical
realities. All I can say is he is a tough man.''
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal, regardless of his illness, faces retirement in the
very near future. In accord with church law, he submitted his
resignation to Pope John Paul II, his doctrinal soul mate, on his
75th birthday. The pope, however, has yet to accept it and so
O'Connor remains in his highly visible post. Upon turning 80 next
year, he automatically loses his vote in Vatican affairs, including
the election of the next pope. At that point, he is expected to be
replaced and step down.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, this Christmas Mass was likely his last.
</P>
<P>
   It began with the congregants facing the rear of the cathedral.
There, in a special ceremony, the huge brass doors were thrown open
to herald the start of the jubilee year 2000, as decreed by the
pope. It was during this ceremony that the cardinal took his place
at the high altar, an unaccustomed spot that reduced the need to
walk or climb stairs.
</P>
<P>
   When the doors opened, a rush of cold air filled the cathedral.
Outside, iridescent from the holiday lights, was the statue of
Prometheus at Rockefeller Center. Thousands of people drew in their
breath, then turned to the altar and the welcome sight of their
ailing cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   Some guessed that O'Connor had made his entry when they were
turned, so it would go unnoticed that he needed help getting in and
out of his chair. But he immediately silenced the worried whispers
with a series of his customary jokes, spoofing a tabloid headline
about his Christmas plans and welcoming an old friend beaming from
the third row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am informed Ed Koch is in place,'' the cardinal said. ``So
we can proceed with the ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's homily, which can be provocative enough to attract
news coverage on many Sundays, was low-key and homespun. In setting
the stage for a plea for love and harmony, he spoke of his doctors
at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, one a Jew and the other
Asian. ``Each one treats me, however, with such gentleness, with
such a sense of worth,'' the archbishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus ``suffered to make it possible for each of us to love,''
O'Connor continued. ``Without that suffering there would be no way
of our truly understanding and loving one another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But could anything, in the final analysis, really mean more
than that we love one another with a gentleness, with a true
profound love?''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the cathedral _ including people in mink coats and
others in rags, prominent worshipers like Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani
and Imelda Marcos, and at least one couple who got engaged during
the Mass _ spoke of the cardinal's acts of love.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Bedin said she shared an elevator with O'Connor on a visit
to the Vatican, where she had gone for a blessing of a picture of
her deceased father. The cardinal, learning of her loss, offered to
say a private Mass on the spot and has counseled her since.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Philip Luloff, a psychiatrist at Mount Sinai Medical Center
and a friend of Ms. Bedin, said he had sought advice from the
cardinal about treating dying patients. Some were helped by the
religious leader's example in dealing with his own illness. Others
found comfort, Luloff said, in shaking his hand once they knew he
had shaken hands with O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Luloff, quick to identify himself as Jewish, said he was
exhilarated, not saddened, by the service. ``This man cannot say
goodbye,'' he said. ``He is part and parcel of New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
