<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 12/25/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- NEWYEAR-SITTERS -- So many
children, so few sitters and so much money. So what exactly does
the supply-demand calculus work out to if parents are in the
lamentable position of needing a baby sitter for New Year's Eve?
Hard to say, since as yet there's no Internet baby-sitter
warehouse, no Click 'n' Sit.com, for easy tracking of prices. But
reports are coming in about millennial partygoers facing tabs of
$30 an hour in Memphis, $45 in Boston and $50 in New York. And up.
(Susan B. Markisz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- ENUFF-EHYPE-REVIEW -- The
restroom at Alt.Coffee, a New York cyber cafe. The surest sign that
the Internet is totally mainstream: Everyone is tired of it, not
just the sleep-starved workers at dot-com startups, but everyone.
(Fred Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- -NY-TIMES-SQUARE-SECURE --
A bustling Times Square on Dec. 20. Against a backdrop of almost
daily government warnings about potential terrorist acts around the
country, the authorities are readying an elaborate plan to keep
Times Square's millennial celebration safe. The plan includes
deploying 8,000 police officers in the area. The ball which drops
to usher in the new year falls from No. 1 Times Square, the
building at center. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- NY-OCONNOR-MASS -- Cardinal
John O'Connor delivers the homily during Midnight Mass at St.
Patrick's Cathedral. Weakened by illness and close to retirement,
O'Connor was determined to celebrate midnight Mass with New Yorkers
Saturday, perhaps for the last time. (Chang W. Lee/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- CHRISTMASS-DOLL -- Cearlie
Lewis, 85, looks at a doll she received for Christmas from Little
Brothers Friends of the Elderly, an organization that whose
volunteers visit the elderly, on Saturday, Christmas day. Lewis, a
retired child care worker, has 68 dolls in her collection, part of
which is seen in the background. Lewis says she began to collect
dolls as an adult because when she was a little girl growing up in
Montgomery, Ala., her parents could not afford to buy her one.
(Evan Richman/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- OBIT-JAFFIN -- George M.
Jaffin, a retired Manhattan lawyer and art patron who started one
of the nation's first lare-scale law school loan forgiveness
programs for public-interest lawyers, died Thursday at a hospital
in White Plains, N.Y. He was 94. Jaffin is seen in a 1982 file
photo. (The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- OBIT-TAYLOR -- John W. R.
Taylor, the longtime editor of ``Jane's All the World's Aircraft,
the authoritative guide to aviation, died on Dec. 12 in a London
suburb at the age of 77. The cause of death was not disclosed.
Taylor, seen in a 1974 photo, was particularly respected for his
ability to obtain informatin about military aircraft. (William E.
Sauro/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK-- Dec. 25, 1999 -- CAGE-OBIT -- Betty Cage, an
administrator of the New York City Ballet who played a quiet but
important role in creating the company, died on Sunday in New York.
She was 82. Ms. Cage is seen in a 1982 file photo. Her title for
many years was simply general manager, but Ms. Cage was a linchpin
of the City Ballet. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LOS ANGELES -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- -RETIREE-EDUC -- Ruth
Gussen, center, the president of the Plato Society, made a point
during a break in a session with, from left, Dan Palmer, Ed
Bressler and Margery Gould. The society, with 375 members, was
founded at U.C.L.A. 19 years ago to provide educational stimulation
for retirees. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MEAD, Wash. -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- LABOR-FIGHT-1 -- The
United Steelworkers went on strike against Kaiser Aluminum's five
plants in September 1998, and both sides have waged a fiece battle
since. Several workers picketed at a Kaiser smelter last week.
(Jeff T. Green/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SPOKANE, Wash. -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- LABOR-FIGHT-1 --
Sheryl Scott and her son William, 5, gathered food at the United
Steelworkers Local 329 food bank last week. Mrs. Scott's husband
joined other union workers in a strike against Kaiser Aluminum in
1998 and was later locked out. The Scotts have five children. (Jeff
T. Green/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- NY-IMMIG-2 -- A collection
of store signs in Woodside, Queens, where many languages are
spoken. As the century draws to a close, one in three city
residents in this area is an immigrant and, of those, nearly half
are newly minted New Yorkers who arrived only in the last 15 years.
Not since 1910, at the peak of this century's great wave of
immigration through Ellis Island, has the ration of newcomers been
soo high. (Jeffery A. Salter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- NY-IMMIG -- The walk from
school on Roosevelt Avenue in Woodside, Queens, where many
languages are spoken. At the end of the century, one in three city
residents here is an immigrant and, of those, nearly half are newly
minted New Yorkers who arrived only in the last 15 years. Not since
1910, at the peak of this century's great wave of immigration
through Ellis Island, has the ration of newcomers been soo high.
(James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) OMAHA, Nebraska -- Dec. 25, 1999 -- EXCESS-REVIEW -- Some
15,000 shareholders came to Berkshire Hathaway's annual-meeting in
May. Among the events: Fistful-of-dollars ornaments were also for
sale. There is so much money sloshing around that it seems to have
overwhelmed the last vestiges of Puritan guilt over spending it.
(Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
