</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORYCOAST-COUP-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVORY COAST COUP DRAWS FRENCH RESPONSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In the wake of a coup in Ivory Coast, France said
Saturday that it was sending small numbers of troops to the country
_ its former colony _ to protect the deposed president and to
evacuate roughly 20,000 French nationals should that become
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   But Agence France-Presse reported Saturday night that Ivory
Coast's new ruler was refusing entry to the soldiers, saying their
presence could ``lead to a blood bath.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy in Abidjan, the country's largest city, warned
American citizens there to lock themselves in their homes. It said
looters were rampaging through the wealthy neighborhoods where
foreigners live, but seemed to be attacking only vehicles parked
outside.
</P>
<P>
   France has about 550 troops in a garrison where ousted President
Henri Konan Bedie was reported to have taken sanctuary from the
coup.
</P>
<P>
   Reports said 40 more soldiers were ready to arrive by helicopter
from Libreville, Gabon. A further 300 French soldiers were reported
ready to fly in from Dakar, the capital of Senegal, if needed. At
the moment there is no apparent threat to French residents of Ivory
Coast, but there has been looting and gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Paris has condemned the coup and granted protection to Bedie.
Agence France-Presse quoted a French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman,
Anne Gazeau-Secret, as saying that Bedie, at his request, was at
the Port-Bouet military base next to the Abidjan airport, under the
protection of the French 43rd Marine Infantry Battalion.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Robert Guei, the coup leader, had said earlier that Bedie
should leave the country quickly because his life could be in
danger, but had stipulated that his Cabinet could not leave.
</P>
<P>
   The French government, which years ago gave up trying to control
the affairs of its former colonies, has not demanded a restoration
of Bedie to power. Instead, it has called for the immediate
re-establishment of order and security. News reports here were
sketchy because it was Christmas Day and the coup caught almost
everyone by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Ivory Coast has long been an island of relative stability and
prosperity in the former French colonies. It is the world's biggest
supplier of cocoa, and it produces palm oil and other tropical
products. Many French sun-worshippers interested in vacationing in
Africa head first for Abidjan and use it as a jumping-off spot for
poorer countries. There are regular Air France and Air Afrique
flights. The new military leaders said Abidjan airport, closed by
the coup, would reopen on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Abidjan, the commercial capital, looks in some ways like a
French city; it has the same black-and-white arrow-shaped signs,
traffic circles and red-and-white stone road markers. There are
luxury hotels, nightclubs and restaurants, and the same stores and
brands that are in France can be seen there.
</P>
<P>
   Its government has been stable compared with those of other
former colonies like Congo, Madagascar or the Comoro Islands. As a
supplier of tropical products that cannot be grown farther north,
Ivory Coast has become an important part of the French economy.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, France had a much more interventionist policy in
Africa than Britain, Portugal or other former colonial powers did.
It diplomatically embraced rulers that it approved of, but it also
was ready to send troops _ often the Foreign Legion _ to prop up or
restore presidents it favored.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, that contributed to more stable rule in former
French colonies than existed in Portuguese or Belgian ones. But in
other ways, it contributed to resentment of rulers, who were
perceived as puppets of France.
</P>
<P>
   In Abidjan on Saturday, the leader of the new ruling junta,
Guei, imposed a dusk-to-dawn curfew after two nights of looting and
sporadic gunfire in some districts. He warned that violators would
be shot.
</P>
<P>
   The streets of Abidjan were reported empty Saturday. Its stores
had been closed for 48 hours, but a curfew on Friday night did not
stop looting. The French radio reported a small skirmish between
Ivorian soldiers and French gendarmes, but the details were
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Bedie was overthrown on Friday when Guei, a former armed-forces
chief, took the reins of power after troops mutinied. He set up a
10-man junta and urged politicians of the governing Democratic
Party and the opposition to engage in what he called consultations
to form a government of national unity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Guei had been asking that France evacuate Bedie, whose calls for
resistance against the coup appeared to have been fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   Agence France-Presse quoted military experts as saying that the
reinforcement of French troops in the region was aimed at securing
Abidjan's airport in case it was necessary to evacuate foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The French regional deployment comes with the risk of
destabilization of one of the pillars of Paris' influence in West
Africa. Officials said Saturday that warnings of caution had been
repeated regularly to French nationals in Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between France and the country, which was long seen as
a model African democracy and a relative economic powerhouse, have
deteriorated in the last few months because of differences between
Bedie and Alassane Ouattara, a former prime minister and deputy
director of the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Ouattara, seen as a serious challenger to the long rule of the
Democratic Party, had sought to take on Bedie in elections next
year, but the president's government barred him from running, on
grounds that his parents were not Ivorians. This tactic of
excluding rivals from elections has become common in Africa in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Some French press comment on Saturday was equally severe with
regard both to Bedie and to France's approach to its former colony.
For the center-left newspaper Liberation, the tardy French reaction
to the deteriorating political situation was ``a triple failure in
political, military and diplomatic terms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
