<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLEANAIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NO RETREAT ON CLEAN AIR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, December 26:
</P>
<P>
   Early last summer, clean-air advocates were on the run.
Back-to-back rulings in May by conservative, anti-regulatory judges
in the Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit had shredded much of
the administration's air pollution strategy, invalidating tough new
federal health standards and blocking efforts to reduce smog in the
eastern half of the United States. But in some mysterious way the
ruling seemed to stiffen the resolve of federal and state
officials, and ever since then the big polluters have been the ones
on the run. In the last week alone, the Clinton administration
issued several major rulings that will require big investments by
the oil, automobile and utility companies to reduce smog-causing
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The most important of these rulings will require automakers to
build cleaner vehicles and oil companies to refine cleaner
gasoline. Taken together, these measures should reduce pollutants
in standard cars by about 75 percent from today's levels. But the
most important aspect of the ruling is that it will subject
so-called light trucks _ sport utility vehicles, pickup trucks and
minivans _ to essentially the same requirements as ordinary cars.
Until now, light trucks have been allowed to produce up to three
times the pollution of standard cars because regulators have
classified them as work vehicles, even though they now account for
about half of all new-car purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Both the automakers and the oil companies grumbled about the
costs of the new rules, which will add perhaps $200 to the price of
a sport utility vehicle and a few pennies to a gallon of gasoline.
But there was less grumbling than usual, for two reasons. One is
that all the major presidential candidates have endorsed tougher
rules. The other was a decision over a year ago by Carol Browner,
the administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency, to spread
the cost of the cleanup by asking the oil companies to reduce the
sulfur content in gasoline. This will make it easier for the car
makers to meet the new targets because sulfur clogs up a vehicle's
catalytic converter, the device that cleans car exhaust of
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   Another ruling, announced by Ms. Browner earlier this month,
would give 400 utilities and manufacturing plants in 12 states
until 2003 to cut by half the pollutants that are blown eastward by
prevailing winds, adding to smog in the Northeast. The ruling _
made in response to four northeastern states that are seeking
relief from windblown pollution _ is only the latest of several
efforts to crack down on the aging, coal-fired power plants in the
Midwestern and border states that lie at the root of some of the
country's biggest pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   In separate actions, for example, the EPA and New York's
attorney general, Eliot Spitzer, have sued more than 30 such plants
for allegedly failing to install anti-pollution equipment in
violation of the Clean Air Act. Meanwhile, Gov. George Pataki has
ordered New York's own power plants to cut the emissions that cause
smog and acid rain. The governor has also promised to impose new
emissions standards on cars sold in New York that he says will be
even stronger than those announced by President Clinton last
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has happened since the disheartening court decisions
in May and despite dire predictions that in an election year
neither the administration nor politicians with possible national
aspirations, like Pataki, would risk offending pivotal Midwestern
states and big industries. These fears, fortunately, appear to have
been premature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1657EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
