<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8928 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TREKS-NYT &LR;      12-25 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TREKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE GLORY OF EARTH TREKS AND STAR TREKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, December 26:
</P>
<P>
   The last millennium encompassed the great age of geographic
discovery, when hardy explorers penetrated the world's landmasses
and mapped the great oceans that, much to everyone's surprise,
turned out to cover 70 percent of the globe. So accessible has the
Earthace become that today adventurers scale Everest and
hike across Antarctica, tourists traverse Africa, and lone sailors
circumnavigate the globe. Even the ocean depths, the last great
frontier on Earth, have begun to yield their secrets to undersea
explorers, revealing a world seething with bizarre life forms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the millennium draws to a close, the frontier that
beckons lies far overhead. Thirty years ago, Neil Armstrong took
humanity's first small step on the moon, declaring it ``one giant
leap for mankind,'' only to have the space program retreat to
tinkering in low Earth orbit. The question for the next century is
whether this nation and others should invest heavily in space
exploration, sending astronauts to Mars and unmanned probes to
distant star systems, or use those resources instead to make the
planet we inhabit a place no one would dream of leaving.
</P>
<P>
   A thousand years ago, most people knew little of what lay beyond
their immediate localities. Then, in the 13th and 14th centuries,
Marco Polo and others followed overland routes to the Far East,
returning with wondrous tales and goods. When those routes were
closed, Western Europeans turned to the seas in search of new
pathways.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese, the first to make exploration a state
enterprise, pushed down the coast of Africa and around to India.
Columbus, seeking a westward route to Asia, discovered a continent
whose existence he had not imagined. Magellan found the sea route
around South America and died while circumnavigating the globe. The
great age of oceanic exploration lasted three centuries and brought
a change in perspective. The sea, once a barrier, was now a highway
that led everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on land, Spanish explorers pushed into most of
Central and South America, English and French explorers traveled
North America, and Lewis and Clark charted the American West. In
the 19th century, explorers reached the interiors of Africa and
Australia, and the coast of Antarctica. One decade into the 20th
century, the last recesses, at the North and South Poles, were
finally reached.
</P>
<P>
   The Age of Exploration had been largely a European enterprise,
driven by a mix of motives. The primary focus was a search for
trade routes and riches, buttressed by a missionary zeal to convert
the heathen, a drive for colonies, a thirst for knowledge about the
natural world and a lust for the glory of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few of these motives are relevant to plumbing the ocean.
Salvagers seek to retrieve gold from wrecked treasure ships on the
ocean floor, and scientists seek new knowledge using undersea
technologies originally developed for military purposes. But
entrepreneurs who had hoped to mine the seabed for minerals can
only wait for the economics to look better. The difficulty of
operating in inky blackness under the crushing weight of the sea
has ensured that progress will be slow. With only one-tenth of 1
percent of the deep seabed explored, we know less about it than
about the surface of Mars.
</P>
<P>
   As space enthusiasts gaze longingly at the solar system and the
heavens beyond, they are entering a realm where few of the usual
motives for exploration apply. The race to the moon was propelled
by the struggle against Soviet Communism. Once that race had been
won, the nation turned to less far-reaching efforts, like the
international space station now under construction in low orbit.
That is not the sort of venture to set pulses racing.
</P>
<P>
   The best rationale for space exploration is to gain scientific
knowledge and to search for life forms elsewhere, a task performed
most cheaply and safely by unmanned probes. But the idea of sending
astronauts to other planets remains a powerful, animating force.
Some space officials predict that humans will be walking on Mars
within two decades, or at least by mid-century.
</P>
<P>
   Visionaries are good at dreaming up reasons for such an arduous,
three-year excursion _ the need to fulfill our destiny, to find
extra resources and living space, to guarantee survival of the
human species should an asteroid hit Earth. But the most compelling
reason for humans to set foot on Mars is for the sheer thrill and
glory of it. That passion should be indulged only when new tactics
and technologies bring the costs and risks down to bearable levels,
or private financing can be found. Meanwhile, there are even more
formidable challenges _ in eliminating poverty, eradicating disease
and educating the ignorant _ to be faced here on Earth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1702EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
