<HEADER>
A8929 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CYCLING-TEAM-TURMOIL-     12-25 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-TEAM-TURMOIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COFIDIS TEAM CAPTAIN WALKS OUT ON HIS CONTRACT
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Cofidis bicycle team staged quite a bash here last
week, celebrating the holiday season by inviting dozens of friends,
riders, officials, employees and journalists to watch a show, lift
a glass or three and then tuck into dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Since Cofidis is one of the better-managed teams, with bracing
involvement by its sponsor, a telephone credit system in France,
everything should have been first rate, with nothing out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Except this: Somebody chose to have the festivities at the
Cirque d'Hiver, the Winter Circus. Imagine the gallows humor as
people noted how so much about Cofidis has been a circus lately.
With everything else that has been going on, who needed Bogino the
acrobat, Helene and her parrots and the fire juggler?
</P>
<P>
   Life under the big top began Dec. 1, when the team's leader,
Frank Vandenbroucke, announced through spokesmen in Belgium, that
he was walking out on his contract, which had another year to run.
Riders rarely walk out on their contracts, especially not at the
end of the year when rosters have been decided and replacements are
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can ask, is Frank Vandenbroucke really adult and
responsible?'' said the director-general of the sponsor, Francois
Migraine. ``For sure he's a great champion, but he seems to lack a
certain balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking the moral high ground, Migraine added that Cofidis would
not raid another team for a leader.
</P>
<P>
   Vandenbroucke, a 25-year-old Belgian often known as VDB, said
that he could not stay because of his two-month suspension by the
team after he was held by the Paris police in a drug case last
spring. He charged that the team had committed ``grave and
excessive faults'' against him and damaged his reputation by
suspending him, even though it was at full pay. Vandenbroucke was
not charged in the case, but admitted indiscretions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to jumping ship, the rider plans to sue Cofidis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the papers to be filed shortly in Paris,'' Alain
Bondue, the team's manager, said by telephone. Bondue said that
Vandenbroucke is seeking $1.84 million in damages, or roughly twice
his salary this year.
</P>
<P>
   Migraine said: ``We don't seem to have luck with our leaders.
``First it was Fondriest, then Armstrong, then Casagrande, now
this.'' Since the team began in 1997, Maurizio Fondriest and Lance
Armstrong were lost to injuries and illness and Francesco
Casagrande was let go last year after he failed a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   Vandenbroucke seemed to be the answer, as he won the esteemed
Liege-Bastogne-Liege classic this year and finished 12th in the
Tour of Spain, winning two daily stages, and seventh in the world
championship road race. But at that road race in Italy in October,
he began listening to offers from other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Since his announcement, Vandenbroucke has remained silent.
Periodically, a spokesman says the rider has been in contact with
various teams _ ONCE in Spain and the new Fasso Bortolo team in
Italy are usually cited _ seeking a job for next season, although
the Italian team's head, Giancarlo Ferretti, said that he was no
longer interested.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, Vandenbroucke's salary demands and the probability
that Cofidis will have to be paid damages outweighed the 1,818
International Cycling Union points that the rider will bring with
him. Those points would give a new team entry to major races, where
entries are determined by team ranking. Those points will also be
subtracted from the Cofidis total, virtually dropping the team into
the second division.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, Bondue insisted. ``We'll do fine,'' he said. ``The
team was shocked, especially since he quit the day before we had a
training camp, but morale is high. Sometimes, when you lose a
leader, that frees everybody to ride his own race and maybe even
win it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1707EST &QL; 
