<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-3TAKES-     12-25 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL AND GREED MAKE ROOM FOR THE RICHNESS OF VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a certain fin de siecle urgency to the past year, the
sensation of rushing willy-nilly toward some brave new sports world
even more expensive, aggressive, chemical and hyperbolic than the
past.
</P>
<P>
   As the numbers hovered eerily between 99 and 00, the entire
world seemed mad with dot.com gold-rush avarice. Free agents jumped
teams with abandon, juveniles leaped from high school to
professional basketball, franchises went for epic prices.
</P>
<P>
   Scandal was everywhere. The Olympic movement, trying to revive
the alleged ideals of ancient Greece, was as jaded as the rest of
humanity. Some International Olympic Committee delegates and bid
cities were caught in a tango of corruption. Eventually, 10
delegates left the IOC and a handful of officials in Salt Lake City
took the blame for the sordid communal effort.
</P>
<P>
   As more evidence piled in from the past (Atlanta and Nagano) and
the future (Sydney), there were calls for Juan Antonio Samaranch to
resign as president. But Samaranch craftily produced so-called
reform measures, while remaining judge and jury of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   At year's end, fearing the loss of American corporate support,
Samaranch essentially told a congressional subcommittee: ``Trust
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of sport remained a competition among chemists, with hot
drugs and masking agents lurking in many athletes' systems.
</P>
<P>
   For all the chicanery, sport was occasionally compelling.
Perhaps the sweetest event in 1999 came from the overlapping worlds
of soccer and women's sports, both normally shunned by the big guys
of American journalism.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup, with charismatic stars like Michelle
Akers and Briana Scurry, packed major stadiums in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The finals were held in the Rose Bowl, normally the province of
prancing female cheerleaders and strutting American football
players. On July 10, more than 40 million Americans watched on the
tube and 90,185 fans jammed the bowl as the United States defeated
China on penalty kicks after 120 scoreless but nonetheless gripping
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 positive and talented players became the nation's
darlings, raising hopes for a league and raising endorsement money
for women with muscles and elbows. Probably inevitably, before
year's end the women were threatening to abandon a January tour to
Australia because of contract problems.
</P>
<P>
   Another compelling event of the fin de siecle was the Ryder Cup
of golf, a biennial competition between the United States and
Europe. In Brookline, Mass., in late September, the United States
was trailing, 10-6, going into the final day of head-to-head
matches, but a 45-foot birdie putt by Justin Leonard on the 17th
hole helped the Americans win, 14{-13{.
</P>
<P>
   There was criticism that golfers and fans had celebrated
prematurely and blatantly, but the enthusiasm and skill of normally
sedate golfers could hook a larger public.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, in winning their third World Series in four years,
touched even some traditional Yankee-haters. Objectively, they did
not match their 1998 total of 125 victories. Subjectively, they did
even better, with feisty old Don Zimmer filling in (and sassing the
Boss on occasion) while Joe Torre was treated for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In this glorious summer, David Cone pitched a perfect game,
Darryl Strawberry rebounded from cancer and a flareup of his
addictions, and Derek Jeter and Bernie Williams and Orlando ``El
Duque'' Hernandez charmed the nation. The Yanks beat the Braves
four straight, and have now won 12 straight World Series games.
</P>
<P>
   Some big-market teams like the Yankees, the Braves and the Mets
flourished, while a few small-market teams like Cincinnati and
Oakland produced unpredictably good seasons. Big bucks did not work
for the insipid Dodgers of Rupert Murdoch and the dreary Orioles of
Peter Angelos.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets staged a rousing autumn, surviving a seven-game losing
streak and stunning Arizona in the postseason. Down three games to
none against Atlanta, they played three straight thrillers before
succumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez of Boston was the best pitcher in baseball with a
23-4 record and a 2.07 earned run average and 313 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   After their 70-66 home-run derby in 1998, Mark McGwire again
beat Sammy Sosa, 65-63, but there was the air of a sideshow because
neither's team was in contention. Midway through the season,
McGwire claimed he had stopped taking the legal but questionable
body-building substance androstenedione. He said he had not
disclosed his decision earlier because nobody asked.
</P>
<P>
   During the World Series, swaggering and suspended Pete Rose was
voted onto an all-century team, taking attention from the Aarons
and the Williamses.
</P>
<P>
   Two foreign baseball teams had a good year against the United
States. In the Little League World Series, Osaka, Japan, beat
Phenix City, Ala., 5-0, a year after Toms River, N.J., won it. And
with Fidel Castro cheering in Havana, the Cubans lost a taut 3-2
decision to the Orioles in March, but Fidel stayed home while his
state-supported amateurs totally embarrassed the Orioles in
Baltimore with a 12-6 victory in May. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the downscale NFL of second-tier cities and eternal parity,
Denver won its second Super Bowl and John Elway soon retired as
quarterback, and the Broncos have not been heard from since.
</P>
<P>
   Other powerhouses like San Francisco, Green Bay and Dallas also
slumped while upstarts like Jacksonville and Tennessee prospered
and young quarterbacks Kurt Warner and Peyton Manning turned
moribund St. Louis and Indianapolis into contenders for the next
Super Bowl in Atlanta. The league also faced a plague of legal and
emotional problems among its players.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants still had a mathematical chance for the coming
playoffs, after going through four quarterbacks in the three-year
regime of Jim Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets reached the conference title game in the 1998 playoffs,
losing to Denver. This season fell apart in the very first game
when Vinny Testaverde tore his Achilles' tendon while making a
simple cut on the killer carpet. Artificial turf will finally
disappear from Giants Stadium next season, at least one hopeful
sign in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   Pro football's elaborate feeder system kept edging toward a
national playoff. Tennessee won the 1998 college championship with
a victory over Florida State in the Fiesta Bowl. Florida State
rebounded to reach the 1999 championship game with upstart Virginia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Peter Warrick, a wide receiver with Florida State, was caught
accepting an illegal discount at a store, and lost his chance for
the Heisman Trophy, which was won by Ron Dayne of Wisconsin, the
leading ground gainer. Professional scouts will surely overlook
Warrick's transgression.
</P>
<P>
   A lockout killed two months of the 1998-99 season before the N
BA and its players union settled and presented their aerobics for
millionaires. Attendance and enthusiasm were generally down, but
two gents named Tim Duncan and David Robinson collaborated for San
Antonio's first championship, over the dysfunctional but surprising
Knicks. The Nets, still in New Jersey, still in the doldrums,
formed an alliance with a bloke named Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the NBA's ennui may have stemmed from the absence of
Michael Jordan, who lent his prestige to the players during the
lockout, then promptly retired. Charles Barkley's proposed
retirement was pushed up a few months when he tore his knee earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Comets, behind Cynthia Cooper, won the 1999 summer
Women's NBA championship, after the rival American Basketball
League folded on Dec. 22, 1998. Now the WNBA will expand by four
teams next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional feeder system for pro basketball was going
through a transition, and television ratings were down.
Connecticut, in its first Final Four, upset Duke for the men's
national championship, after which Connecticut's top player and
three of Duke's best players promptly turned professional with
eligibility left. Purdue's women beat Duke for their first
championship and nobody left school early.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Belt won its first Stanley Cup as the Dallas Stars
defeated the Buffalo Sabres on a disputed goal by Brett Hull. Wayne
Gretzky retired as hockey's greatest scorer as well as the best
spokesman any sport ever had. The Pittsburgh Penguins nearly went
under financially until Mario Lemieux, their retired superstar,
bought the franchise. In New York, the Rangers staggered with a
huge payroll, the Devils plodded along with a moderate payroll and
the Islanders, saddled with owners who would rather build malls
than sign players, skated off the edge of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer retained a modest fan base and stable
salaries and even produced a dynasty in D.C. United, which won its
third title in four years. A ghastly team in the New York area
severely handicapped the league. Manchester United stunned
Germany's Bayern Munich, 2-1, on two late goals to win the
Champions League and also won two domestic titles. In college
soccer, the Indiana men defeated Santa Clara, 1-0, and the North
Carolina women won their 15th title in 18 years, beating Notre
Dame, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The big news in golf was Tiger Woods' turning 24, having laser
eye surgery, excising his caddie, fine-tuning his swing, helping to
win the Ryder Cup and taking the PGA Championship as well as seven
other tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Maria Olazabal of Spain won the Masters and Payne Stewart,
the American in retro golfing knickers, made a clutch 15-foot putt
on the 18th hole to defeat Phil Mickelson at the U.S. Open at
Pinehurst, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Paul Lawrie of Scotland, playing at rugged Carnoustie
in his homeland, started the final day of the British Open 10
strokes out, but Jean Van de Velde of France stumbled badly and
Lawrie won on the fourth hole of a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Woods beat Sergio Garcia of Spain, age 19, to win the
PGA in Medinah, Ill., as Americans chanted ``Sergio! Sergio!''
</P>
<P>
   Having come to know Stewart for his born-again friendliness as
well as his born-again golf game, fans grieved in late October when
he and three others were killed in a mysterious crash of his leased
plane in South Dakota, far from his planned route.
</P>
<P>
   In women's golf, Karrie Webb, age 24, won six tournaments and
led in earnings and was the LPGA player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Suffering from injuries and general lassitude, Pete Sampras
missed the Australian Open, won by Yevgeny Kafelnikov, and made his
usual early exit from the red clay of the French Open. Andre
Agassi, bouncing ba near oblivion and a divorce from Brooke
Shields, his body buffed from sessions with trainer Gil Reyes, came
back to win the French.
</P>
<P>
   At Wimbledon, Sampras beat Agassi to finally tie Roy Emerson for
the most Grand Slam titles with 12, but the wait goes on. In New
York, Sampras hurt his back in practice, leaving Agassi to win his
second Open, over Todd Martin. For the first time in his career,
Agassi finished a year ranked first in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams sisters became nearly as good as their father,
Richard, had predicted. Venus defeated her younger sister in the
Lipton final in the spring and finished the year ranked third,
while Serena won the U.S. Open and finished fourth. Martina Hingis
won in Australia and would finish first for the year, while Lindsay
Davenport won at Wimbledon and the Chase in November to finish
second.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the French Open and reaching the Wimbledon final,
Steffi Graf realized she no longer had the drive, so she retired,
immediately. By the U.S. Open, Graf and Agassi were, as the saying
goes, keeping company.
</P>
<P>
   No sport seemed more upbeat than the stock car version of racing
known as NASCAR, with its new NBC, Fox and TBS contract for $400
million a year. The sport also has Trumpian visions of expanding to
within screaming earshot of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The top driver in NASCAR was Dale Jarrett, 42, of the Robert
Yates Racing team, while Mika Hakkinen won the Formula One, Juan
Pablo Montoya won the CART championships and Kenny Brack won the
83rd Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the seas beyond Auckland, New Zealand, Paul Cayard's
America One and Dawn Riley's America True advanced to the fleet of
six for the America's Cup semifinals in January, but John
Marshall's Young America suffered hull damage and failed to
advance. Team New Zealand will defend its title in February.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Several traditional sports are staggering on reputations gained
decades ago. In boxing, Lennox Lewis of Britain received poetic
justice for his jobbing in March by taking a very narrow decision
over Evander Holyfield in November for the unified heavyweight
championship. After some unusually outrageous shenanigans, several
officials in New Jersey were under investigation. In December, a
journeyman boxer named Stephan Johnson, suspended in Ontario for
marginal CAT scan results, died after a fight in Atlantic City.
Many women, including a daughter of the damaged Muhammad Ali, began
boxing professionally.
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing is fairly aching for its long-delayed 12th Triple
Crown champion. Charismatic, trained by D. Wayne Lukas, won the
Kentucky Derby and Preakness, but broke down in the Belmont
stretch. A horrified 85,818 fans watched jockey Chris Antley
gallantly control the wounded horse, and surgery saved Charismatic
for a long life on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Drop Kid won the Belmont and the year ended enigmatically
with Cat Thief winning the Breeders' Cup Classic and Artax winning
the Sprint. The sport lost a star when Julie Krone, the greatest
female jockey in history and a past Belmont winner, retired at
midyear. Definitely not retiring was Laffit Pincay Jr., who passed
Bill Shoemaker for most career victories.
</P>
<P>
   Another form of racing, on two bicycle wheels, saw the American
Lance Armstrong rebound from testicular cancer to win the Tour de
France, a race still haunted by the specter of doping.
</P>
<P>
   August's world track and field championships in Seville, Spain,
produced excitement when Michael Johnson set a world record of
43.18 seconds in the 400 meters, and American sprinter Maurice
Greene won three gold medals. The emotional highlight came when
Lyudmila Engquist, a Russian now running for Sweden, won the bronze
medal in the 100-meter hurdles only four months after undergoing a
mastectomy for breast cancer on her 35th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm rooting for her, and I'm running against her,'' said Gail
Devers, 33, the American gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
   Australia, embarrassed by Olympic scandals, did have cause to
celebrate: its men beat Pakistan to win the World Cup in cricket,
beat South Africa and France to win the World Cup of rugby and beat
France for the Davis Cup in tennis, and its women beat New Zealand
for the world netball title, whatever netball is.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Thompson of the United States set a world record in the
100-meter butterfly at the Pan Pacific Championships and was named
female athlete of the year by the U.S. Olympic Committee. (Lance
Armstrong and the women's soccer team were also honored.)
</P>
<P>
   Other retirements included: the graceful Jana Novotna, whose
1998 Wimbledon victory made up for an earlier teary collapse;
Darrell Waltrip, a three-time NASCAR series champion; Don Haskins,
who coached Texas Western to the 1966 NCAA basketball title over
Kentucky, using only African-Americans and striking a huge blow for
equality; football lineman Reggie White; baseball hitter Wade
Boggs; NASCAR driver Ernie Irvan, and Barry Sanders, who made an
end run from the Detroit Lions as the second-leading rusher of all
time.
</P>
<P>
   Among the great sports figures who died in 1999: Joe DiMaggio;
Wilt Chamberlain, the enigmatic basketball scorer; Walter Payton,
football's Sweetness; Payne Stewart; Kim Perrot of the WNBA Houston
Comets; Catfish Hunter, the droll Yankee from North Carolina;
Malcolm Marshall, the compact fast-bowling cricket star from the
West Indies; Marion Motley, the devastating fullback and linebacker
for the old Cleveland Browns; PeeWee Reese, captain for life of the
Brooklyn Dodgers; grand old golfer Gene Sarazen, and the generous,
reticent owner of the Jets, Leon Hess.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of Hess' funeral, the Jets were for sale, at prices
most definitely fin de siecle. Charles Dolan, the proprietor of
Cablevision, and three other competitors seemed likely to drive the
price toward $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the money. The fabled Washington Redskins were sold for
$805 million to one Daniel Snyder, a 30-something with a penchant
for micromanaging. This figure remains, temporarily, the highest in
sports history.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the expansion Cleveland Browns sold for $530 million.
Larry Dolan, a Cleveland lawyer and brother of Charles, bought the
Indians for $320 million, just beyond the $311 million Rupert
Murdoch paid for the Dodgers in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the money come from? From television. CBS Sports is
paying $6 billion to keep the men's college basketball tournament
for 11 more years, despite declining ratings. The $545 million
annual fee ranks behind only the $2.2 billion paid to the NFL and
the $650 million paid to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, NBC will be paying an average of $750 million
for the 2000, 2004 and 2008 Summer and the 2006 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder great players command such staggering salaries that
their teams sometimes seem downright eager to get rid of them.
</P>
<P>
   At century's end, the most ludicrous example was Ken Griffey
Jr., perhaps the best player in baseball, who announced he wanted
to leave Seattle with a year left in his contract, ostensibly to be
closer to Orlando, Fla., where he has chosen to move his family.
His best option might be his hometown of Cincinnati, if only that
modest market could afford him.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey seemed fated to mope back to Seattle for one sour,
leftover season, a melancholy symptom of a money-mad world hurtling
toward a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   What are the prospects for sporting peace in the new age?
</P>
<P>
   Consider this fearsome bit of news: the volatile John McEnroe
has been named the U.S. Davis Cup captain, and will lead the Yanks
into Zimbabwe in February. While there has never been a war started
by a tennis match, at this fin de siecle juncture, anything seems
possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
