<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RETIREE-EDUC-1STLD-WR     12-25 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREE-EDUC-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDEN YEARS BRING NEW EMPHASIS ON LEARNING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.C.)   (DELETES reference to Alzheimer's disease in 9th graf) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT 26 and 28 were sent Dec. 17 to NYT photo
clients, with the slug ELDERLY-EDUC. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first thing you notice is that everyone has
done the reading. Not a single student shies away from the seminar
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   You glimpse a graying lady switching eyeglasses between scanning
the text of ``The Optimist's Daughter,'' by Eudora Welty, and
glancing at the author's photographs of Mississippi. A balding
gentleman turns his left ear, the one with the hearing aid, toward
whoever is talking. A couple of canes are propped in a corner.
</P>
<P>
   This is definitely not your typical college class.
</P>
<P>
   Here at the Plato Society, an educational haven for retirees,
they prefer not even to call it a class. Please, say study group.
Teachers? Call them coordinators. No papers, no tests. Just
learning, for learning's sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very narrow-minded in my education. I came here to
broaden my education,'' explained Bud Hellman, 76, an engineer who
spent the fall studying the films of Stanley Kubrick. ``If I was to
live again, I'd want to be a student someplace, at one of these
beautiful modern campuses. This is my campus.''
</P>
<P>
   With the increased emphasis on standardized testing in
elementary and secondary education, and a push toward job training
even at liberal arts colleges, the purity of the intellectual
exercise at Plato is rare to behold. But it reflects an explosion
in the lifelong learning movement, as the first generation to
pursue higher education in big numbers _ thanks largely to the GI
Bill _ has settled into its Golden Years.
</P>
<P>
   Experts expect study among older citizens to continue to
skyrocket as baby boomers retire and live longer and healthier
lives. The fellowship in places like Plato can be crucial for
people who crave the sense of community they lost when they left
the workplace; research also suggests that vigorous mental
stimulation might help ward off senility.
</P>
<P>
   ``One theory is the `use it or lose it' theory: If you exercise
your brain cells, you're going to keep them,'' said Gary Small, a
geriatric psychiatrist who directs the Center on Aging here at the
University of California at Los Angeles. ``One of the key elements
is remaining engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   A sign of the trend is the surge in groups like Plato, which was
founded at UCLA 19 years ago as the Perpetual Learning and Teaching
Organization (modeled on a program started in 1962 at the New
School for Social Research in New York). In 1989, there were two
dozen such Institutes for Learning in Retirement affiliated with
Elderhostel, a national group best known for its traveling
educational seminars; today, there are 272.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers of participants are hard to come by, since many older
people who audit college classes are never counted, while others
pursue independent research in libraries or participate in ad-hoc
book clubs. But, according to the National Center for Education
Statistics, one in three Americans over 50 _23 million _ were
engaged in some sort of adult education last year, more than double
the 11 million (18 percent) who were involved in 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a new wave of retirement communities being built
in conjunction with universities like Iowa State and Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plato, somewhere, says that knowledge falls away from us and
we have a need to replace it,'' said Ronald Manheimer, who runs the
North Carolina Center for Creative Retirement at the state
university campus in Asheville. ``I don't know exactly what he had
in mind, but it's great insight for that period.''
</P>
<P>
   While the 375-member Plato Society is one among myriad
institutions providing education for retirees, experts say its
rigor is unique. That reflects its highly educated membership _ 56
percent have master's degrees or doctorates, and another 26 percent
graduated from college, according to a recent survey _ and its
high-minded mission: intellectual stimulation. Each member of a
study group leads one week's session; experts, like UCLA
professors, visit only at weekly lectures.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the few rules in Plato's modern suite of rooms above a
take-out chicken restaurant near the UCLA campus is a ban on talk
of health, wealth or grandchildren. Despite members' impressive
roster of accomplishments, they never use honorifics. People
typically avoid their own expertise, instead perusing the course
catalog with whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Heller, an engineer who worked on the Manhattan Project,
runs study groups on Asian art. Ruth Gussen, a pathologist who is
now the society's president, specializes in French opera. Lawyers
take literature; pharmacists do philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   The ``resident medievalist'' is Ed Bressler, 73, an internist
who ``never heard of medieval, or Dark Ages, or anything
historical'' before joining Plato. ``I feel like Howard Carter when
he discovered King Tut _ three times a month,'' Bressler said.
</P>
<P>
   Leila Newman, 79, has a retirement schedule so packed with
tennis and bridge and teaching English to Russian immigrants that
she just signs up for whatever Plato is offering on Thursday
mornings. ``I've never been disappointed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bressler added: ``The process is far more important than the
subject.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that members spend an average of 20 hours
preparing for their own study group presentations, and just under
three hours getting ready for the other sessions. This fall, there
was a group on the queens of England and one on terrorism, a
seminar on the first millennium and another on Islam in America, a
close reading of ``Ulysses'' and an intense look at Einstein. Once
in a while, Plato offers ``come as you are,'' in which members
present the topic of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a bunch of reasonably bright people together on
any topic, they will teach each other,'' Heller said. ``What we
don't know, we teach each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides their intellectual curiosity, Plato members bring a
barrel of experiences to the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   In a session on 1960s protesters for a study group on ``The
American Century,'' a former university professor recalled the
dilemma of whether to give bad grades to draftable young men. Some
of the people discussing Charles Lindbergh were at the ticker tape
parade welcoming him back to New York. As for Kubrick, most of
those around the table saw ``Spartacus'' when it was first
released, in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become so much more sophisticated in our film
watching,'' said Irv Shimer, 70, who loved ``Spartacus'' in the
1960s but hated it upon review three decades later. ``You look at
an old picture and it's an old picture. It doesn't have the stuff
of a new picture, even a bad new picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Wally Graham, though, said he watched both times with the same
sense of wonder. ``I can't honestly remember much about 40 years
ago,'' he allowed. ``I have a hard time with last week.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one young face in the classroom, belonging to Eugene
Pino, a UCLA senior who is one of 246 honors students who have
taken Plato courses since 1986 in an arrangement that allows for
intergenerational relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's contributing, and the contributions are more
mature, it's coming from experience,'' he said. ``At UCLA, a lot of
times you hear, `It's just human nature.' These folks know what
human nature is.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Plato membership costs $395 a year, and after candidates are
approved by an interview panel, they can still get kicked out if
they are not lively participants. Publicity is mostly word of
mouth, though some said they were referred by doctors, a kind of
prescription to combat loneliness and brain atrophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I get older, I'm frightened of narrowing horizons,'' said
Richard Gilson, 74, whose wife pushed him to join. ``My greatest
fear is that I'll go brain dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Between study groups, they have lunch in the lounge. On the
bulletin board, there are pictures of Plato tennis groups and
fliers announcing holiday parties. Some study groups go on retreats
_ a Steinbeck seminar traveled to Pacific Grove _ and people have
found romance in Plato.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came seeking intellectual stimulation,'' said Martin Jaffe,
a onetime systems analyst who wears his graying hair in a ponytail.
``But I also found society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 1831EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8946 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-MUDSLIDES-H     12-25 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-MUDSLIDES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA'S DEVASTATING FLOODS COULD SET BACK CHAVEZ'S
`REVOLUTION' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MACUTO, Venezuela _ On a day that was supposed to mark a new
beginning for Venezuela, this beach town was entombed by what looks
like a whole new layer of Earth's crust.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks of torrential rains triggered flash floods and
landslides Dec. 15 that roared down nearby Mount Avila and crashed
into Macuto and other locales. The floods left behind a congealing
mud stew of tree trunks, boulders, crumpled cars and human remains.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of other communities were washed away in Venezuela's
worst-ever natural disaster. Government officials estimate that
between 5,000 and 30,000 people died.
</P>
<P>
   ``This used to be beautiful. But now, it's totally devastated,''
said Jaime Pacheco, as he walked across a newly formed plain of
brown, hard-packed dirt and debris that was once Macuto's beach.
</P>
<P>
   Besides remaking the topography, the mudslides could alter
Venezuela's political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   President Hugo Chavez has spent his first 10 months in office
railing against the wealthy elite, promising a peaceful revolution
on behalf of the poor and campaigning for a new constitution that
was approved by voters on the same day the mudslides struck.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, some analysts say that Chavez must tone down his
class-based politics, postpone upcoming elections and bring
Venezuelans together to rebuild the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This catastrophe changes the agenda,'' said Anibal Romero, a
political science professor at Simon Bolivar University in Caracas.
``Chavez has to create jobs, attract investment and fix the
infrastructure. And he has to do it fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of the task was evident during a tour last week
along the Caribbean coast of tiny Vargas state, just north of the
capital city of Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   With sections of the main highway blocked by landslides,
bulldozers and backhoes were cutting paths into hillsides of dried
mud. On parts of the new route, trucks cruised above buried
rooftops and power lines. Pedestrians wore face masks to avoid the
dust and the stench of rotting human and animal remains.
</P>
<P>
   At La Guaira, Venezuela's main cargo port, shipping containers
knocked over by the floods still stood on end. Plastic bags,
mangoes, ripped clothes and even twisted car chassis lay scattered
on the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers of mud turned the Caribbean Sea a chocolate brown. In the
background, Mount Avila appeared scarred as if scratched by a cat.
The landslides had cut into its green slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A river came right into my house,'' said Daniluz Aguilera, 19,
who survived by fleeing to the top floor of a clinic in La Guaira.
``This is a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, a former army paratrooper, threw himself into the relief
effort as if it were a war. Outfitted in camouflage fatigues and a
red beret, he flew to the worst areas to assess the damage and
comfort refugees.
</P>
<P>
   At one stop last week he told a group of survivors: ``I feel
from the bottom of my heart, from my soul, the worst pain I have
experienced in all my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Visibly moved by the unfolding tragedy, first lady Marisabel
Chavez invited displaced children into the presidential residence
and set up an aid distribution center on the manicured grounds just
outside the walled compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her face is swollen because she has been crying all the
time,'' said Armando Pelaez, a volunteer at the aid center.
</P>
<P>
   Pelaez pointed out that the first family feels a special bond
with the victims because most are poor and working-class
Venezuelans who make up the bulk of Chavez's political support.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Freddy Hidalgo, a 43-year-old construction
worker, showed up at the aid center to check its database for
missing persons. He held up a photo of his 9-year-old adopted
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of two things,'' he said. ``Either we find her or we
find her body.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials said that many of the dead will never be found
because they were buried in the mud or washed into the sea.
</P>
<P>
   To help the living rebuild, Chavez suggested that the rich adopt
a family for the holidays. Rather than rebuild along the steep
folds of Mount Avila, the estimated 400,000 homeless people will be
offered new housing in seven agricultural areas around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a crowd of flood victims last week, Chavez referred
to one relocation site in western Miranda state, and said: ``Let's
make a town over there. You'll live quite a life, without fearing
floods or falling mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, though, questioned the plan because many of the victims
work in tourism, the fishing industry or at the La Guaira port and
have no experience in farming.
</P>
<P>
   Others blamed the government for putting politics ahead of
public safety.
</P>
<P>
   According to Diego Urbaneja, a former opposition congressman,
the Chavez administration ignored pleas from the governors of
Miranda, Vargas and Falcon states for federal help to evacuate
at-risk families on Dec. 15, the day the mudslides began.
</P>
<P>
   That was also the day Venezuelans voted on a new constitution
that could greatly enhance Chavez's powers. Rather than encouraging
people to seek shelter from unseasonable torrential rains, which
had been falling for two weeks, the government instead encouraged
people to brave the elements by extending the hours at the polling
places from 4 to 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government had been more concerned about the people
than about the elections, perhaps they could have saved more
people,'' said Maruja Tarre, a political analyst in Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new constitution, another round of elections for state
governors, mayors and possibly for the presidency must be called
within 90 days. But Tarre said the vote should be postponed because
the government cannot now afford to spend millions on a nationwide
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Superstitious Venezuelans wonder if the approval of the new
charter and the mudslides were somehow related.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible that on the same day we were supposed to start
a new period in our history, we also had the most terrible natural
catastrophe in our history,'' said Romero, the political scientist.
``Many people think that this is a bad omen.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only bright spot is that the tragedy has, for the
moment, cooled political passions and brought people together.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took office Feb. 2, Chavez has portrayed Venezuela as a
nation divided between rich and poor, between friends of his
government and enemies. While campaigning for the new constitution,
Chavez lambasted business groups, the Roman Catholic Church and
media groups for their opposition to the new magna carta.
</P>
<P>
   Now, these same groups are playing a vital role in the country's
relief effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businessmen in helicopters saved hundreds. Churches opened
their doors to orphans. Those who had been portrayed as devils a
day earlier showed the nation what they are: true heroes,'' wrote
Julio Borges in the Caracas daily El Universal.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Chavez's politics of division could lose some of
its appeal, Romero said. He added that Chavez may instead be forced
to bond with big business and the church as he confronts the
nation's deepening economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a speedy recovery appears unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The Caracas business group Fedecamaras estimates that
reconstruction will cost between $15 billion and $20 billion. About
200,000 jobs were erased, and the Caracas stock market lost 8
percent of its value in the aftermath. Last week, the government
forecast that the economy would contract by a whopping 7.2 percent
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a lesson for Chavez about the need for unity,''
Tarre said. ``Right now we are starting a very long process of
reconstruction. And he has to count on everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
