<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ALBANY-MUSEUM-590&AMP;     12-25 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ALBANY-MUSEUM-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG-EARED MUSEUM PLANS A $69 MILLION OVERHAUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JEFF WAGGONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Years ago, children who visited the New York
State Museum were apt to take a big lick of a 4-foot salt pillar on
display. That most salt licks are enjoyed by livestock and deer did
not limit the illicit interactive appeal to thousands of small
visitors, who over the years wore grooves in the rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we licked it _ I don't know if we were supposed to, but
we did,'' said John McEneny, now 56, a member of the state
Assembly, recalling how he and his childhood friends would while
away long summer days at the museum, with its dioramas of Mohawk
life and other exhibits on the natural and human history of the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The case for public hygiene and a move to a new location ended
what might have been the museum's first and last tongues-on
display, a testimony to the state's once-booming salt industry. The
pillar was banished to one of the institution's own salt mines:
storage.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the museum's collection of 6 million items was also
moved out of view there in the mid-1970s during the move from the
State Education Building to an austere marble-clad building in the
Empire State Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the 163-year-old museum, which says it is the
nation's oldest state museum, has fallen victim to what its
director, Clifford Siegfried, calls benign neglect. He likens it to
a tattered and worn textbook, with fixed displays, many of them two
or three decades old, in a dark, almost mournful, setting.
</P>
<P>
   Annual attendance has dropped by half over the last decade, to
650,000 last year from a high of 1.3 million in 1990. State
financing has not kept up with inflation, resulting in staff cuts,
to 115 today from 167 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to stop the slide, Siegfried and his boss, state
Education Commissioner Richard Mills, last month announced a $69
million overhaul of the museum.
</P>
<P>
   A state budget included $4.5 million to get the renovation under
way, but the museum is far from securing the full amount. Although
both Siegfried and McEneny are optimistic that the project will be
fully financed, the official word from Gov. George Pataki's
administration, said Suzanne Morris, a spokeswoman, is that ``the
governor will take a look at the proposal in terms of the overall
budget.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is also planning its own private fund-raising
efforts, and this month it hired an Ohio firm, Gerald Hilferty &AMP;
Associates, to design the renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Over five to 10 years, the project will create skylights to
brighten the museum. Other changes will make exhibit areas easier
to change and add interactive displays in six large exhibits that
will each trace a theme.
</P>
<P>
   In one exhibit, ``Empire State,'' visitors will take a virtual
trip by boarding a replica canal boat for ``Fifteen Miles on the
Erie Canal,'' a display with projected images that recreate life
along the canal in the 1850s. Another exhibit, ``New York
Ecosystems,'' will feature a stream running from the mezzanine to
the first floor.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit ``Politics of Change'' will include a copy of the
1799 state law that gradually abolished slavery and a draft of the
Emancipation Proclamation, written mostly in Abraham Lincoln's
hand. Also being considered are displays on the 1969 Stonewall
uprising, considered a watershed in civil rights for gays.
</P>
<P>
   The three other large exhibits will be ``Shaping the Land,'' a
study of the ancient natural history of the state, and ``Peopling
the Land'' and ``Growing up in New York,'' two lessons on the
state's diverse population groups and their experiences.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The museum, older than the American Museum of Natural History
and the Smithsonian Institution, is among the 5 percent of the
country's museums that qualify as research museums.
</P>
<P>
   Siegfried also plans to move more of the museum's intellectual
vitality out of its laboratories and academic cloisters and into
its public spaces. That could mean making researchers available to
talk to visitors more often. Gerald Hilferty, of the design firm,
said the museum should provide the most ``literal, visceral
experience'' possible.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the salt pillar is back on display in a retrospective
of the museum's older exhibits. Its grooves are testimony to the
days when New Yorkers were much more intimate with their museum, an
intimacy its supporters hope will soon return.
</P>
</TEXT>
