<SLUG> BC-NJ-COL-AIRPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IN AN UNLIKELY SETTING, A SEASONAL OASIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Holiday travel sounds like something you might do
while wearing a party hat and sipping one of those drinks with an
umbrella stuck in it.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, of course, it is overbooked flights, bomb-sniffing
dogs and unpleasant incidents of ``gate rage'' _ those nose-to-nose
arguments that make passengers and airline agents look like
baseball managers and umpires.
</P>
<P>
   The daily commute is a nuttiness that eventually begins to feel
familiar, even comfortable. But holiday travel is, as the surgeons
say, never routine.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Obando is a veteran. She's a ticket agent at Newark
International Airport. That's why she was in the airport's
meditation room early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first thing I do in the morning before I go to my
position,'' she said. ``For me, it's peace. For me, it's
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lord is compassionate. Passengers are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come with a lot of stress,'' Ms. Obando said. ``They
are in a hurry. They want to go places as soon as possible. We need
to be in a good frame of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The meditation room is the admiral's club for the frequent
faithful. A small, spare room in Terminal C, it is set up for
prayer of all kinds, including an altar for Catholic Mass and a rug
for Islamic prayer (plus a compass for finding east). It caters to
religious travelers stuck in the airport, and to the scared or
grateful.
</P>
<P>
   A flight attendant was there Friday morning, quietly adjusting
her uniform and making the sign of the cross before hurrying to her
gate. Later, an Israeli student came to say morning prayers, and,
eyeing the poinsettias in the room, joked, ``Are we going to have a
minyan?''
</P>
<P>
   Finding relief at an airport during this season of happy
dislocation is rare. First, there are the crowds. And there are so
many rumors of terrorism threats at Newark Airport that it is
difficult to keep them straight. (Was it really a pilot who said he
might have a bomb in his luggage or was it the guy on the Internet
with the bomb in the Holland Tunnel? What is this, open-mike night
for amateur terrorists?)
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, there is the feeling of being stuffed into a
kielbasa skin. Chris Gallagher, 27, had left work at a translating
service in midtown Manhattan at 3 p.m. on Thursday and six hours
later was still waiting with his grandmother at the end of a very
crowded seating area for their flight home to Milwaukee. Even the
big number of his gate told him that Newark Airport had gotten
outsized. ``C-130,'' he said. ``That's a ridiculous number for a
gate!''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, that was the observation of a man who had waited four
hours for a two-hour flight. But just as people invariably
understate the length of their commutes, they tend to embellish the
duration and drama of their airport incarcerations.
</P>
<P>
   An Orange County, N.Y., man said he had woken up at 4:30 a.m. to
get his daughter on an 8:50 a.m. flight. And, he said, because of
delays at the airport, she made the flight only because ``I was
throwing her on the plane as the doors closed.''
</P>
<P>
   The mismatched strains of the season are everywhere at the
airport. A jazz band filled Terminal B with lively music the other
night, while behind the scenes, security agents were scanning
baggage for explosives.
</P>
<P>
   And while a periodic announcement ominously informed travelers
that unattended luggage would be inspected ``and may be
destroyed,'' countless arriving passengers flipped open their cell
phones and happily announced to relatives: ``Hi, can you hear me?
It's me! I'm at the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   It was nice to step out of the flow for a moment, away from the
boarding announcements and the whirring of little suitcase wheels.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Isaac Schochor did. A 31-year-old Israeli studying
at Columbia University, Schochor was bumped from a 7:15 flight to
Miami on Friday morning. He had left New York too early to say
morning prayers and was preparing to pray in the meditation room,
standing between the altar and the prayer rug. The room is a little
like Israel. ``It's small and it has a lot of meaning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning, at Newark Airport? He thought for a moment. ``I
wouldn't say it's more spiritual than JFK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
