<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-HEALTHCARE-PATAKI-     12-25 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTHCARE-PATAKI-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE PLAN HAS GOVERNOR AT ODDS WITH REPUBLICANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ A major new entitlement program, paid for with a
major new tax. Sounds more like Bill Bradley than Trent Lott,
right?
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the political figure embracing the deal is a
Republican, Gov. George Pataki, and while the plan is likely to
sell well in New York, it puts Pataki at odds with most of his
party's leading figures around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The week before last, the governor and the Legislature announced
an agreement to subsidize health insurance for as many as half a
million low- and moderate-income people who do not qualify for
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will be financed with most of the money New York will
receive from the national settlement with tobacco companies, but
even that is not enough to pay for the cost of such an ambitious
new program. So in addition, state lawmakers will raise the
cigarette tax by 55 cents a pack, to $1.11, highest in the nation,
generating an additional $500 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Each half of that equation _ government-subsidized health care
and a big increase, even in a sin tax _ is anathema to many
conservatives, and the combination is enough to make them blanch.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, the presidential candidate, has
been one of the few prominent Republicans to champion an increased
federal tobacco tax, arguing that it was the best way to divert
teen-agers from smoking. But McCain's approach to helping people
pay for health care has been to advocate medical savings accounts
that give them some marginal tax breaks in buying their own
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   On the presidential trail, only the two Democrats _ Bradley, the
former senator from New Jersey, and Vice President Al Gore _ are
talking about a new government effort to aid the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Several calls to George W. Bush's presidential campaign last
week about the New York plan were not returned, but Bush, the
Republican front-runner, has never advocated anything remotely like
it.
</P>
<P>
   New York, of course, is not Texas. This, after all, is the state
that four times elected Gov. Nelson Rockefeller, a national symbol
of liberal Republicanism, and three times voted for Gov. Mario
Cuomo, icon of Democratic liberalism.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is the most conservative governor in most New Yorkers'
lifetimes, but even after years of ascendant smaller-is-better
rhetoric, the state remains a place with an expansive idea of what
government should be.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even in New York, some conservatives found the deal hard
to stomach. The governor's staunchest supporter in the Legislature,
Assemblyman John Faso, the Republican minority leader, said, ``I
have a very strong disagreement with him'' on both the health-care
program and the higher tax.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's record as a tax-cutter is unassailable. Since he took
office five years ago, New York has lowered taxes far more than any
other state. But in some quarters, the aversion to taxation is so
strong that no increase can be brooked, even in the context of much
larger cuts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pataki is especially out of sync with Republicans in Congress,
who have rejected the cigarette-tax increase proposed by McCain in
1998, rejected a similar levy that President Clinton called for
this year and rejected various plans to broaden health coverage for
the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's much less ideology at work and much more innovation at
work when you're in the governor's seat than when you're in
Washington,'' said David Gergen, a former aide to Presidents Reagan
and Clinton, and now a professor of public service at the Kennedy
School of Government at Harvard University. ``Pataki has become one
of the leaders in that crowd of Republican governors who believe in
using government aggressively to tackle big problems.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the nation's Republican governors, what Pataki has
done puts him in the minority. Only a handful of others _ in
Minnesota, Rhode Island and Wisconsin _ have enacted similar major
efforts for the uninsured; and Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey
has proposed one.
</P>
<P>
   And even by the standards of that group, the cigarette tax is
remarkable. Some other Republican governors have raised cigarette
taxes, but most by 10 to 20 cents. None, Democrat or Republican,
has pushed through an increase as large as 55 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
