<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TAYLOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN TAYLOR, AIRCRAFT EXPERT, DIES AT 77 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   John W.R. Taylor, the longtime editor of ``Jane's All the
World's Aircraft,'' the authoritative guide to aviation, died on
Dec. 12 in a hospital in Surbiton, a suburb of London, where he
lived. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was not disclosed, but Taylor was
hospitalized with angina two days before his death, said Paul
Beaver, a spokesman for Jane's in London.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor spent 30 years, from 1959 to 1989, editing ``Jane's All
the World's Aircraft,'' the annual compendium of technical and
engineering data, photographs and historical information about
virtually all the airplanes that exist in the world. The
blue-covered book, part of the venerable Jane's Information Group,
which also publishes ``Jane's Fighting Ships,'' is regarded as the
bible of the industry. It is known for its accuracy and
comprehensiveness and is read by military, aircraft manufacturers
and intelligence agencies around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was particularly respected for his ability to obtain
information about military aircraft. His reputation was such that
during the Falklands War in 1982, Argentina provided him with
details about its airplanes even though it was fighting Britain.
``They felt that he was above politics,'' Beaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor was also adept at gathering data about aircraft from the
Soviet Union, which, like Argentina, rated Jane's highly and
provided relatively accurate information on its planes even during
the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, Taylor had to rely on photographs taken
during parades and air shows to judge the capabilities of aircraft.
His skill at this method was so polished that he occasionally came
up with scoops that surprised the Western intelligence community.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, for example, Taylor did an analysis of the Soviet
MIG-29 fighter. Seven years later, a group from Jane's visited the
Soviet Union and found that his physical measurements of the plane
came within an inch of his earlier projections.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, the Soviet Union introduced the Tupolev Tu22 supersonic
bomber, and many analysts in the West estimated that it could reach
a speed of Mach 2.5. Taylor, by gauging the air intakes, made a
lower estimate _ Mach 1.4, which was later found to be much closer
to the actual speed.
</P>
<P>
   John William Ransom Taylor was born on June 8, 1922. He became a
draftsman and joined Hawker Aircraft in 1941, where he was a
designer on the Hawker Hurricane 2-D fighter that destroyed German
tanks in World War II. He later specialized in fixing design
defects.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, he joined Jane's as an editorial assistant; four years
later he became editor. After he retired in 1989, he was named
editor emeritus. Until the late 1960s, Taylor was almost the entire
editorial staff of the publication. ``It is seldom appreciated how
much is involved in producing an edition of Jane's,'' he wrote
dryly in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor wrote numerous books, among them ``Spitfire'' (with M.F.
Allward, 1946) and ``Passenger Aircraft and Airlines'' (with S.H.H.
Young, 1975).
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Doris; a son, Michael, of Ewell,
Surrey, and a daughter, Susan, of Ampthill, Bedfordshire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
