<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLUMN-COACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON COLLEGE BASKETBALL :  YOUNG COACHES ARE MAKING FAST BREAKS FROM
MENTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They play ``H-A-W-K-E-Y-E'' now instead of ``H-O-R-S-E,'' after
the two-ball dribble and footwork drills. And there are many nights
when 7-year-old Kory and 4-year-old Bryce join their father, Steve
Alford, Iowa's new coach, and their grandfather, Sam, his son's
assistant, in the coaches' office for slumber parties.
</P>
<P>
   The men break down game film; the boys watch videos. Old coach.
Young coach. Budding players.
</P>
<P>
   In the Alfords' case, it is in the blood. But on more than a few
benches during this college basketball season, 30-something coaches
who have inherited old traditions will try to elbow their
``basketball fathers'' out of the polls.
</P>
<P>
   From the Mike Krzyzewski family tree, Quin Snyder, 33, has taken
over at Missouri and Tommy Amaker, 34, in his third season at Seton
Hall, is attempting to move the Pirates to the top tier of the Big
East.
</P>
<P>
   From the Rick Pitino school, 34-year-old Billy Donovan has built
Florida into a top 10 program.
</P>
<P>
   And from the most royal basketball line of all, Matt Doherty,
37, leads Notre Dame after assisting Roy Williams at Kansas and
playing for Dean Smith at North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge will be finding the players with the same
passion for the game I have and making it even deeper,'' Steve
Alford, 35, said earlier this season of the task he and his young
peers face. ``And I think I have developed my own way of doing
that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The energy these young coaches bring to college basketball is
already evident in recruiting. Donovan has had two straight
star-studded freshman classes and has made Gator fans think beyond
football; Florida is 9-1 and ranked No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Amaker has already been declared the winner of next year's
recruiting wars by virtue of his early signings for Seton Hall
(whose 7-2 record includes victories over Quinnipiac and Stony
Brook). And Snyder is expected to turn Missouri into a home of
McDonald's all-Americans in the same way he did as an assistant at
Duke. So far, he is 7-3, and his last two victories came against
Alford's Iowa team and No. 15 Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   But Alford _ whose Hawkeyes are 5-4, with a season-opening upset
of Connecticut, the defending national champion, alongside losses
to No. 1 Stanford and No. 17 Maryland _ is the most compelling
figure in this new generation of coaches. That is partly because he
has the most impressive basketball resume and partly because he is
estranged from his mentor, Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Alford was Indiana high school's Mr. Basketball in 1983; he won
a gold medal as a member of the U.S. Olympic team in 1984 and, as
an all-American guard, led Knight's Indiana Hoosiers to a national
championship in 1987. He also played four seasons in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   And he is the most seasoned coach among the newcomers. Alford,
in his ninth season as a head coach, compiled a 157-78 record at
Division III Manchester College and Division I Southwest Missouri
State, which he led to a 22-11 record and a berth in the round of
16 of the national tournament last year.
</P>
<P>
   While Krzyzewski, Pitino and Williams speak glowingly of their
coaching proteges, Knight does not speak about _ or to _ Alford.
The two have not shared anything more than a civil hello since
Alford left Indiana, and Knight has not returned calls or letters
from his former captain since Alford became a rival Big Ten coach.
</P>
<P>
   Alford is diplomatic about the strain in their relationship but
indicates that it probably has much to do with having had to share
the spotlight in a basketball-crazy state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed my career at Indiana and I learned a lot from one of
the game's greatest coaches,'' Alford said. ``I'd like to have a
better relationship. But that's up to him. But I do have a
relationship with basketball in Indiana that goes back to high
school. I worked hard to become a better player. I won some games
for us. I contributed to our national championship. That is where I
learned the game first from my dad, then from coach Knight.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did at Southwest Missouri State, Steve Alford took Sam,
who was his high school coach, with him to the Iowa bench. Kory and
Bryce attend Iowa practices, just as the young Steve did when Sam
was coaching at New Castle Chrysler High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be with my kids,'' Steve Alford said. ``I want them
to understand what I do and how much I love it.'' Alford also has a
2-year-old daughter, Kayla.
</P>
<P>
   But Alford also acknowledges the habits he formed under Knight,
for everything from pregame meals to how he conducts a walk-through
practice. ``But I use my own personality,'' Alford said.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that he smiles rather than glowers on the sideline,
and discusses rather than discourses at practice. But he shares his
former college coach's iron will.
</P>
<P>
   Before Iowa's season-opening upset of Connecticut, the defending
national champion and preseason No. 1, at the Ikon Classic at
Madison Square Garden, Alford took Rob Griffin, a junior-college
transfer, out of the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not just about the basketball floor,'' he said. ``We
are about academics and community. Rob tested me by missing a
couple classes and I had to pass that test along.''
</P>
<P>
   Alford also sounded like his old coach when he railed against an
experimental rule implemented for the tournament: the choice to
shoot free throws or take the ball out of bounds in the final
seconds of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a media guy, but when television starts asking to take out
part of the game that James Naismith put in a long time ago, it's
silly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Knight wants to acknowledge it or Alford wants to
embrace it, the Indiana way has taken root alongside the Carolina,
Duke and Kentucky ways in the crop of new coaches. College players
and the game's fans may meet some new bosses this season, but they
are likely to discover that they are the same as the old ones. Just
a little younger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
