<HEADER>
A8960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-YACHT-JAPAN-NYT &LR;      12-25 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YACHT-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE OFFER LIMITED EXPERIENCE AND UNLIMITED DESIRE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When their fair-haired Australian captain barks the commands in
his native tongue, many of them don't understand a word. They are
racing in sailing's most visible and prestigious event against a
field of multifaceted sailors who have tasted success aboard
everything from dinghies to maxi-boats, yet several of them have
never trimmed a sail on anything other than an International
America's Cup Class yacht.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, before they signed on to be crew members aboard the two
Japanese boats representing the Nippon Challenge, most of them were
content in their landlocked jobs as truck drivers and, as they say
back home, salarymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``True, many of them have very, very little overall sailing
experience,'' Nippon's skipper, Peter Gilmour, said last week in a
telephone interview from Auckland, New Zealand. ``But the Japanese
people are fast learners.''
</P>
<P>
   They must be, for when the semifinal round of the Louis Vuitton
challengers trials begins next Sunday, the Nippon team will be one
of the six remaining squads squaring off to earn the right to face
Team New Zealand in next February's Cup finals. And many see Japan
as a serious threat to sideline its far more experienced
counterparts, including the Prada Challenge of Italy and America
One of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   How far Japan goes will depend largely on the vast skills of the
39-year-old Gilmour, who faces daily challenges _ like basic
communication _ beyond those of most cup skippers. ``I've lived in
Japan for a few years now so I have a casual understanding of the
language,'' he said. ``And I know all the sailing terms. So when
we're racing I speak English, they speak Japanese, and we all seem
to understand each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour acknowledged that his task had been eased by Japan's two
prior America's Cup appearances in 1992 and 1995, when it advanced
to the semifinals both times before being eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The groundwork was done in previous campaigns,'' he said.
``We've added another 10 or 12 individuals to the group, but there
were already some good sailors on the team, even though they'd come
to it rather late in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour was the coach of the '95 team, which was fronted by the
mercurial New Zealander Chris Dickson. Married and the father of
three, Gilmour appears to bring a more stable presence to the
proceedings. As he pointed out, he and his wife, Christine, have
lived in Japan with their children for several years to meet cup
eligibility requirements, an experience he says he has relished.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour's home life may be settled, but on the race course he is
a fierce competitor. A leading skipper on the international
match-racing scene for several years, he burst onto the cup scene
in 1987 as a helmsman aboard Australia's defender Kookaburra, where
his reputation for aggression on the starting line began to
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   If Gilmour has a perceived weakness, it is his tendency to begin
events slowly, a pattern that repeated itself in the early rounds
of this campaign. The Japanese scratched out six victories in each
of the first two rounds before taking off in Round 3. Nippon's
eight victories in that round included a solid triumph over Prada,
one of only three losses for the Italians thus far.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gilmour said it was all part of a greater plan.
``I wouldn't draw too much from the round robins,'' he said. ``We
use them as a method of entry into the main part of the regatta,
which is the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention was always to use the slower of our two boats
early on, to see where we stood in the field. That was a conscious
decision we made in the beginning, because you tend to learn more
when you're racing from behind than you do when you're out front.
When things got going later on, we switched boats and had some
reasonable improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's first boat, Asura, was named after a Buddhist deity. The
second boat is called Idaten after a god of war renowned for its
brilliant speed. But will it be fast enough to propel Japan to a
Pacific Rim matchup with New Zealand in a cup final that would have
been unthinkable not very long ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be interesting to see,'' Gilmour said. ``I do know
that the Japanese are very, very committed to winning the America's
Cup. At the same time, they realize the depth of effort that's
required. I get a sense that they're into it for the long haul, and
they won't give up until they're successful. They're patient,
hard-working people, and they'll just stick away at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmour paused for a moment of contemplation. ``I just don't
know if it will play out that they're successful on my watch or
not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
