<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8961 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-WILSON-COLM-AZR &LR;      12-25 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-COLM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE MIRACLE FOR CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a story of faith, hope, high-tech medical care, coping
with the unexpected, both kinds of luck and a one-week vacation
that turned into a four-month ordeal. Mostly, though, it's about
love.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, Jim and Steph anie Sadler of Phoenix flew to
New York to watch the U.S. Open Tennis Tournament. They were joined
by her parents, Richard and Doris Gurtler of Mesa, who were
celebrat ing their 40th wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie was 23 weeks pregnant with their first child.
Conceiving hadn't been easy. The couple spent three years and many
thousands of dollars on fertility treatments. They felt blessed by
the news that their first child was due on Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   But that would soon change.
</P>
<P>
   Four days into the trip, she felt some cramping. The next day
her water broke, and she was admitted to Manhattan's Lenox Hill
Hospital, which has a state-of-the-art neonatal unit.
</P>
<P>
   For babies born at 24 weeks, the chance of death or serious
disabili ties is high, making every extra day in the womb critical.
Doctors did all they could to hold off contractions and delay
birth.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks in intensive care, Stephanie showed signs of
infection, and doctors decided to deliver the baby by Caesarean
section. Al though the survival rate is better at 26 weeks, the
risks remain large.
</P>
<P>
   In the operating room, Jim waited anxiously, eager for some sign
of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   He got it. Unlike most babies born that prematurely, who have
minimal lung function and go im mediately on respirators, this
little guy came out kicking and crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a fighter,'' Dr. Michael Giuliano announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that moment, I felt a burst of joy impossible to
describe,'' Jim said.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on their faith and mind ful of the story of the angel
sent by God to the Virgin Mary, they named him Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a lot of prayers into the pregnancy and the birth and
felt something miraculous had happened in our lives, too,'' Jim
said.
</P>
<P>
   Their struggle wasn't over, how ever. Like all preemies of that
age, Gabriel needed intensive care and was unable to travel. He
spent the next three months in Lenox Hill Hospital connected to
countless wires, monitors and IVs. He under went five brain scans,
seven spinal taps and seven blood transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bionic baby,'' they dubbed him.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie didn't leave New York, and Jim spent most of his time
there, too, setting up a temporary office in a room at the Marriott
Hotel, which learned of their situa tion and gave them a generous
discount.
</P>
<P>
   Jim, 35, and Stephanie, 34, met when they were students at
Arizona State University. A vice president with Comfort Systems USA
in Tempe, Jim said the baby's arrival motivated him to rebalance
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked 70 to 80 hours a week and traveled 100,000 miles a
year for the past 10 years. This experience has made me clearly
aware that my family matters most.''
</P>
<P>
   Their goal was to bring a healthy baby home by Christmas. As re
cently as two weeks ago, the chances didn't look good since Gabriel
came down with a viral infection. But it quickly cleared up, and
doctors said they could leave the next week, though not by plane
because of the changes in air pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, they began a 55-hour Amtrak trip from New York to
Flagstaff. Stephanie's parents drove them the rest of the way home
Wednesday morning. Gabriel trav eled well with the assist of a
portable oxygen tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had done everything right during the pregnancy,
but when something like this happens, you realize you're not always
in control,'' Stephanie said. ``When I look into his face, I am so
grateful for what God has given us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sadlers spent a quiet Christ mas at home with family. Since
they hadn't much time for shopping and are facing some steep
medical bills, they didn't buy many presents this year, which seems
about right.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest gift they've ever hoped for _ all 5 pounds, 4
ounces of him now _ came early.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 2005EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
