<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8963 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN     12-25 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST, WORST OF NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We've barely passed the one-third mark of the
season, but in a league that allows 24 seconds to take a shot, it's
plenty of time to make snap judgments. Face it, most people
(analysts) determined some things (like Lamar Odom being rookie of
the year) in the first week.
</P>
<P>
   So let's figure out where some other players stand with a mere
50 games to change our opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Most valuable player: Shaquille O'Neal, Lakers. He started the
season getting criticized for poor free-throw shooting and losing
his temper. But today, he's in the top four in scoring, rebounding
and blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq would also be in the top three in minutes but for the two
games he was thrown out of.
</P>
<P>
   Most overrated player: Mitch Richmond, Washington. It's hard to
rip someone who has done so many good things for so long,
especially when you count Juwan Howard and Rod Strickland as
teammates. But after signing a huge new contract, a lot of people
in Washington's organization believe he has become much more
concerned about his own stats than helping the Wizards improve.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the Year: It's hard to go against Odom. Who else can
dish out seven assists and block seven shots like Odom did
Wednesday against Golden State?
</P>
<P>
   But he's in a dead-heat today with Houston's Steve Francis, who
is averaging 17 points and six assists while playing the game's
toughestposition, point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Worst Rookie of the Year: Frederic Weis, New York. While the
Knicks wanted frontcourt help, Weis wanted to play for his French
team, Limoges.
</P>
<P>
   Coach of the Year: Danny Ainge, Phoenix. If you don't think
dealing with Penny Hardaway can ruin careers, just ask Ainge and
Chuck Daly.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge was getting tired of a lot of things with the Suns and
wanted to return to a normal existence. The weekend after he quit,
he attended his son's high school basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   That beats dealing with Hardaway any day.
</P>
<P>
   Worst contract of the decade: Cleveland Cavaliers. It's hard to
believe, but this is final year of the 10-year deal the Cavs
foolishly gave to Danny Ferry. Besides a solid decade of mediocre
play, the contract has also ruined Cleveland's salary-cap
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Chalupas chit-chat: Seattle guard Brent Barry and Minnesota
coach Flip Saunders had a little get-together before the teams
played this week about comments Saunders made when the teams met on
Dec. 8 in Key Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Barry hit a late 3-pointer that gave the Sonics enough points
(110) for fans to enjoy free Taco Bell chalupas. Saunders took
offense afterward to the alleged running up of the score, telling
reporters that Barry's shot was
</P>
<P>
   The personal attack angered Brent, who had apologized to the
Timberwolves after the game. Barry anticipated a similar apology
from Saunders.
</P>
<P>
   But Saunders denied making the comments despite confirmation
from two Minnesota writers to whom Saunders made the statement.
Barry said he was disappointed that Saunders did not apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Double talk: When asked before Wednesday night's game against
the Knicks why he had chosen to re-sign with Toronto this season,
Raptors forward Charles Oakley had a simple answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because no one else could guarantee me a championship,'' said
Oakley, who talked with the Lakers and the Knicks as a free-agent
in the summer. ``It wasn't about money.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   Knockout trip: Last weekend, the Utah Jazz played Indiana with
boxing legend Muhammad Ali sitting at center court of Conseco
Fieldhouse in Indianapolis. The team then spent a few days at the
swanky Coconut Grove, Fla., hotel with Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   The pudgy looking former heavyweight champ took time to pose for
pictures and spent several minutes talking to Jazz star Karl
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   No punch: Sacramento's backcourt of Jason Williams and Nick
Anderson was recently outscored 111-12 in back-to-back games. Worse
for Anderson, he went scoreless in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has gone scoreless in four games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Another opinion: Atlanta center Dikembe Mutombo was one of the
few athletes in Atlanta who didn't read the controversial Sports
Illustrated article in which Braves pitcher John Rocker virtually
destroyed his relationship with other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I hear, I don't like it. I always say, I may forgive
you, but I will not forget,'' Mutombo said.
</P>
<P>
   Mutombo said it was ironic that he is paid by the same owner
(Ted Turner) as Rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``A strange world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonehead play of the week: The Bulls' Kornel David, who is
Hungarian, showed that he has some things to learn in the NBA, or
maybe just about plain, simple basketball.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bulls trailing Philadelphia by three points, David
received an inbounds pass from Ron Artest with 7.1 seconds
remaining and shot an off-balance 25-foot air ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very poor decision at the end of the game, in terms
of our shot selection and awareness of time on the clock,'' Bulls
coach Tim Floyd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was obvious. Even a dead man could see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Here come the Knicks: Patrick Ewing may be a pompous pain for
coach Jeff Van Gundy at times, but the Knicks are 6-1 since he
returned from injury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
