<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SKOREA-TENSION-1STLD-     12-25 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-TENSION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREANS SEE DARK SCENARIO IN A U.S. PRECAUTION _ GAS MASKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS name spellings in 5th, 7th   and 24th grafs) 
 (DW) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Ever since war divided the Korean peninsula
in 1953, residents of this bustling capital city, 30 miles from the
demilitarized zone, have lived with the threat that Communist
troops from North Korea could storm the border at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite doomsday scenarios that North Korea would attack this
city of 10 million people with every imaginable weapon, including
chemical and biological agents, few residents have taken such dire
predictions seriously, and for seemingly good reason.
</P>
<P>
   About half a million South Korean soldiers are guarding the
border, backed up by 37,000 American servicemen and some of the
most sophisticated military technology available. Recently, North
Korea has seemed more interested in diplomacy than making war.
</P>
<P>
   But a decision by the U.S. military in November to distribute
14,000 protective gas masks to dependents of American soldiers and
embassy staff members living in Seoul has raised concerns here that
despite its new diplomatic tone, North Korea is planning a major
assault that will include chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard that the United States was issuing gas
masks to its citizens in Seoul, I was deeply troubled because our
government has no plans to do the same,'' said Lee Shin Bom,
chairman of the foreign affairs committee of the opposition Grand
National Party. ``I asked myself what does the United States know
that our government isn't telling us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States says that the decision is not tied to
any increased threat or impending attack by North Korea, rumors
have spread across Seoul that an assault is imminent and is likely
to occur sometime near the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am afraid,'' said Kim Yong Shik, a taxi driver who was
waiting for a fare near the U.S. military base at Yongsan. ``None
of us have gas masks like the Americans. We are like sitting
ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korean and U.S. military intelligence officials said in
recent interviews that North Korea had large stocks of chemical
weapons and missiles and artillery shells to carry those weapons to
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Should chemical warfare be used against an unprotected civilian
population in Seoul, enormous casualties would result, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of North Korea's chemical warfare capability vary
widely. A South Korean defense ministry report issued in October
estimated that North Korea's chemical and biological arsenal was
2,500 to 5,000 tons, including nerve gas, blistering agents and
anthrax. The ministry's latest figures were a fivefold increase
over last year's, which the ministry said were grossly
underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence officials said that equipping the public with
protective masks could reduce the number of civilian casualties and
injuries to about one-tenth.
</P>
<P>
   But very few residents of Seoul own gas masks, and neither the
state nor local governments have plans to distribute them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are recommending that individual citizens purchase their
own gas masks to guard against an attack of chemical and biological
warfare from North Korea,'' said Chun Jung Soo, head of the gas
mask distribution team at Seoul City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't started any massive campaigns yet because this
would obviously lead to a panic among Seoul citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Chun said that although residents could buy gas masks from a
booth at City Hall or at retail outlets for about $25, sales were
low because most Koreans ``don't believe that a war will actually
break out.''
</P>
<P>
   Seoul city government plans to distribute about 1.7 million gas
masks over the next 10 years to civilian defense squad leaders,
volunteers who supervise neighborhood evacuations in the event of
an attack or other emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The city government said that it had distributed about 300,000
masks to defense squad leaders and that recent surveys indicated
that about 200,000 Seoul residents had bought gas masks on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Chun said the city government hoped that the U.S. military's gas
mask program would increase awareness among South Koreans of the
importance of masks.
</P>
<P>
   Col. David R. Apt, public affairs officer for the U.S. Forces
Korea, said that distributing gas masks to dependents of military
personnel was part of the Pentagon's effort to improve protection
of noncombatants stationed overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the ability to provide your dependents with this
protection, you'd be negligent not to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. military is issuing M-17A2 masks and hood systems,
which are used by many active duty forces around the world to
protect against chemical warfare. It is the first time that such
protection is being provided for noncombatants in South Korea,
which is a test case for other U.S. military installations.
</P>
<P>
   Apt emphasized that the plan was not related to any specific
event and had been in the works for more than a year. He said that
the United States had deliberately delayed distribution of the
masks until November, when relations between North Korea and the
rest of the world seemed to be improving.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, North Korea has engaged in talks with officials
from the United States, Japan and Europe in what appears to be an
effort to improve its foreign relations, after decades of isolation
and hostility.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo Suk Ryul, a defense expert for the Korea Institute for
Foreign Affairs and National Security, said that North Korea's vast
arsenal of chemical weapons posed a great threat that should not be
underestimated.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo said that since foreign governments had already persuaded
North Korea to abandon its nuclear and long-range missile programs
in exchange for concessions, chemical weapons were now likely to
become the major issue in dealing with the Stalinist country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North has plenty of weapons, and if they decided to use
them, many South Korean people would be sacrificed,'' Yoo said.
``The bottom line is that everyone needs to be prepared to use a
gas mask.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 2022EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8967 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-FATAL-FIRE-KAN &LR;      12-25 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-FATAL-FIRE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY TOWN HOME FIRE KILLS MOTHER, CHILD; INJURES HER OTHER
TWO CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH and JOHN A. DVORAK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Tragedy marred a sunny Christmas morning when
a fire in an east Kansas City town home killed a mother and child
and critically injured two other children.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Russell, 27, and her 1-year-old son, Gavin Russell, died
in the blaze, Fire Department spokesman Brad Humston said.
</P>
<P>
   Injured were two other children of Russell's, 3-year-old Gabriel
Benson and Garrett Russell, 6 or 7.
</P>
<P>
   The two injured children suffered severe burns and smoke
inhalation. They were listed as critical Saturday night at
Children's Mercy Hospital, Humston said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors, firefighters and emergency medical personnel wept at
the scene, and neighbors held a short, impromptu prayer service
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Kellee Wallace, a neighbor, cried as she received a comforting
hug from her 11-year-old daughter, Cadela Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly sad,'' Wallace said. ``This is Christmas Day. I
don't feel like celebrating any more. It doesn't feel like
Christmas any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire was in a two-story, three-bedroom town home at 2013
Park Tower Drive in the Blue Valley Court development. Humston said
that the mother and the dead child were in one bedroom and that the
two injured children were in a second bedroom. Both bedrooms were
on the second floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us have kids of our own,'' Humston said. ``It's at
times like this that we see how vulnerable they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Humston said that the fire was under investigation late Saturday
and that officials did not expect to release information about the
cause until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was reported at 9:43 a.m. Firefighters arrived within
two minutes and the injured children were removed from the burning
building in less than five minutes, Humston said. The fire was
under control in about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said she feared the worst when firefighters pulled off
the front door of the town home and smoke and flames shot out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying desperately to get in there,'' she said.
``They did a wonderful job.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Harris, a next-door neighbor, said she and her two sons
ran from their home when the fire set off her smoke detector. Once
outside, she heard someone inside the burning apartment banging on
a bedroom window.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very, very scared,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said she had taken her trash out at 1:30 a.m. Saturday
and had seen Russell and the three children playing with Christmas
gifts inside their town home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe it could happen that fast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Stemmons, who lives nearby, said she was preparing for a
typical Christmas Day when she looked outside and saw the blaze
ravaging the front of the victim's unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole doorway was just engulfed in flames,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stemmons summoned help, just as the Fire Department began
receiving calls about the blaze. Soon she learned there might be
two fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts me,'' said Stemmons, her voice shaking slightly. ``I
have a daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Rogers, a Kansas City animal-control officer who lives
nearby, said he saw smoke pouring from the burning building as he
was driving home about 9:45 a.m. Rogers said he then looked through
a window of the town home and saw a burning Christmas tree in the
front room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went round back and broke out a back patio window,'' Rogers
said. ``Smoke shot out and I couldn't see anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he reported the fire on his dispatch radio and tried
to get in the front door, but was unable because the door was too
hot.
</P>
<P>
   James Simmons, who manages the town homes for a property
management company, said Angela Russell was a hairdresser.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very nice lady,'' Simmons said. ``She worked hard to
make a better life for herself and her children.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Tim Richardson, fighting back tears, said the blaze was
an especially tragic blow to a neighborhood that had been combating
crime and drug problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is such a thing, maybe the one good thing that will
come of this is it will bring the neighborhood closer together,''
Richardson said. ``We want to make sure everybody understands
they're not isolated.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances of the fire victims were so distraught that aid
workers could not immediately talk with them, said Bill Miles, a
volunteer with the American Red Cross, Kansas City chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very depressed; they were crying; they've been holding
hands; you could hardly get anything out of them,'' said Miles, who
arrived not long after firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Miles was able to speak with some of the area residents
and offer them assistance in finding emergency living quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel just as bad as they do,'' said Miles, of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the family of Angela Russell, three other families in
adjacent living units were forced out of their homes. Humston said
15 persons were affected.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross, which sent five volunteers to the scene, will
make sure families have a place to go.
</P>
<P>
   Humston said Russell's town home had an estimated $60,000 worth
of structural damage and $20,000 in damage to contents. A
neighboring town home had an estimated $10,000 in structural damage
and $3,000 worth of damage to contents. Another neighboring unit
had an estimated $3,000 worth of smoke damage to contents.
</P>
<P>
   Humston told neighbors at the scene that they should formulate
an evacuation plan in case of fire. A firefighter distributed
literature on the subject, and a battalion chief demonstrated
evacuation techniques to residents of the complex.
</P>
<P>
   Similar information may be obtained from the Internet by logging
onto www.kcmo.org/fire and then clicking on ``Safety Information''
and ``Exit Drills In The Home.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Troy Nash visited the scene and offered moral
support to residents and firefighters. He said he wanted to work
with the Fire Department to make sure that every home in Kansas
City had smoke detectors and that residents became familiar with
fire evacuation strategies.
</P>
<P>
   While the fire turned Christmas into a tragic occasion, neighbor
Wallace said such a calamity ``makes you thankful for everything
you've got. Never take anything for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said she was going to begin working with her children on
a fire evacuation plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to happen to my family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
