<HEADER>
A8970 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CRACKED-AZR &LR;      12-25 1633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRACKED-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX AREA HOMES VULNERABLE TO CRACKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BETTY BEARD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - As the Phoenix area building boom restlessly stretches
toward the fringes, it is moving onto poorer soils and leaving
thousands of newer homes vulnerable to excessive cracks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some homes have already come apart and had to be partially
rebuilt or abandoned because builders didn't realize how
destructive these soils can be.
</P>
<P>
   These fine-grained clays get gummy and greatly expand when wet,
exert ing enough pressure to pick up a car or move a house
foundation an inch or two, cracking the walls and floors.
</P>
<P>
   Cracks have become more common, especially where flat expanses
of farmland have been plowed into neighborhoods. Many became no
ticeable after the heavy rains of early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And although local standards, codes and inspections are supposed
to reduce damage from these soils, the fact that even new homes in
the Phoenix area are cracking shows the system isn't working.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been approving just about anything that comes across
their desk with a stamp on it,'' said Carl Josephson, a Scottsdale
structural engineer. ``It's all a shared responsi bility to be
honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Expansive soils are so spotty that Michael Goldwater, director
of the Registrar of Contractors, believes a soils test should be
done for every house lot.
</P>
<P>
   He said most builders now take precautions when building on
these soils. But he also acknowledged, ``lots of contractors try to
cut corners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They may do soils tests but only five holes for 600 houses. .
. . We get quite a few that don't go the extra yard,'' Goldwater
said.
</P>
<P>
   There's such a bad crack in the foundation of Gail Mitchell's
north east Gilbert home that her kitchen floor is split open as if
someone slashed the heart of her home with a dagger.
</P>
<P>
   Just across the street, an inch-wide gash has scarred the front
of another home. Over the past two years, cracks have turned up in
every house in the cul-de-sac.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worrying us to death,'' Mitchell said. ``How would I ever
resell this house?''
</P>
<P>
   There doesn't appear to be current maps showing where the
expansive clay soils are because engineers turn up new problems all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   But some areas they have mentioned include Fountain Hills,
Gilbert, Chandler, southeast Mesa, Tucson, Flagstaff, Avondale,
Goodyear, Tolle son, Maryvale and some other parts of west Phoenix,
Scottsdale, Tempe and the Navajo Indian Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're becoming more of a prob lem because all the good sites
that didn't have expansive soil are al ready built on,'' said
Prescott geo technical engineer Glen Copeland. ``We're now getting
to areas where clay soils predominate. That's a fairly recent
occurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   The same thing is happening nation ally. The American Society of
Civil Engineers estimates that half of the homes in the country are
built on expansive soils and half of those will have some damage.
The group claims these soils are responsible for more home damage
every year than floods, tornadoes and hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Not every crack in a house is a sign of expansive soils. It's
normal for houses to settle, and hairline cracks are common,
especially in homes with cathedral ceilings.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers who have examined homes in the Phoenix area say that
80 to 90 percent of cracks are cosmetic, whether caused by
expansive soils, old garbage pits, improperly com pacted fill,
green lumber, badly taped drywall or something else.
</P>
<P>
   The rest are structural, meaning major repairs may be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   What makes expansive soils espe cially ominous is their
unpredict ability. They swell and shrink repeatedly through wet and
dry seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Only six months after Lety Haynes moved into her northwest
Gilbert home on Halloween 1996, the front door wouldn't open.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, cracks began appearing and then gaps. Walls began
separating from each other and from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's too embarrassed to let anyone see her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no inclination to decorate,'' Haynes said. ``All I can
think of is when can I get out. . . . It's so depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Josephson, the structural engineer, said parts of Haynes'
foundation need to be sawed out, replaced and reinforced. He
doesn't know the cost yet.
</P>
<P>
   She is one of 28 Gilbert homeowners who have sued their
builders, Trend Homes and Shea Homes (formerly UDC Homes), over
excessive cracks. Both companies have denied negli gence and say
they're willing to fix problems. The suits are pending.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Joyce Kapsal, who filed both suits, said the problems
seem to occur with a variety of builders.
</P>
<P>
   She said filing lawsuits is often the only way to get builders
to respond because their insurance carriers balk at paying money.
</P>
<P>
   As the lawsuits show, there is a lot of finger pointing, with
builders, sub contractors, inspectors and home owners blaming each
other.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best solutions to living with expansive soils appears
to be widely ignored: keeping them dry. It's imperative that any
structure built on expansive soils be designed to keep water away
from the house.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Gibbons, president of Con struction Inspection and Testing,
said many builders don't know about the soils. And if they do, they
fail to pass on recommendations to buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an education problem that everyone needs to be
aware of,'' Gibbons said.
</P>
<P>
   The company does the bulk of the residential soils testing in
the Phoe nix and has been named in both lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons said most cities and lenders require soils tests before
subdivisions can be built.
</P>
<P>
   Before Haynes' 25-acre subdivision in Gilbert was built, CIT
took six borings and found expansive soil. It recommended that
foundations be reinforced, lots be graded to drain away, and
recommended against ov ercompacting the existing soils, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be essential to prevent moisture from infiltrating
beneath the footings and slabs,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   But after the house was built and cracks developed, an
independent study done by Copeland, of Prescott, hinted at
negligence by both builders and owners. He found that the floor
slabs were built three months after the pads were built, which
could cause them to dry out too much unless they were wet down. He
also determined that some of the perime ter footings were too
light.
</P>
<P>
   Also, drainage holes that are sup posed to drain water from the
side yards were either clogged or the ground wasn't graded right to
let them drain. These openings are normally put at the bottom of
block fences.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons also said city inspectors share in the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``City engineers don't make sure homeowners don't alter their
drain age. City inspectors don't come out to make sure that
happens. That's a weak spot in the industry. We try to make sure
builders are educated so homeowners know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert inspectors check the average new home under construction
seven or eight times before a buyer moves in.
</P>
<P>
   But Ray Patten, Gilbert's director of building and code
enforcement, con ceded that homes are often inspected before lots
are landscaped, which can result in poor drainage away from homes.
</P>
<P>
   Patten didn't even know about the 28 cracked homes in Gilbert.
He said he was aware of only two homes in the city with bad cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Josephson said that there are better foundations that can
alleviate a lot of problems with expansive soils but that cities
don't seem to know about them.
</P>
<P>
   But homeowners also have to make sure that landscapers and pool
com panies don't alter drainage.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy Satterfield, president of Shea Homes Arizona, said: ``We
have found no matter how much we talk about it that unfortunately,
people alter their grades and drainage, either with mounds or pools
and end up with water around their founda tions. It's a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about it during the escrow period and the walkthrough.
It's in a home-buyer video and warranty manual.''
</P>
<P>
   One solution that's been known since the late 1960s _
post-tension foun dations _ have just become more widespread in the
Phoenix area over the past three years for homes. Del Webb Corp.,
Shea and Trend are among the builders offering them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely gained momentum, really, in the last year,''
said Jim Rogers, Arizona division manager of Suncoast Post-Tension,
a Houston-based company that builds these slabs throughout the
country. He said builders started taking notice after Del Webb
began building them at Anthem and Sun City Grand.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of reinforcing concrete with rebar, builders put cables
in the concrete. As it sets, workers stretch the cables to help
hold the concrete together. These foundations have been used in
Texas for about 30 years, are widespread among newer homes in
Tucson and are now spreading to Denver and Phoenix, said Rogers and
Gerard McGuire, executive director of the Post Ten sioning
Institute in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Porter, president of Trend Homes said, ``I think the whole
building industry is moving toward that.''
</P>
<P>
   But those steps don't help homeown ers who have already seen
their dream homes tainted by cracks.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Berk, a Scottsdale attorney, once handled a case for a
California couple who spent $200,000 for a house in Gilbert's Val
Vista Lakes development, which is known for lush landscaping around
homes.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 house began moving and cracking so much that cabinets
be gan separating. Soil experts later confirmed that the builder
didn't follow recommended procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The owners never were able to move in, and the suit was
dismissed earlier this year because of a separate procedural issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just fell apart in front of their eyes,'' Berk said. ``It
sits vacant to this day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
