<SLUG> BC-NEWLAWS-CALIFORNIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE'S 2000 SLATE OF REGULATIONS KEYS ON TRANSPORTATION SAFETY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Terri Hardy  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- If any proof is needed of the impending
millennium, Californians only need to look at a host of new traffic
laws that will take effect in the Golden State on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling signal of a new century is a ban on that
old-fashioned tradition of drivers using their hands and arms
instead of blinkers to alert others before making a turn.
</P>
<P>
   More changes on the horizon: bicycle signals on some traffic
lights, seat belts on farm vehicles, and street-legal electric
scooters that look like skateboards with handle bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time to clean up some laws. And, it was time to look at
alternative ways to get from one place to another,'' said Sen.
Betty Karnette, D-Long Beach, who chairs the Senate Transportation
Committee. ``When you go to a dinner party and people spend an hour
talking about transportation, you know it's a high priority.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1999 legislative session, state lawmakers enacted
more than 1,000 bills, most of them becoming effective on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, more than 175 were changes to the Vehicle Code. A
spokeswoman for the Automobile Club of Southern California said
legislation this year reflects motorists' concern about increasing
congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people's commutes get longer and longer, there is more
discussion about how to tackle the problem,'' said Auto Club
spokeswoman Marie Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Among the several new bills which legalize and regulate the use
of electric scooters, the Legislature declared that ``it is of
paramount import to find ways to reduce the state's severe traffic
congestions and air pollution problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers agreed to promote the use of low-emission or
no-emission vehicles, such as the scooter, said Traci Perry, chief
of staff for Sen. Wes Chesbro, D-Santa Rosa, the author of SB 441.
</P>
<P>
   Described as a skateboard with handlebars, the scooters are
capable of reaching speeds of up to 15 mph. Used extensively in
Pacific Rim countries and Europe, the scooters are perfect for
residents of small cities or college commuters, Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make it easier for folks to get out of their cars
and into an alternative form of transportation that's fun and
cheap,'' Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   New statutes require the scooters' riders to wear helmets and be
at least 16, but they do not need to have a driver's license or buy
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Jan. 1, drivers of electric cars can cruise in the
state's car-pool lanes at any time with no minimum number of
passengers required. Qualifying cars must show a special decal,
which will be distributed through the Department of Motor Vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Cities will now be able to make way for bicyclists under new law
AB 134. Designed after a pilot program in the college town of
Davis, the law authorized the installation of special traffic
signals at intersections in areas with large concentrations of
cyclists.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to move bicycles more safely through the
intersection, the law provides for their own red, yellow and green
signal. The pilot program in Davis successfully reduced the number
of bicycle-related crashes, according to a legislative analysis of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Safety was the impetus for much of the new traffic legislation,
including the law prohibiting signaling turns by hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young drivers don't even know what those signals mean
anymore,'' Karnette said.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers of vehicles without turn signals or with turn signals
that don't work may still use their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature, after years of debate, pushed through a bill
this year that will require seat belts on school buses manufactured
after Jan. 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   And it went further, mandating seat belts on farm vehicles by
May 1, 2000. It was an idea few had seriously considered until 13
agriculture workers died in a crash near Fresno, said Assemblyman
Dean Florez, D-Bakersfield, the author of AB 1165.
</P>
<P>
   With the push for safer roadways, stiffer penalties will face
some drivers in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers under 21 can have their licenses immediately suspended
if they are stopped and found to have a blood alcohol level of 0.01
percent, a change from the current 0.05 level.
</P>
<P>
   Other amendments clarify that passengers in a vehicle are also
prohibited from drinking or possessing open containers of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The new laws also establish a base fine of $100 for a driver's
first railroad grade-crossing offense. The penalty increases to
$200 and $250 for the second and third offenses.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RULES OF THE ROAD
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other changes in California laws affecting roads,
traffic and vehicles that will go into effect on Jan. 1. Each is
identified by the Senate or Assembly bill containing the new
provision and the lawmaker who sponsored it:
</P>
<P>
   AB 1121 (Assemblyman George Nakano, D-Torrance) -- Reduces the
vehicle license fee by an additional 10 percent, for a total
reduction since 1998 of 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SB 171 (Sen. Martha M. Escutia, D-Montebello) -- Sets up a pilot
low-cost auto insurance program in Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   SB 1296 (Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles) -- Prohibits an
automobile insurance or homeowner insurance company from refusing
to renew a policy solely because of a pending claim.
</P>
<P>
   SB 681 (Sen. Jackie Speier, D-Daly City) -- Allows a motorist
involved in an auto crash resulting only in damage to property to
move the vehicle to a safe location off the main lanes of the
highway.
</P>
<P>
   SB 63 (Sen. Hilda L. Solis, D-El Monte) -- Reduces the minimum
occupancy requirements for vehicles using the diamond lanes on the
San Bernardino Freeway from three people to two.
</P>
<P>
   SCR 17 (Sen. Adam Schiff, D-Pasadena) -- Designates the
interchange of the Golden State and Ventura freeways as the ``Gene
Autry Memorial Interchange.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LAWS OF THE LAND
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other new laws that will take effect Jan. 1,
including the number of the Senate or Assembly bill that embodied
the change and the legislator who sponsored it:
</P>
<P>
   AB 60 (Assemblyman Wally Knox, D-Los Angeles) --Restores daily
overtime pay after eight hours on the job.
</P>
<P>
   SB 15 (Sen. Richard Polanco, D-Los Angeles) -- Outlaws the
manufacture, sale and transfer of handguns that fail to met
rigorous safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   AB 26 (Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San Francisco) -- Creates
a statewide domestic partnership registration for homosexual
couples and heterosexual couples over age 62.
</P>
<P>
   AB 55 (Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San Francisco) -- Requires
health plans to let patients seek an independent medical review
when services are denied or delayed.
</P>
<P>
   AB 531 (Assemblywoman Nell Soto, D-Ontario) -- Requires service
stations to offer free air and water to customers
</P>
<P>
   AB 1355 (Assemblywoman Sally Havice, D-Artesia) -- Creates a new
environmental conservancy for the watersheds of the lower Los
Angeles and San Gabriel rivers.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
