<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-S.C.-SPRAWL-REAL-915(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA CONFRONTS PROBLEM OF URBAN SPRAWL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Pa., Ga., Fla., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By LYN RIDDLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Just outside this city of 60,000 lie huge
stretches of subdivisions where a few years ago cattle grazed or
loblolly pines grew wild, reflecting a pattern of sprawl around
midsized cities that has led state leaders to call for more control
on development and greater attempts to preserve open space.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hodges, the governor of South Carolina, has agreed to take
part in a conference scheduled here for March 26 to 28 on how
sprawl affects the state. The organizers hope to bring together a
disparate group, some of whom are usually on opposing sides _ such
as home builders and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   It is a discussion that many call long overdue, but one that is
touchy in a state that has swept forcefully out of economic
doldrums with some $28 billion in industrial construction since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we have to do is identify sprawl as a
problem,'' said Kit Smith, a Richland County councilwoman who has
pushed for land-use planning in her county, which includes
Columbia, the state capital. ``There is such a dichotomy in this
state of rural and growth areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressures of development vs. preservation are being felt
elsewhere in the country as well. A study released earlier this
month by the federal Department of Agriculture showed that 16
million acres of the nation's farmland, forests and open space had
been developed from 1992 to 1997. And six of the 10 states that
gobbled up most of the open space were in the South.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina ranked ninth with 539,700 acres, more than double
the annual conversion rate of the previous 10 years. Texas was No.
1; Pennsylvania, No. 2; Georgia, No. 3, Florida, No. 4, and
California, No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are one of the most wasteful states in the nation in terms
of land,'' said Dana Beach, director of the nonprofit South
Carolina Coastal Conservation League, based in Charleston, which
researches and promotes coastal preservation.
</P>
<P>
   But, said John Cone, director of the Homebuilders Association of
South Carolina, ``the fact is we still have huge, huge, huge
amounts of open space in the state.'' For example, he said, the
Agriculture Department found that the amount of farmland had
remained the same over the five-year period its report covered.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 13 percent of this state, generally considered to be
rural and agricultural, has been developed, the agriculture
agency's study showed. But that pales in comparison with highly
developed industrial states such as New Jersey, with 41 percent of
the land mass developed, or Massachusetts, with 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The state's primary growth areas surround its biggest cities _
Charleston near the coast, Columbia in the central section and
Greenville in the northwest, near the Blue Ridge Mountains. Myrtle
Beach, a vacation resort area along the state's northern Atlantic
coast, has seen tremendous growth as well, primarily in hotels and
second-home resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent growth spot has been York County, just south
of fast-growing Charlotte, N.C. But York County, planners say, has
jumped ahead of other areas in recognizing they are losing their
cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Its County Council created York County Forever, a commission
designed to protect one acre of land for every acre developed. The
goal is 10,000 acres in five years. The county set aside $357,000
for this year, the commission's first, to buy land and to pay for
conservation easements in key areas _ riverfronts, farmland and
open space.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Ferguson, the chairman of the commission, said the group
soon will have executed deals on 3,500 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for our county to retain its character,'' Mrs.
Ferguson said. ``Southerners have a real affinity for the land.''
</P>
<P>
   In Greenville, 1,018 subdivisions with 28,543 homes have been
approved for construction in the last nine years, according to the
Greenville County Planning Commission. The growth pattern here
mimics the pattern that changed the nation's urban centers decades
earlier, with the first subdivisions ringing the central city and
then, as the houses aged and more people moved in, developers moved
farther out.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60,000 people moved into this county in the last decade,
pushing the population to about 380,000, while the population of
the city of Greenville remained virtually the same, planning
commission records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Numberwise, we are the fastest growing county in South
Carolina,'' said David Montgomery, the economic demographics
planner for the planning commission.
</P>
<P>
   F. James Forbes, director of the Greenville County Planning
Commission, said the county was trying to steer developers toward
urban centers, rather than outlying areas, without much success so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Home builders, especially national companies, have gravitated
toward the southern part of the county, which has no zoning. The
only approval needed there is by the planning commission, which
must make sure the infrastructure can handle development.
</P>
<P>
   Only about half of Greenville County is zoned, while some
high-growth counties such as Cherokee, along Interstate 85, the
busy link between Charlotte and Atlanta, have no zoning at all.
But, said Cone of the home builders' group, as public officials
develop regulations they must remember that the market is what
drives the developers' business.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have decided they want to have a little piece of land
with grass and trees and a couple of cars,'' he said. ``That's the
way the South is.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sprawl has brought South Carolina's governments big-city
problems, Ms. Smith said, such as traffic, water pollution and
budgets spread thin to provide police, school, sewer and water
service to outlying areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raise taxes every year in Richland County,'' she said.
``When you build way out, it's the most expensive place to deliver
services. There is always a social cost, an environmental cost and
a financial cost to development.''
</P>
<P>
   Her county has begun to require developers to consider not only
what they are going to put on their own land, but how development
relates to the community as a whole. Often, she said, subdivisions
are built beside a newly built and academically successful school
without direct and easy access to it.
</P>
<P>
   She would like to see communities where residents can walk to
school and stores, even to their work. In addition, she said,
agencies must coordinate planning of land use, road building,
school construction and sewer and water line extensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still this myth that large lots protect the rural
landscape,'' she said. ``They don't. They churn it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Ms. Smith said, small changes add up. Old-fashioned
grid designs for roads, rather than the disconnected subdivision
thoroughfares, she said, give drivers more choices and thus cut
down traffic on individual roads.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she had talked with Inez Tenenbaum, the state's
superintendent of education, about rewriting regulations that now
require 25 acres for each school and prohibit two-story buildings.
Such regulations bar putting schools on a smaller piece of property
when necessary, said Ms. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more sprawl has taken place because there hasn't been
redevelopment of urban areas,'' said Dan Glickman, the federal
secretary of agriculture, shortly after his agency's study was
issued. People are moving farther and farther out because they are
looking for green spaces, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's primarily a local and state issue,'' he said. But, he
added, he wants to reorient the nation's farm policy away from a
commodity-driven approach and toward conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he considered his agency's report a ``wake-up call,'' he
noted that 70 percent of the nation's land was in private hands.
The value of open space and farmland, he added, is ``not for some
anachronistic purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about how you want to grow,'' said Ms. Smith. ``What
will attract industry is good neighborhoods and good quality of
life. We still have a chance to do it right in South Carolina.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
