<SLUG> BC-OBIT-ROTHSTEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORMAN ROTHSTEIN, 63, BROADWAY PRODUCER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Fla., Ga., Texas)  (lb) 
 By MERVYN ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Norman E. Rothstein, a producer and general manager
for more than 40 years on and off-Broadway and in the national and
international theater, died on Thursday at his home in Manhattan.
He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pancreatic cancer, said his wife, Julie Hughes, a
New York casting director.
</P>
<P>
   Rothstein was involved in one major capacity or another in more
than 300 plays and musicals, from the original Broadway productions
of ``My Fair Lady,'' ``The Sound of Music'' and ``Who's Afraid of
Virginia Woolf?'' to the Pulitzer Prize-winning off-Broadway dramas
``The Effect of Gamma Rays on Man in the Moon Marigolds'' and ``No
Place to Be Somebody.'' The list also includes the Broadway and
touring revivals of ``The Little Foxes,'' with Elizabeth Taylor;
``The King and I,'' with Yul Brynner; and ``Peter Pan,'' with Sandy
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   A governor of the League of American Theaters and Producers, the
Broadway trade group, Rothstein was a principal negotiator for the
league on contracts with the theatrical craft unions. He was also a
consultant to Walt Disney Co. for the renovation of the New
Amsterdam Theater on West 42nd Street, an important element in the
revival of Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Rothstein, a native of Brooklyn, fell in love with the
performing arts at an early age. He was a theater major at the
University of Massachusetts. While in the Army, he worked on stage
productions for servicemen. After military service, he started out
in theater in Milwaukee before returning to New York in the late
1950s as a stage manager for ``My Fair Lady,'' ``The Sound of
Music'' and ``Virginia Woolf.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothstein's first marriage ended in divorce. In addition to his
wife, he is survived by a son, Jeffrey, of New York; a daughter,
Elisa Rothstein of Los Angeles, and a granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s Rothstein was managing director of the
Mineola Playhouse on Long Island. Among the many Broadway, national
or international productions for which he was general manager,
executive producer or both were ``Black and Blue,'' ``Torch Song
Trilogy,'' ``On Your Toes,'' ``The Tap Dance Kid,'' ``The Pirates
of Penzance,'' ``Grease,'' ``Pippin,'' ``Tango Argentino,'' ``Tango
Pasion,'' ``Flamenco Puro,'' ``Hello, Dolly!'' and ``Andre Heller's
Wonderhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   He was general manager for more than 90 off-Broadway productions
and tours, among them ``Marigolds,'' ``No Place to Be Somebody''
and ``Your Own Thing,'' as well as for Broadway appearances and
international tours for concerts and dance companies. Among them
were the Beijing Opera, the Netherlands Dance Theater, the Dutch
National Ballet, the Dance Theater of Harlem and the Martha Graham
Dance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Rothstein was also a consultant to 42nd Street Redevelopment
Corp. on the renovation and reuse of historic Times Square
theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Theater construction or renovation projects outside New York in
which he played a role include the Miami Beach Theater of the
Performing Arts, the Fox Theater in Atlanta and the Tower Theater
in Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 2131EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8984 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-90s-ESSAY-2NDTAKE-     12-25 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-90s-ESSAY-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES OF THE 20TH CENTURY PLAY ON AS 1999 WINDS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KANSAS CITY, Mo.: human history.  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Outbreak of information
</P>
<P>
   That democracy, the personal computer and the Internet
simultaneously spread around the world strikes historian James
Gleik as no coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The global sharing of information and aspirations made
tyranny, if not instantly obsolete, at least that much less
plausible,'' Gleik writes in ``Our Times: The Illustrated History
of 20th Century America.''
</P>
<P>
   High-tech industries, sprouting like daisies, served as new
world testaments to what economist Paul Krugman called ``the
romance of capitalism: The idea of the heroic entrepreneur who
builds a better mousetrap, and in so doing becomes deservedly
wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Versions of the Internet date back to the late 1960s. Its use
prior to the 1990s was mostly limited to Defense Department
bureaucrats and college professors. Then, in 1993, the worldwide
computer grid became a ``superhighway'' as the U.S. National
Science Foundation replaced its technological backbone with a
system called T3 _ 30 times faster than the old system.
</P>
<P>
   Again, our achievements carried consequences. Cyberspace
attracted some of America's most twisted villains of the '90s:
Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh and Columbine High School
killers Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, to name three.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing a means for spreading pornography,
racism and bomb recipes, the personal computer changed the way
regular people viewed their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be more likely to think of ourselves as machines _ as
supercomputers _ than ever before,'' Gleik writes. ``(We now say:)
`Let me process that. Time to reprogram my thinking. I've got
sensory overload.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even President Clinton spoke cybertalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was downloading what I remembered,'' he told a grand jury in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The question put to him: What was Clinton's intent when, amid
allegations that he had an affair with a former White House intern,
he told his secretary, ``I was never alone with her, right?''
</P>
<P>
   The president was downloading.
</P>
<P>
   In time, raw details of his relationship with Monica Lewinsky
could be accessed via the Internet. With the click of a mouse, we
could see every word of independent prosecutor Kenneth Starr's
report _ including, sadly, the word ``cigar.'' Something about this
aspect of the information age made us wince.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's detractors pushed for his impeachment on charges of
obstructing justice and lying under oath. After months of denials,
the president confessed to the affair and pleaded for government to
move on to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal swelled into a 14-month exercise in information
overload. Its outcome would not redirect history's course (a Senate
majority refused to remove Clinton from office, as expected.) But
the episode revealed things about ourselves at century's end, for
many of us simply shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   Despite relentless media coverage, despite the pundits who said
impeachment proceedings would ``tear the country apart'' and
present ``a constitutional crisis,'' despite even Starr's report on
the Internet, opinion polls showed Americans holding their ground
through the whole sordid saga.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market continued to soar _ higher, in fact, than we
had ever known. Computer whizzes fresh out of college were striking
it rich in the Silicon Valley. Nationwide, the number of female
executive vice presidents had more than doubled in just a decade.
Black income was rising, too, and nine of every 10
African-Americans surveyed in early 1999 said they were happy _ way
up from 56 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Lewinsky? Yes, we're upset, a majority kept telling
pollsters. Now let's drop it.
</P>
<P>
   In the final year of the 1990s, both the Constitution and the
American majority prevailed. Quality of society
</P>
<P>
   More about the American majority: 63 percent polled by the Pew
Research Center said they thought life was better in 1999 than a
half-century earlier. Eight in 10 said things improved
substantially for women, African-Americans and disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   And, curiously, 56 percent said teen-aged life had gotten worse.
</P>
<P>
   School violence was the crime of the decade. According to Pew,
twice as many Americans paid close attention to the Columbine
massacre than to the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   What worries boomer culture most, perhaps, are things it cannot
control. A public that, in this decade, came to rely upon Prozac,
Ritalin and Viagra to conquer the most vexing of human maladies
found itself clueless as to how to keep fame-seeking teens from
sneaking weapons to school.
</P>
<P>
   We're doing fine, says the bulk of boomers. It's the next
generation that troubles us.
</P>
<P>
   People have been saying that throughout the century. But today,
their fears rattle against a backdrop of global change. Experts
point to the absence of a Cold War rival and suggest that Americans
are now looking for enemies within our own institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In the information age we fear for our privacy. In our dreams of
curing cancer and slowing the age process through gene therapy, we
fear genetic engineering. In the nation's efforts to scale back
federal welfare, we fear a society of have-nots teetering without
safety nets.
</P>
<P>
   In a multicultural workplace of men and women, we fear saying or
doing the wrong thing _ an uneasiness heightened by
sexual-harassment allegations against Supreme Court nominee
Clarence Thomas, in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Compare ``Seinfeld,'' the sitcom of the '90s, to ``Father Knows
Best,'' and nothing looks familiar. Yesterday's gone.
</P>
<P>
   Good, David McCullough said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pulitzer Prize-winning author of Truman would rather be
living in 1999 than in any other period of the century, he said in
a recent interview. Having seen the Depression, a world war, the
advent of TV, the civil rights movement, medical wonders, the
Internet and ``a long list of great movies,'' McCullough, 66, can't
wait to see what happens next.
</P>
<P>
   As for the next generation to assume power, consider: Today's
young adults and teens volunteer more time than their parents do,
watch less TV and are more likely to have close friends of
different races, studies show.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``millennials'' rival baby boomers in number. Born
between 1976 and 1994, theirs is a demographic that includes
Jedediah Purdy. At 23, he wrote this year's best-selling ``For
Common Things: Irony, Trust and Commitment in America Today,'' an
essay on sincerity and ecological stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   Those old enough to vote tend to be absent. But give them time.
Some experts characterize today's college crowd as
``balanced-budget populists'' who eschew two-party dogma for fair,
practical solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like conservatives, they favor fiscal restraint. Like
liberals, they want to help the little guy,'' says Ted Halstead,
president of the New America Foundation in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's young adults will be remembered either as a
late-blooming generation that ultimately helped revive American
democracy by coalescing around a bold new political program...or as
another silent generation that stood by.''
</P>
<P>
   The 21st century will tell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
