<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA ANITA SEASON SET TO BEGIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ For Cat Thief and the rest of the
thoroughbreds listed in Santa Anita's opening day program, Y2K is
already here.
</P>
<P>
   When Cat Thief, the 1999 Breeders' Cup Classic winner, lines up
outside six others for the Malibu Stakes this afternoon, he'll be
just another soon-to-turn-4-year-old getting ready for the 2000 San
Fernando Stakes (Jan. 15), Strub Stakes (Feb. 5) and Santa Anita
Handicap (March 4).
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves Cat Thief and jockey Pat Day vulnerable to
opponents who have more to gain by winning the $200,000 Malibu, who
might have trained harder for the Grade I race, or who are better
suited to 7 furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the concern,'' trainer D. Wayne Lukas said of turning
back from 1 miles, the length of the Nov. 6 Classic at Gulfstream
Park in Florida, to seven-eighths. ``He's got a lot of raw ability,
but we're coming out of a lot of two-turn races.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas hopes Cat Thief's freshness and ``tactical'' speed will
keep him in range of the confirmed sprinters early in the Malibu,
and his class will kick in late. The Overbrook Farm colt is the
first reigning Breeders' Cup Classic winner to run in the
traditional Santa Anita opener; Ferdinand won the nation's richest
race nearly a year after his victory in the 1996 Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   But Cat Thief, a 5-2 morning-line favorite, could get a battle
from any of his opponents: sprinters Five Star Day, winner of the
Vernon O. Underwood Stakes at the recent Hollywood Park meet, and
Love That Red, the California Cup Sprint champion; Desert Hero,
training sharply for his first start since running fourth to Cat
Thief in the Swaps; Bob Baffert-trained Prime Timber and Straight
Man; and Painter, debuting for trainer Ron McAnally after winning
all six starts in Argentina from 5 furlongs to 1 mile.
</P>
<P>
   Cat Thief _ or the horse who upsets him in the Malibu _ will be
only the first star of the 87-day Santa Anita meet that will
stretch to April 24.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge, the 1999 Santa Anita Derby winner, is among
those pointing for the San Fernando and Strub, both for horses
turning 4 years old on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Older horses with a chance to run in the $1 million Santa Anita
Handicap include Budroyale, second to Cat Thief in the Classic,
Malek, Puerto Madero and River Keen.
</P>
<P>
   The road to the $1 million Santa Anita Derby on April 8 _ and
the Kentucky Derby at Churchill Downs on May 6 _ developed an
unanticipated bump for the leading contender when Breeders' Cup
Juvenile winner Anees was reported Friday to have a tender hind
foot.
</P>
<P>
   The injury, apparently a bruise, could cost Anees ``a couple of
days or a couple of weeks'' of training, Thoroughbred Corp. racing
manager Richard Mulhall said. ``The plan was to run him in the
Santa Catalina (Jan.30). That may be out the window.''
</P>
<P>
   Other stakes-winning 2-year-olds 3-year-olds of 2000
</P>
<P>
   who are at Santa Anita include Baffert's Captain Steve and
Forest Camp, and Lukas' High Yield and fillies Surfside and Cash
Run.
</P>
<P>
   Today's nine-race card starts at noon. Day, Lukas and Overbrook
Farm have the heaviest morning-line favorite in 3-year-old Cape
Canaveral, 8-5 for an optional claiming sprint based on the promise
he showed in winning the San Miguel last January before being
sidelined with a shin injury.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita will be open every day but Tuesday in its first
week. Baffert and jockey David Flores will try to defend their
1998-99 Santa Anita championships. Laffit Pincay, who broke Bill
Shoemaker's record for career victories on his way to capturing the
Hollywood Park riding title will add to his 8,844 wins even as he
celebrates his 53rd birthday on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Off-the-track attractions in Santa Anita's second year under
Frank Stronach's ownership include the opening of a gourmet
restaurant and a day in Pincay's honor.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant, named Front Runner, overlooks the homestretch
and features a 215-foot bar. It will be open 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. on
racing days.
</P>
<P>
   The track will hold Laffit Pincay Day on Jan. 15, giving away
posters and souvenir magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The lone change in the wagering menu, effective with a state law
change Jan. 1, finds the superfecta offered on as many as four
races a day instead of one. Superfecta bettors must pick the first
four finishers in order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
