<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8986 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-90s-ESSAY-2TAKES-K     12-25 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-90s-ESSAY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALES OF THE 20TH CENTURY PLAY ON AS 1999 WINDS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Over and over, the rock song played. The
balloons fell. The baby boomers danced, looking groovy but stiff.
``You'll see things in a different way,'' went the lyrics of
Fleetwood Mac's ``Don't Stop,'' a 1970s hit that now heralded a new
generation taking over.
</P>
<P>
   `` Don't stop thinking about tomorrow...
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday's gone, yesterday's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   It was July 16, 1992. The partyers cutting up the stage at the
Democratic National Convention included nominee Bill Clinton _ soon
to be the first U.S. president born after World War II _ and his
law-practicing spouse, the consummate working mom.
</P>
<P>
   To this generation belonged the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The boomers never stopped thinking about tomorrow. In fact, some
would argue they've done more thinking, consulting, logging on and
focus-grouping than, well, taking action. But on that night, for
all the Democrats' pop theatrics, their closing anthem got it
right.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday was gone, for better or for worse.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the Soviet Union, losers of a Cold War mostly waged by
the American generation that won World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was Johnny Carson, 30-year king of talk TV. He had just
turned his show over to a boomer, Jay Leno, who immediately ordered
up a new theme song and redid the set.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks earlier, Martin Luther King's dream of racial harmony
appeared to be fading fast. A very different King, Rodney, uttered
a memorable phrase as he trembled in the face of a Los Angeles
riot: ``Can we all get along?''
</P>
<P>
   And President Bush, a Pacific war hero, was just months away
from handing the Oval Office keys to Clinton, who openly opposed
the war that shaped his own generation.
</P>
<P>
   As that summer of 1992 played out, America's unquestioned
dominance in world affairs showed not on the battlefield but, in
surreal fashion, on the basketball court. The U.S. Olympic ``Dream
Team'' of professional superstars outscored their rivals by an
average 44 points.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Boris Stankovic of the International Basketball
Federation spoke of more than hoops when he said: ``We, of course,
know the U.S. will win everything for the time being.''
</P>
<P>
   So, just as high hopes, general prosperity and technical
triumphs marked the start of America's century, they now seem to
mark the end _ despite societal problems old and new.
</P>
<P>
   A Kansas City Star poll showed more than 60 percent of area
residents optimistic as their country nears the 21st century. Only
12 percent said they were pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   The last century has taught us, however, that success in some
areas can mean tragic costs in others. Consider Dream Team player
Magic Johnson, himself a baby boomer. Johnson's celebrity lifestyle
led to his admission in 1991 that he had contracted the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   The boomers have larger houses, more cars, more phones and far
more information than their parents had, but how well are they
managing life?
</P>
<P>
   Four of every 10 persons polled by The Star cited the ``decline
of families'' as the biggest moral problem facing America in 1999.
Another 22 percent pointed to ``a lack of spiritual values;'' 15
percent singled out ``putting too much emphasis on money and
possessions.''
</P>
<P>
   And, despite the 1990s clarion call for ``community,'' more than
40 percent of area respondents said they were not close friends
with any of their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's gone, and that's making many Americans nervous.
Visions of the generations
</P>
<P>
   President Bush, 65 when the decade began, was awkward at
courting boomer culture. He shrugged off the ``vision thing,'' wore
glasses instead of contacts, had a bubbly, white-haired wife who
wrote a book about...their dog.
</P>
<P>
   His most memorable slip of the 1992 campaign occurred at a
grocers convention in Florida. At a mock checkout counter, the
president handed over a quart of milk, a light bulb and a bag of
candy, then he marveled as an electronic scanner priced each item.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is for checking out?'' Bush asked in awe. In fact,
grocers had used scanners since the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Challenger Clinton wore his hair feathered back, a patented
boomer. Campus activist. Vietnam-era draft resister. Policy wonk.
Poll-savvy. ``Feel your pain.'' If Bush knew nothing about
electronic scanners, Clinton's running mate, Al Gore, struck some
voters as an electronic scanner in the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush's generation _ what newscaster Tom Brokaw called ``The
Greatest Generation'' at century's end _ sending men to the moon
was as much a military conquest as a technological feat. Beating
the Soviets, of course, meant putting lives on the line, turning
Air Force pilots into astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton's generation, space exploration became an enterprise
of ideas, tempered by horrific footage of the shuttle Challenger
exploding. The official mantra at NASA in the '90s was ``faster,
better, cheaper,'' hardly a call to arms.
</P>
<P>
   By 1997 one small step for man had been replaced by the
remote-controlled roll of a wheel, as a robotic box named Sojourner
wobbled across the surface of Mars. Scientists hailed victory, only
to be rebuffed two years later when the Mars Polar Lander failed to
phone home.
</P>
<P>
   Warfare itself became a seemingly bloodless, push-button affair
for the world's sole remaining superpower. Not a single American
soldier died in the final U.S. military stand of the 1900s _ NATO's
campaign against Serbian forces and ethnic cleansing of Kosovo. In
what resembled a fantastic video game, our smart bombs took out
Serbs by the thousands, as they did to Iraqis in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   From Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri, the modern warrior
could race out Friday at noon in a stealth bomber, attack Belgrade
and be home within 30 hours, enabling him to watch a daughter's
soccer game Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The syndrome of the quick, painless war has become very acute
in the '90s,'' said Donald Abenheim of the Hoover Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Realistic or not, it's a notion without precedent in human
history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
