<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DEER HUNTING ON DAY 1, DAWN IS LAST ON THE SCENE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   PETE BODO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EQUINUNK, Pa. _ It seemed that dawn finally decided to take a
day off, but that's how a hunter always feels in the early-morning
hours of opening day of deer season. I sat in the sturdy tree stand
built on the edge of the north field on Steve Renehan's mountaintop
property high above the Delaware River, watching the darkness. And
I knew that some time soon, in 2 minutes or 4 or 8 or 10, I would
begin to discern shapes.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it seems impossible that those shapes represent
concrete objects, much less the corporeal reality of living things
as beautiful as whitetail deer. The shapes are much more like the
patches and blotches children playfully make themselves see by
squeezing their eyes shut. But inevitably, the inchoate forms
multiply, and a landscape emerges from the dark. And with any luck,
deer are part of the tableau.
</P>
<P>
   I strained my eyes, trying to identify the stone wall where I
sat late one afternoon years ago, in the midst of a raging snow
squall, laughing out loud at how amazing it was, just being there.
And off to my right, the slender trunks of the poplars became
individuated in the grayness. It was just there that I shot my best
buck ever.
</P>
<P>
   I have a long history in the north field, going back to the time
when a different, mutual friend, Chris von Strasser, still owned
it. In fact, I was proud to give the place its former name,
Kellam's Heights Club.
</P>
<P>
   Now the north field, along with the rest of the remote 400-acre
parcel, belonged to Steve. He works hard at making the wild land a
richer, friendlier place for a deer herd. He spends a lot of time
clearing brush, planting crops and building tree stands. And on
this opening day, we hoped to kill a few deer off his land. Some
people can't understand why we would want to do that, but that's
all right. It is only the hunter who must know what he is doing,
and why.
</P>
<P>
   Developing light is almost musical in its profundity, and it has
startling power. Gradually on this day, it revealed the margins of
the meadow carved out of the north field, the hard, straight edges
delineated by a plow. The clover changed slowly from black to
green. In time, half a dozen dark shapes materialized over 200
yards away, in the gray morning mist, where I knew the meadow
abruptly ends and yields to spent brown goldenrod and standing
yellow hay. But it was still too dark to see any of that.
</P>
<P>
   The shapes were about the right size to be deer. They seemed to
be moving around, but then anything does, if you stare at it long
enough in poor light. Perhaps there was nothing there at all. It
was still impossible to tell. But light is also cumulative, and
soon I found myself blinking and frequently turning my eyes away
from the shapes, in effect clearing my eyes, hoping they would be
fresher and sharper when I looked back. I was hoping but not quite
daring to believe that those shapes, those six little black stick
figures way out there, were indeed whitetails.
</P>
<P>
   One of the figures bolted across the meadow, and I knew for
sure. Not only were they deer down at the end of the field, in fact
one of them was surely a male, or buck _ the only kind hunters are
allowed to kill during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Even with binoculars, it was still too dark, and the buck was
too far away, to make out horns. But it wasn't necessary. The
large-bodied deer had the thick, swollen neck that bucks develop
during the rut, or breeding season. And it was clearly running the
does, at least one of which must have been in estrus and growing
receptive to his clumsy advances. Between dashes, the buck
slouched.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the deer, one considerably smaller than the other,
trotted briskly to the far corner of the meadow. The slouching buck
watched, and then he made another run at the does. He was harassing
the smaller deer, a six-month-old fawn. Its mother grazed,
unconcerned, as did the other three does nearby.
</P>
<P>
   It was both fascinating and pleasant to watch because there
wasn't enough light, and the deer were too far away, for me even to
contemplate that most serious of questions: do I shoot this buck?
</P>
<P>
   Mist rose from frosted goldenrod, a slash of orange light fell
across the stand of beech on the ridge, and from across the valley,
the searing crack of a high-powered rifle rent the stillness. I was
so busy watching the deer that I had almost forgotten it was
opening day.
</P>
<P>
   In the breaking daylight, things began to happen swiftly. The
buck swayed, grunted softly, and charged the fawn again. This time
the fawn darted toward its mother. The big doe switched her tail
and peevishly began to canter directly toward me. She kept coming,
and I kept watching, in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   And then she stopped, just 50 yards from my stand, and lowered
her head to feed. The fawn followed her, and my chest swelled with
a sense of gravity and, perhaps, preordination. I heard the big doe
rip out a mouthful of clover, every color before me grew more
vivid, and now the buck was on the move, lumbering toward the does
in a heavy gallop, his hooves audibly striking the black soil.
</P>
<P>
   As I raised the rifle, the two does detected me and froze. Their
posture alerted the buck, who pulled up short. Through the scope I
saw the sun gleaming on the six tines of the buck's antlers. I shot
another memory, out in the north field, on opening day of another
deer season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
