u a BC-OBIT-FRISON-ROCHE-NYT     12-25 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-FRISON-ROCHE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGER FRISON-ROCHE, 93, MOUNTAINEER AND WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Frison-Roche, a French mountaineer, explorer and popular
writer who carried out the first live radio broadcast from the
summit of Mont Blanc, died on Dec. 17 in Chamonix in the French
Alps. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Frison-Roche's books were widely translated and sold in the
millions. His first mountaineering novel, ``First on the Rope,''
has sold more than 3 million copies since its publication a
half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his novels were set on Mont Blanc, Europe's highest
peak. In addition to ``First on the Rope,'' his books included
``The Big Crevice'' (1952), about a dying guide listening to calls
from members of a search party who cannot hear his cries for help.
He also wrote nonfiction books about his Alpine travels.
</P>
<P>
   Frison-Roche was known, too, for his works set in the North
African desert, like ``The Lost Trail of the Sahara'' (1952), which
was translated into English by Paul Bowles, and ``Lights of the
Arctic'' (1957).
</P>
<P>
   Frison-Roche was born in Paris on Feb. 10, 1906. He left school
early and in 1923 moved to Chamonix, where his parents had lived,
to work in a travel agency and then as a mountain and ski guide. He
later founded a rock-climbing and mountaineering school, and became
known for organizing and winning races to the tops of mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932 he produced the first live radio program from the summit
of Mont Blanc for Radio Lyon. He also wrote for newspapers about
mountaineering, and in 1935 was sent to , Algeria as a
correspondent for La Depeche d'Alger. The assignment, and 17
expeditions into the Sahara, gave him material for his first book,
``The Call of the Hoggar.''
</P>
<P>
   He was then asked to write a series for young people. The
installments became ``First on the Rope.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1942 he was a war correspondent in Tunisia, but the next year
he left to join the Resistance. This experience gave him material
for another novel, ``The Mountain Soldiers of the Night''(1968).
</P>
<P>
   Frison-Roche's wife died in 1994. He is survived by a daughter
who lives in Chamonix.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 2208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9074 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ALGERIANS-MONTREAL-BO     12-25 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALGERIANS-MONTREAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTRAL'S ALGERIAN COMMUNITY RESENTS SUSPICION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In the shadow of a mosque on Rue Jean Talon, shoppers
in spice-scented Arab markets and sippers of highly sugared coffee
in small cafes were feeling the heat, even as a bitter Arctic wind
whipped through their adopted city Saturday. They complained
nervously of unmarked surveillance vans prowling their streets, of
bomb-sniffing dogs, of arrest warrants, police raids and close
questionings.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the talk was rumor or exaggeration, but there's no
masking the real resentment, outrage and even fear racing through
Montreal's Arab community _ especially among ethnic Algerians _
amid an intense international investigation into a suspected
terrorist plot against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel singled out, targeted,'' said Abderrahim Alachaher, a
former schoolteacher from Algeria who now owns a grocery store
called Chez Cordoba. ``Once again, it seems all of us must be
thrown together with a few bad men.''
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood is one of several that are heavily populated by
Algerian nationals in Canada's second-largest city. About 20,000
people from the North African country live in Montreal, and the
vast majority arrived this decade, escaping the civil strife and
economic instability that have gripped their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years I've been in Canada, and I've been hard-working
and built a business for my family,'' said Mourad Nasari, owner of
an electrical repair service. ``Now comes trouble. And I am
frightened Canadians are looking at us with different eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``trouble'' he referred to is on the front page of nearly
every newspaper in North America: On the eve of the millennium,
police in the United States and Canada have mounted a massive
investigation into activities of suspected Algerian Islamic
radicals after the arrests of three people with ties to Algeria in
Vermont and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The two men and one woman in federal custody are from Montreal
and, according to US prosecutors, have links to Algerian radical
groups. Meanwhile, French counterterrorism experts have
investigated whether Montreal is becoming a major center for
Islamic terrorist groups as a floating international population of
Islamic radicals, some suspected of committing crimes in Europe,
exploits Canada's admittedly loose immigration rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Security Intelligence Service warned last year that
the country has become an important sanctuary for scores of
extremely dangerous organizations and their operatives.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Elcock, director of the intelligence agency, stated in
testimony before the Canadian Senate, ``Terrorist groups are
present here whose origins lie in every significant regional,
ethnic and national conflict there is. The nature of our society
and related policies concerning refugees and immigrants make us
particularly vulnerable to terrorist influence and activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, following the arrests of the past two weeks, the attention
of the FBI and Royal Canadian Mounted Police _ together with the
intellegence services of Canada, the United States, France and
other nations _ is focused heavily on Montreal as the point of
connection for suspected plotters.
</P>
<P>
   The first arrest came on Dec. 14, when US Customs officials
apprehended Ahmed Ressam, a 32-year-old Algerian national, as he
arrived in Port Angeles, Washington, aboard a ferry from British
Columbia. In the trunk of his car were nitroglycerine, timing
devices and enough explosive material to flatten a building.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam arrived in Canada in 1994 carrying a false French
passport and soon slipping into Montreal's Algerian underground as
a suspected member of a ring specializing in car break-ins and
computer thefts, authorities allege.
</P>
<P>
   The next arrests came Dec. 19, when Lucia Garofalo, 35, and
Bouabide Chamchi, 20, arrived at a remote border post in Beecher
Falls, Vt. They were taken into federal custody after specially
trained dogs detected trace amounts of explosives in Garofalo's
vehicle. The pair have been charged with fairly minor violations of
immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo's Algerian husband was deported from Canada in 1993.
Authorities say she recently crossed the border to New England
accompanied by two Algerian males. Authorities have said they fear
she may have carried bomb-making materials or terrorist operatives
on that early December trip.
</P>
<P>
   Chamchi, also of Montreal, is an Algerian who entered Canada
illegally in 1997 as a shipboard stowaway.
</P>
<P>
   Cross-border investigators led by the FBI are looking hard at
Montreal's Algerian community, especially at those with links to
the Armed Islamic Group, responsible for massacres and atrocities
in rural Algeria as well as violent crimes in France, which ruled
Algeria until 1962. Canadian police and intelligence officials
allege radical Algerians have formed cells in Montreal to raise
money for fundamentalist Islamic causes through theft, extortion
and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   But many Algerians and other Arabs complain bitterly that they
are being tarred by media and police. ``A whole community is being
stigmatized for the acts of a few,'' said Jerry Khourri, executive
officer of the Canadian Arab Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Until this decade, Montreal's Algerians numbered only a few
hundred, mainly university students. But larger numbers started
pouring into Canada in the 1990s as fighting flared between Islamic
fundamentalists and Algeria's military government.
</P>
<P>
   By and large, according to refugee officials, the newcomers tend
to be well-educated, Western-oriented professionals, skilled
workers afraid of persecution from both sides in their homeland's
struggle. They are attracted by Quebec's French-rooted culture _
not too dissimiliar from the culture of middle-class Algerians _
and Montreal's cosmopolitan ambience.
</P>
<P>
   But police say there are also increasing numbers of Algerian
radicals entering the country to join the loosely organized ranks
of Islamic extremists financing their activities through crime.
They like Canada because the country has welcomed Third World
nationals who claim to be fleeing persecution _ almost all are
granted at least temporary residency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Algerians chose Canada because of its commitment to
democracy and human rights. We live in harmony beside all kinds of
people, and we work very hard to get ahead,'' said Alachaher, the
grocery store owner. ``So to be depicted as dangerous or criminal _
this hurts us, this frightens us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
