<HEADER>
A9115 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     12-25 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 2)  
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NUREYEV: His Life &LR;  By Diane Solway. Morrow, $16. The author
draws on extensive interviews and research to provide fresh
material on the Russian dancer's life and career, particularly his
Soviet years and his defection in 1961. This balanced biography is
``informative and filled with vivid anecdotes,'' Jennifer Dunning
wrote in The New York Times Book Review in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PECULIAR MEMORIES OF THOMAS PENMAN &LR;  By Bruce Robinson.
HarperPerennial, $13. The hero of this darkly funny first novel by
the writer and director of ``Withnail and I'' is a 13-year-old
asthmatic schoolboy searching for identity as he copes with his
exotically dysfunctional family in working-class England in the
grim 1950s. He is an obsessive snooper, and what he's most keen to
find is the key to his grandfather's extensive pornography
collection. ``Never before has the painful, knotty journey to
maturity been depicted with such gusto, and never has the venerable
Bildungsroman received such riotously profane treatment,'' Patrick
McGrath wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SECRECY: The American Experience &LR;  By Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
Yale University, $10.95. In this withering tour of nearly a century
of official secrecy, the New York senator argues that the use of
classified information and misinformation has caused much more harm
than good. ``It is a dismaying tale,'' Sam Tanenhaus wrote in 1998,
though Moynihan tells it ``with uncommon liveliness and a mordant
wit.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; ALL THE LAWS BUT ONE: Civil Liberties in Wartime &LR; , by
William H. Rehnquist (Vintage, $14), the chief justice of the
United States reviews prominent cases in which civil liberties
issues have arisen during times of war, from the 1860s to the
internment of Japanese-Americans in World War II. ``Rehnquist
presents full and fascinating human profiles'' and conveys ``what
it must have been like to grapple with these issues in a time of
crisis,'' Jeremy Waldron wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INGRATITUDE &LR;  By Ying Chen. University of California, $13.95.
This compact novel is narrated from the grave by a woman who
committed suicide to punish her mother and thus escape the
traditional Chinese culture of obedience. The result is ``a
sustained philosophical exploration studded with passionate
outbursts, a glimpse of a consciousness liberated from family and
social expectations,'' Elizabeth Schmidt wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARK BABY &LR;  By Liz Jensen. Overlook, $13.95. This raucous, unruly
novel is a satirical jab at Darwinism and the notion of scientific
certainty through 150 years of British life, up to the early years
of the new millennium, when a fertility crisis threatens the
survival of Homo britannicus. ```Ark Baby' is written in an
exuberantly naughty style that suggests Jensen shares a certain
kinship with writers like Peter Carey and Fay Weldon,'' Alida
Becker wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIP HOP AMERICA &LR;  By Nelson George. Penguin, $13.95. A New York
music critic traces the evolution of rap music and its influence on
culture and society, in the process chronicling his own intense
love-hate relationship with hip-hop. In 1998 the reviewer Laura
Jamison called this ``an invaluable, entertaining and well-written
account.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; ELEVATING THE GAME: Black Men and Basketball &LR;  (University of
Nebraska, $15), George explores the history of basketball and how
the integration of black players from colleges around the United
States advanced the game. The result is a ``folksy yet scholarly
study'' and ``a rich, welcome addition to sports literature,''
Michael E. Ross wrote in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEETINGS WITH THE ARCHANGEL: A Comedy of Spirit &LR;  By Stephen
Mitchell. HarperPerennial, $13. The celestial visitor in question
stops by to deliver a primer on the afterlife and give the novel's
narrator a chance to review his spiritual progress, as well as
provide the author with an opportunity to display his religious
learning. In 1998 the reviewer David Guy called this a
``fascinating and beautifully written'' book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOY OF MAN'S DESIRING &LR;  By Jean Giono. Counterpoint, $16. This
earthy French novel about the loves and toils of a group of
peasants in the rugged, isolated hills of Provence is a pagan
allegory about the fragile communion between man and nature. ``It
is a beautiful story of renewal ... set in terms of a kind of
cosmic faith, and in a lovely and fearless imagery,'' Katherine
Woods wrote in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CANONE INVERSO &LR;  By Paolo Maurensig. Owl/Holt, $12. This Italian
novel, steeped in musical imagery and themes, revolves around a
haunted 17th-century violin and its effect on the friendship of two
boys in Central Europe during the 1930s. Last year the reviewer
Jonathan Keates admired ``the mournful beauty of this sparely
proportioned, soberly recounted story.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GRIEVING TIME: A Year's Account of Recovery From Loss &LR;  By
Anne M. Brooks. Herodias, $11. This slender, heartfelt book is a
monthly journal kept by the author after her husband's death from
cancer. The ``entries are sometimes startling in their candor,''
one critic wrote in 1985. ``It will linger in the mind and give
comfort'' for a long time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
