<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Jan. 2)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Dec. 18 at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. HARRY POTTER AND THE SORCERER'S STONE,
</P>
<P>
   by J.K. Rowling. (Scholastic, $5.99.) A British
</P>
<P>
   boy, neglected by his relatives, finds his fortune
</P>
<P>
   attending a school for witchcraft.
</P>
<P>
   2. THE GREEN MILE, by Stephen King. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A six-part thriller set on death row at Cold Mountain
</P>
<P>
   Penitentiary.
</P>
<P>
   3. SOUTHERN CROSS, by Patricia Cornwell. (Berkley,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) A former police chief is summoned to Richmond,
</P>
<P>
   Va., to clean up scandalous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   4. SEIZE THE NIGHT, by Dean Koontz. (Bantam, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Snow seeks to discover why children in
</P>
<P>
   his hometown keep disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   5. JEWELS OF THE SUN, by Nora Roberts. (Jove, $7.50.)
</P>
<P>
   An American woman, studying folklore in Ireland,
</P>
<P>
   unexpectedly finds romance.
</P>
<P>
   6. VINEGAR HILL, by A. Manette Ansay. (Avon, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman moves with her children and unemployed husband
</P>
<P>
   to live with his loveless family.
</P>
<P>
   7. A MAP OF THE WORLD, by Jane Hamilton. (Anchor,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) When a dairy farmer's wife makes a mistake
</P>
<P>
   one morning, her life falls apart
</P>
<P>
   8. TOM CLANCY'S POWER PLAYS: Shadow Watch, created by
</P>
<P>
   Tom Clancy and Martin Greenberg. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Terrorists target a space station project in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   9. MIRROR IMAGE, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Identical twin sisters experience dissimilar lives
</P>
<P>
   in New York and France early in this century.
</P>
<P>
   10. POKEMON: Nos. 1-5, adapted by Tracey West. (Scholastic,
</P>
<P>
   $4.50 each.) Stories about the characters currently
</P>
<P>
   popular with children.
</P>
<P>
   11. WELCOME TO THE WORLD, BABY GIRL!, by Fannie Flagg.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $7.50.) The pleasures and problems of
</P>
<P>
   a rising star in television news during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   12. INTO THE GARDEN, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Four troubled teen-age girls, subjects of the Wildflowers
</P>
<P>
   series, stage a revealing reunion.
</P>
<P>
   13.(x) POKEMON: Mewtwo Strikes Back and Pikachu's Vacation,
</P>
<P>
   adapted by Tracey West. (Scholastic, $4.99 and $4.50.)
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated adaptations of ``Pokemon'' stories.
</P>
<P>
   14.(x) THE POISONWOOD BIBLE, by Barbara Kingsolver.
</P>
<P>
   (HarperPerennial, $14.) Five female characters narrate
</P>
<P>
   a novel set in the Belgian Congo during that country's
</P>
<P>
   fight for independence.
</P>
<P>
   15.(x) A SUDDEN CHANGE OF HEART, by Barbara Taylor
</P>
<P>
   Bradford. (Dell, $7.99.) When tragedy strikes, a woman
</P>
<P>
   turns to her best friend, an art dealer, for help.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14 and $7.99.) An Irish-American writer recalls his
</P>
<P>
   childhood amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
