<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-GIFTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIFTS CAN CREATE DILEMMA FOR TEACHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By David R. Baker  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- As her students squirmed through the last few
hours before winter break, teacher Gaby Calzadillas examined her
loot.
</P>
<P>
   Random tokens of her students' affection lay heaped on her desk
at Fenton Avenue Charter School in suburban Los Angeles. Body gel.
A wooden picture frame. A Pokemon card. One large bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, how cute--look, it's got `1999' on its paw!'' Calzadillas
said.
</P>
<P>
   The gifts may not always make sense, but the tradition of
showering presents upon teachers during the holiday season remains
strong.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that many of these children come from working-class
families with little cash to spare. Somehow, Calzadillas' children
in Lake View Terrace, 24 miles east of downtown Los Angeles,
managed to bring her something for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may not be the most affluent kids, but they've got big
hearts,'' said Joe Lucente, Fenton's co-director.
</P>
<P>
   That tradition has come under scrutiny this year as the Los
Angeles Unified School District, reeling from administrative
scandals, crafts a new ethics policy for employees. The consultant
charged with writing the new policy said he will likely include
recommendations on accepting gifts from students and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Josephson said there's a possibility some parents may
try to influence teachers through expensive gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like, `Here are some tickets to the Lakers game, and gosh,
Johnny would really like to be on the Academic Decathlon team,'''
said Josephson, founder and president of the Josephson Institute of
Ethics.
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly adds he has never seen such a thing happen here.
And Josephson said he doesn't want to wreck a tradition so many
parents and teachers genuinely love.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to go crazy on this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At many schools, the expensive gifts that concern Josephson are
out of the question. In schools where many children come from poor
families, cookies, cake and tamales are often the gifts of choice.
Cosmetics and candles, too, remain low-cost favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Spomenka Cikara, who teaches English to immigrant children at
Knollwood School in Granada Hills, 21 miles northwest of L.A.'s
downtown, eyed a small collection of presents recently with
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel guilty,'' she said. ``Guilty because I know their
situations at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Other gifts may seem odd at first, until teachers realize the
emotions or thoughts that went into them. Lisa McIntyre at
Knollwood once got an enormous nightgown from a little girl who,
although she didn't know her teacher's size, thought the immense
stretch of pink material was beautiful. She also got a necklace
made of strips of magazine paper meticulously rolled into beads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still wear that sometimes,'' McIntyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Pricey gifts can be far more awkward to receive. Vic Pallos,
spokesman for the Glendale school district, said one local parent
who ran an import business once brought several teachers expensive
purses. The principal returned them to the parent, with apologies.
</P>
<P>
   But turning back a gift isn't easy. In Korean culture, for
example, rejecting a gift is seen as a serious insult, Pallos said.
And 12 percent of Glendale's students come from Korean families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers are in a difficult position here,'' Pallos said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Glendale and Los Angeles school systems already have
policies barring teachers and other employees from accepting gifts
given with an expectation of a favor in return. LAUSD employees
also can not receive more than $100 per year from a single person.
</P>
<P>
   Knollwood teacher Daneh Gallo has seen the full spectrum of
gifts. One year, the parents of her twenty students chipped in to
get her a $100 gift certificate to a mall.
</P>
<P>
   She loved it. But ask her for her favorite gift, and she
remembers something simpler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I got a card I'll keep forever, saying `you've made
a real difference in our family,''' Gallo said. ``That's the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
