<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9175 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r n BC-LASCHOOL-BOARD(2takes     12-25 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASCHOOL-BOARD(2takes)-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL REFORM DERAILED BY HASSLES
</HEADLINE>
 
(Story moves in two takes) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Greg Gittrich  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Exactly three weeks after a slate of
reform-minded candidates took control of the Los Angeles school
board, they gathered at a therapeutic residential treatment center
in Hollywood that serves abused and neglected children.
</P>
<P>
   The July 22 sitdown was billed as a daylong retreat that would
help create a bond among the seven board members, and the location
fit poetically with the reformers' accusations that 710,000
children enrolled in the Los Angeles Unified School District had
been mistreated by the past administration.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by a few key downtown administrators, the motley
participants sat around a table, repeatedly complimented each other
and occasionally scribbled down determined but happy mission
statements for the future of the nation's second-largest school
district.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be a sign of things to come. And it was, but
in an entirely different way than portrayed at the time by the
smiling faces of the part-time politicians and entrenched
bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   Busy with more important matters that sunny summer day, Los
Angeles Unified's top business administrator, David Koch, sent a
stand-in rather than attend.
</P>
<P>
   The district's top lawyer, Richard Mason, at one point wryly
refused to share a personal story with the crowd, saying it was
``attorney-client privilege,'' a blatant reference to complaints
that he had been concealing information from the public.
</P>
<P>
   And shortly before lunchtime, Superintendent Ruben Zacarias
walked into the room and looked around. He was an uninvited guest,
well aware that he faced nearly impossible odds to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, the board booted Koch and Mason, and
Zacarias found himself announcing his early retirement--an ousting
eased by a $750,000 golden handshake.
</P>
<P>
   Since sitting in the retreat circle, the reformers' energies
have been consumed by massive administrative problems, financial
abuses, two scathing audits, and the fate of the district's
albatross, the Belmont Learning Center, which sits partially
completed atop an oil field that seeps potentially deadly and
explosive gases.
</P>
<P>
   By their own admission, it has been a long six months, and
actual instructional and curriculum reforms have taken a back seat
to cleaning up the administrative mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in far worse shape than I imagined,'' said board
member Caprice Young, one of four ``reformers'' elected earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In six months, we've made great progress, but clearly we have
a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Board President Genethia Hayes, the strong-willed leader of the
reform majority, agreed, saying: ``I never envisioned any of this
happening so quickly. It was my hope to reorganize and revitalize
the district completely. But if someone had said that in October we
would have been making those major changes, no, I didn't anticipate
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also didn't anticipate finding a district without anything
that even looked like a functioning management structure where
people were being held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated because he couldn't just to appoint a board to fix
Los Angeles' failing public school system, Mayor Richard Riordan
set out to do the next best thing in the closing months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The millionaire mayor decided to buy the election.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-May, unprecedented contributions from Riordan and an
elite cadre of businessmen he put together figured prominently in
the successful campaigns of three newcomers--Hayes, Young and Mike
Lansing-- and one incumbent, David Tokofsky.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was simple. Together, the four would form a reform
majority on the seven-member Board of Education. They could get
things done if they stuck together.
</P>
<P>
   Only it didn't work out that way.
</P>
<P>
   At the board's first meeting, Hayes, a new president feeling out
her power, appointed board member Valerie Fields as her second in
command. The move surprised many district insiders who were
confident Tokofsky would receive the post, especially after being
denied the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, Fields increasingly aligned with the three
newcomers, as Tokofsky drifted away, assuming his traditional role
as watchdog and devil's advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Those roles were solidified when Tokofsky opposed the foursome's
decision to oust Zacarias in October, citing a lack of public
notice and poor process, two of the board's biggest problems during
the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised by it because David Tokofsky was
always the one on the board who was the watchdog for the public
about all of the things that he perceived were wrong with the
institution,'' Hayes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then to discover it was Valerie Fields who had the strength
and courage through all of this--David's decision still puzzles me.
I would have thought that David would have understood the necessity
of moving when you have the will of the board ready to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   To hear Tokofsky tell it, he made up his mind to bolt the
foursome when he disagreed with Hayes over how to resolve the fate
of Belmont, the nation's costliest high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may share Genethia Hayes' goals,'' Tokofsky said, ``but I
realized we differed strongly on the means to those goals from the
day she wanted to implement that gag order.''
</P>
<P>
   That gag order, which the board would later claim was unofficial
and then concede was unenforceable, was announced July 20.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the board had gone behind closed doors with
the LAUSD administrators to discuss scrapping Belmont. A majority
of the panel had publicly stated they were troubled by the climbing
costs of the unfinished campus and were worried about the safety of
putting kids in a school built on the environmentally troubled
downtown property.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: -- the environmentally troubled downtown property.
</P>
<P>
   The board was ready to kill Belmont and put the scandal behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   That all changed when a LAUSD number cruncher told them it would
be ``cheaper to keep building the school than to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer comfortable with scrapping Belmont, the board voted to
slow down construction, announced a gag order on all matters
relating to the project, and decided to create a citizens
commission to help guide the district to a final decision by
mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   The district has sunk $175 million into the project and internal
estimates show it could cost an additional $112 million to
complete. No decision has been made yet on the future of the
stalled project, and a board vote isn't expected for many more
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a 6-1 vote back in July to kill that project,''
Tokofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have driven a stake through the Belmont beast at the
outset of the new board. Rather, we punted it to some commission
that came back with an ambiguous decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted 4-3 to advise the board to finish Belmont,
but attached a number of conditions to its recommendation. Muddling
the matter further, former District Attorney Ira Reiner, who served
in a nonvoting role as commission executive director, sided with
the opposition. Reiner called Belmont a ``disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the experts were more in unison about whether it can be
made safe,'' Lansing said. ``It's too bad that there is really no
consensus on this issue from the people who are supposed to know
better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, none of us on the board are experts, and we have
to make a final decision on Belmont. The bottom line is we've taken
the right steps to put the project at a place where we have more
information and a decision can be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Board member Victoria Castro, who represents Belmont's
attendance area, is the only vocal advocate for the project on the
school board.
</P>
<P>
   Castro has steadfastly fought to complete the school, arguing a
safety system could prevent methane and hydrogen sulfide gases from
entering the classrooms. She did not respond to requests to be
interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Julie Korenstein, the most ardent Belmont opponent,
said the politics have changed and a final decision has become
increasingly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of pressure being applied by outsiders for this
school to be finished,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of that pressure comes from O'Melveny &AMP; Myers, the
powerful downtown law firm being sued for malpractice by the new
board over its advice on key matters related to Belmont, including
the district's decision to buy the tainted property and hire a
developer without competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   In November, O'Melveny &AMP; Myers hired lobbyists from Cerrell &AMP;
Associates to drum up support on the school board to complete
Belmont. Armed with sound bites from environmental pundits, the law
firm has set out to prove the school can be opened safely and
cost-effectively, which in turn would protect its reputation and
sharply reduce its liability.
</P>
<P>
   The board's bold decision to sue O'Melveny was the first fallout
from a scathing internal audit of Belmont by the district's chief
investigator, Don Mullinax.
</P>
<P>
   The Sept. 14 audit led to the board's decision to remove Koch
and Mason, and contributed to ending Zacarias' career. Eight other
senior employees have been suspended with pay pending disciplinary
hearings. One administrator has quit.
</P>
<P>
   In a second report this month, Mullinax detailed misspending of
millions, sweetheart deals and other financial abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a superintendent who was not willing to accept the new
management structure and need for change,'' Hayes said. ``When you
put a structure in place and you ask a superintendent to make it
work and there is a flat-out refusal from the superintendent, you
have to do what you need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In a flurry of board votes, Hayes, Young, Lansing and Fields
stood together to first strip Zacarias of authority and then force
him into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The chaotic two-week power shift saw real estate attorney Howard
Miller, who had just been brought in as a facilities czar, elevated
to the newly created post of chief operating officer, and
introduced Ramon C. Cortines as the district's interim
superintendent when Zacarias retired in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   It also left many Latino community leaders, who view Zacarias as
an educational deity, cursing the board's lack of public notice and
perceived lack of respect for their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The backlash, which first materialized in several angry
protests, has spun into organized efforts to break up the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only regret is that the Latino community felt so insulted
by our decision to replace the superintendent,'' Hayes said. ``That
wasn't our intention. That is what happened. I regret that and I
will always regret that.''
</P>
<P>
   The administrative coup also severely damaged an already
strained relationship between the reform foursome and the remaining
members. In the heat of the administrative changes, Castro called
for Hayes to resign as president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the schism was momentary and we need to get past it,''
Hayes said. ``I know that I am working very hard and I believe that
Vicky (Castro) is working very hard, as well as everyone else on
the board.''
</P>
<P>
   For student achievement to improve, Tokofsky said, the board
must pull itself together and put aside personality differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to come to an agreement that things will proceed based
upon seven people's input,'' he said. ``Otherwise the collateral
damage caused by not following good process will keep us from our
core mission of improving curriculum, instruction and student
achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly six months after their retreat, board members still are
finding consensus-building elusive, but they do agree on the need
to find a strong and skilled new superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find a superintendent with a vision to change this
district's culture,'' Young said. ``The history of the last 30
years is that turf battles and bureaucracy has taken precedence
over the kids in the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saying that has now stopped--but the bottom line is the
kids still can't read.''
</P>
<P>
   Fully aware that breakup movements are gaining momentum and time
is running short for the LAUSD, board members hope to be able to
replace Cortines with a nontraditional candidate as early as April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hopeful that we can change this institution,'' Hayes said.
``We are going to need the public's help. Now is not the time to
give up on the LAUSD.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why try to break up the district now? For the first time, we
are improving things and have the best opportunity to use the size
of the district for our advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time to join with us, to help us and to keep
hammering away. We have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
