<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9181 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-KWANZA-HOLIDAY-LADN     12-25 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KWANZA-HOLIDAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FESTIVAL FOCUSES ON FAMILY, CULTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jesse Hiestand  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Emphasizing family, community and culture, the
seven-day Kwanzaa celebration that begins Sunday (Dec. 26) leads
African-Americans through a deeply reflective week where family and
philosophy overshadow presents.
</P>
<P>
   The few gifts that grace the traditional Kwanzaa table in
celebrants' homes are highly symbolic: books and heritage symbols
showing appreciation for ancient African culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the heart of our celebration of Kwanzaa is the practice of
pausing and turning inward as persons and a people and thinking
deeply about the wonder and obligation of being African in the
world,'' said Maulana Karenga in his annual message.
</P>
<P>
   Karenga founded the celebration in 1966 as a black studies
professor at California State University, Long Beach. The festival
has grown in popularity and is now celebrated by more than 28
million people around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa ends Jan. 1 with a feast on the Day of Mediation, a
period of self-questioning that ideally should last throughout the
coming year, which according to the ancient Egyptian calendar is
the year 6240, according to Karenga.
</P>
<P>
   Though a relatively new cultural celebration, Kwanzaa draws on
ancient winter agricultural festivals marking the harvesting of
crops and sharing of good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   A modern-day emphasis on the environment preserves that legacy,
with some Kwanzaa observers using the occasion to clean up their
neighborhoods, parks or beaches, said Chimbuko Tembo of Us, the
nonprofit African-American cultural center which Karenga chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time we stop and take particular appreciation for all
the beauty we have around us in terms of creation and other
people,'' Tembo said. ``It's not a religious holiday, so people who
are followers of traditional African religions, Christmas, black
Jews or Muslims can all come together around our African-ness.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa, which means ``first fruits'' in Swahili, honors seven
principles: unity, self-determination, collective work and
responsibility, cooperative economics, purpose, creativity and
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Families mark the occasion with five activities, including
reinforcing their bonds, commemorating the past, recommitting to
cultural ideals and celebrating the good life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody of goodwill can certainly appreciate the aspects of
Kwanzaa,'' Tembo said.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional symbols of Kwanzaa are set up on a table that is
first covered with a straw mat symbolizing the foundations of
African culture.
</P>
<P>
   Fruits and vegetables represent crops and the rewards of
collective labor, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A candleholder symbolizes people who continue to live in Africa
and the seven candles represent the seven principles. Ears of corn
are laid out to symbolize children, and a unity cup honoring
ancestors is used to pour libations. Last, the table contains gifts
of books and heritage symbols.
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa, an African-American cultural celebration that runs from
Dec. 26 through Jan. 1, honors one of the following seven
principles, translated from Swahili, each night, with the lighting
of a candle:
</P>
<P>
   Umoja _ unity
</P>
<P>
   Kujichagulia _ self-determination
</P>
<P>
   Ujima _ collective work and responsibility
</P>
<P>
   Ujamaa _ cooperative economics
</P>
<P>
   Nia _ purpose
</P>
<P>
   Kuumba _ creativity
</P>
<P>
   Imani _ faith
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 2238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991225.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-25 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT     12-25 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS LOSE COOL AND THEN THE GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The Indiana Pacers had enough motivation and
adrenaline Saturday night to push them against a team that stepped
between them and a title in an intense Eastern Conference final
last season without the New York Knicks supplying them with more
venom.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks' Kurt Thomas only served to further rile the
Pacers when he appeared to instigate a skirmish in the third
quarter. What had been a close game was then blown open by the
Pacers, who came together as the Knicks came undone in a 101-90
loss at Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks (17-11) were led by Latrell Sprewell's 23 points,
while the Pacers leaned on 26 from Reggie Miller. Allan Houston,
whose night was weighed down with foul trouble, finished with 10
points. The Knicks were at their greatest disadvantage at the
free-throw line. The Knicks had 25 attempts, making 15; the Pacers
had 40 and made 32.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever these teams meet, there is bound to be some
confrontation. Usually, it is just bodies banging and words flying
in the heat of a tense rivalry. But with 8 minutes 52 seconds left
in the third quarter and the Pacers ahead 54-50, Jalen Rose and
Thomas got tangled up running down the floor and their tempers
boiled over.
</P>
<P>
   After the two collided at midcourt and a whistle blew, replays
showed that Rose approached Thomas, who then threw as many as two
forearms at Rose's head. Rose, who was hit in the face, did not
appear to retaliate but was thrown out of the game, along with
Thomas, for fighting. The league's president of basketball
operations, Rod Thorn, will no doubt review the incident and could
suspend Thomas and Rose.
</P>
<P>
   On a night that began so well for the Knicks, the momentum then
shifted and they became unglued as the third quarter slipped away
from them. Suddenly, the Knicks were without a big body, and the
Pacers were down a top scorer and playmaker. As Rose left the floor
with a look of disbelief, the crowd stood in a roar of support.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of buckling without Rose, the Pacers picked up their
intensity while the Knicks unraveled. With four minutes left in the
third quarter, Larry Johnson picked up a technical for arguing a
call and watched Miller hit the technical foul shot to put the
Pacers ahead, 64-56.
</P>
<P>
   With Houston having a miserable night and Sprewell's quick start
a faint memory, the Pacers took a 73-64 lead entering the fourth
quarter. The Knicks' plan had been disposed of by the Pacers, foul
trouble, the ejection of Thomas and the open shots Miller was able
to get.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell tried to defend Miller, as did Chris Childs, but he was
humming along with 21 points through three quarters. The same
Knicks who had begun the game strong were in need of a strong dose
of poise. They were allowing the Pacers to run free on the
perimeter and connect on 3-pointers and not coming back with a
reply.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Knicks were the calm ones. Coach Jeff Van Gundy's
experiment with a big backcourt launched into its third straight
game with its best start yet. With Houston by his side _ and often
feeding him the ball _ Sprewell took advantage of his matchup with
Mark Jackson and then slipped around Miller, too. But Sprewell's
greatest assist came from the multiple misses by the Pacers, who
began the game 1 for 14. A handful of those misses were turned into
transition baskets by Sprewell, who scored 11 of the Knicks' first
13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Defying the mood of the team on their flight here _ which was
described as quiet by Van Gundy, who noted that no one wanted to
spend Christmas Day ``at the Westin Hotel in Indianapolis'' _ the
Knicks shook whatever holiday homesick blues they had and took a
15-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers seemed almost too pumped up in their revenge-seeking
mode after going down to the Knicks in the conference finals last
season. Once the Pacers settled down, things began to change. With
Houston's foul trouble taking the edge off the big lineup, the
aggressive Pacers began getting to the free-throw line, doubling
Sprewell, putting pressure on the ball and coming up with
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby, who defined his young career with his performance
in last year's conference finals, picked up some of the slack with
a couple of nifty post moves; he finished with 13 points and 15
rebounds. But as the Pacers began working the ball into the post
through Rose and Jackson, the Pacers began to make up ground by the
end of the first quarter and trailed by 28-22.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't Miller who brought the Pacers back in the second
quarter, it was Sam Perkins. He was part of a second unit that
caught the Knicks. Getting lost in transition, the lumbering
Perkins sneaked away from the Knicks and popped a 3-pointer to
bring the Pacers within 30-27 with 9:35 left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks turned to Johnson for a couple of baskets, but soon
became onlookers to a 16-4 run the Pacers used to take a 48-42
lead. The Pacers' first lead, 43-42, came with 3:18 left in the
half, after Patrick Ewing lost a rebound as he hit the floor. Dale
Davis snatched the ball from his hands and snapped a pass to
Miller, who was fouled on a 3-point shot by Johnson. Miller's shot
did not fall but his three free throws did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-25-99 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
