<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT'S COURT TIME COULD BE LIMITED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Travis Knight's season, derailed twice by ankle
problems, started anew Saturday, and now he'll face a tougher
hurdle: finding playing time.
</P>
<P>
   With his 7-foot frame, Knight would seem an asset on a Los
Angeles Lakers team lacking big men. But coach Phil Jackson is
happy with his current rotation and doesn't foresee many minutes
for Knight, who was activated from the injured list prior to tipoff
against the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I'd play him, actually, to be honest with
you,'' Jackson said. ``Right now John (Salley) is doing a decent
job backing up Shaquille (O'Neal) for the six or eight minutes (per
game).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see Shaquille sitting out 12 or 15 minutes a game
unless it's an injury that would sideline him, and then it would be
a matter of concern for us. But we have a pretty good rotation
right now. And we're pleased with the nine-, 10-man rotation that
we're getting on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight's other position is power forward, but Jackson has a nice
one-two punch with A.C. Green and Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least now, I can move and I can give coach some options,''
Knight said. ``Before, I wasn't really an option, but now
hopefully. ...''
</P>
<P>
   He also hopes the sprained right ankle that has dogged him since
the exhibition season is fully healed this time. Knight suffered
the injury Oct. 13 but avoided starting the season on the injured
list. Playing the first month, instead of rehabbing, proved to be a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it felt good when I did come back, and it was my
decision to come back,'' said Knight, who averaged 5.1 minutes in
15 games. ``Sometimes you want to play so bad that you end up
making a mistake, which is unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The ankle ``feels a lot better'' this time, Knight said. ``The
time off (15 days) just gave it a chance to heal, get some of the
scar tissue out, and that helped a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Jackson still feels undermanned at center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have a backup center,'' he said ``I think
everybody (in the front office) thinks that would be important for
us, to have another big body on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Big assist: Derek Fisher had extra incentive to set up his
teammates Saturday _ every assist meant $2,000 for Big Brothers of
Greater Los Angeles. Fisher pledged $1,000 per assist, with a
dollar-for-dollar match from the Lakers Youth Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   A little extra pressure to dish the ball? ``Actually, yes,''
Fisher said before tipoff. ``I'm always looking to make the extra
pass anyway, but tonight will definitely have a much more special
meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Fisher said he planned to make a significant
donation no matter his assist total.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
