</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOSPITALS-NEWYEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS PREPARE FOR ALL THE POSSIBILITIES
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-TIMESSQUARE-SECURE) 
(rk) 
 By   JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Maimonides Medical Center in Brooklyn, the
biohazard suits have been fitted, and the decontamination showers
have found an outdoor home near the emergency room bay. Almost two
dozen doctors, nurses and other hospital staff members have been
through a rigorous two-day training program in protecting
themselves and treating victims of a chemical weapons attack,
should they be wheeled into the emergency room on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Local and federal law enforcement agents stress that they are
not expecting such a terrorist attack, but many of the New York
region's hospitals say they have prepared their emergency rooms for
that possibility. For instance, they have stockpiled antibiotics to
treat victims of an anthrax attack, bought special equipment and
prepared ventilated rooms so that a victim of a chemical attack
cannot contaminate other patients inside.
</P>
<P>
   Many hospitals have quietly been adopting procedures and
equipment to deal with terrorist attacks since the World Trade
Center bombing in 1993. But on the eve of the year 2000, which some
security experts say may be a tempting opportunity for terrorists,
hospitals like Maimonides are enhancing their procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, President Clinton warned Americans to be on guard for
such attacks, after the indictment of an Algerian man who the
federal authorities say tried to enter Washington state from Canada
carrying bomb-making materials.
</P>
<P>
   And Dr. Steven Davidson, the chairman of the department of
emergency medicine at Maimonides, in Borough Park, said:
``Candidly, I think all of us need to recognize that there will be
people who are seeking publicity and acting inappropriately, and
New Year's Eve is the time they might do it. I think it is prudent
to make appropriate provisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential terrorist attacks are among many disasters that local
hospitals have considered for that night. Most have run several
drills that test backup plans should the electricity and telephone
lines fail; backup generators, emergency phones and radio systems
are in place. Hospital officials also say they are ready if there
is a loss of water.
</P>
<P>
   The role of hospitals will be so crucial that night, not because
of the things that can but probably will not happen, but because of
what will most likely come their way, like dozens of cases of
alcohol poisoning. Staff levels will be higher than in memory for
the holiday. Almost all of the local hospitals' chief executives
and administrators will be on hand, hospital press officials said,
and medical staffing will be roughly 10 to 25 percent above normal,
with plenty of others on call.
</P>
<P>
   But chemical warfare and plane crashes or other transportation
calamities are not as high on the list of potential worries as are
computer problems and failures of systems like power or
communications, hospital administrators say. Most New York
hospitals already pride themselves on having busy and sophisticated
emergency rooms that are ready at all times for huge disasters;
their press officials often take pains to brag about the hospitals'
roles in responding to catastrophes. Potential technical foul-ups,
however, are what most operations people in every industry have
focused on in preparation for the year 2000 changeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have clearly planned for a disruption in communications,''
said Susan Waltman, general counsel for the Greater New York
Hospital Association. ``We have satellite telephones, 800-megahertz
radios, and there is a hospital channel in the mayor's office.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Hospital Center has stocked extra intravenous
fluids and other medicines, and has trained doctors from other
parts of the hospital in how to handle a terrorist emergency by
using volunteer victims splayed out on stretchers.
</P>
<P>
   At NYU Downtown Hospital in Lower Manhattan, disposable thermal
blankets for newborns were ordered in the event of a power failure,
and ``Last Shift of the Century'' T-shirts were ordered in the
event of a fashion emergency. ``All of senior management is on duty
and on site that night,'' said Ellen Karasik, the hospital's
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Many hospitals declined to discuss their preparations for a
potential terrorist attack. Ms. Waltman of the hospital association
said, ``One of the rules of emergency preparation is not to talk
publicly on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor's Office of Emergency Management has been working
with hospitals for two years, preparing them for just such an
attack, said Jerome M. Hauer, director of the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have tried to build their infrastructure for
bioterrorism,'' Hauer said, ``but not in any way solely focused on
New Year's Eve.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals have been trained in how to identify symptoms and
illnesses in a biological attack, and in decontamination procedures
in the event of chemical warfare.
</P>
<P>
   But medical staffs would be much more stymied by a biological
attack, in which illnesses are released into the environment in
some covert way, medical and terrorism experts say. Illnesses
resulting from bioterrorism often seem like the flu or some other
disease and are therefore hard to identify and immediately contain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any scenario with biological agents is contingent on forward
or heightened surveillance,'' said Lisandro Irizarry, head of
emergency medicine at the Brooklyn Hospital Center, which has
campuses in Fort Greene and Prospect Park South.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have four or five or six patients who suddenly show up
with pneumonia, that may tip you,'' he said. ``So would early cases
of influenza.''
</P>
<P>
   Many hospital administrators are taking it all in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in a permanent state of heightened readiness
since the World Trade Center bombing,'' said Myrna A. Manners, a
spokeswoman for New York Presbyterian Hospital. ``All of the
essential staff are on alert and prepared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
